\par\par \uc2 U.S.; Politics\par {\*\bkmkstart toc0}{\*\bkmkend toc0}\b \uc2 Supreme Court Nominee Calls Trump\u8217\'20\'19s Attacks on Judiciary \u8216\'20\'18Demoralizing\u8217\'20\'19\b0\par\par\uc2 By JULIE HIRSCHFELD DAVIS \par \uc2 1,183 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 09:24\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 WASHINGTON \u8212\'20\'14 President Trump on Wednesday lashed out at federal judges considering a challenge to his executive order banning travel from seven predominantly Muslim countries, as his Supreme Court nominee called Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s attacks on the independent judiciary \u8220\'20\'1Cdemoralizing\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1Cdisheartening.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump escalated his public feud with the courts over his immigration order, saying that he had found a federal appeals court hearing on his executive order Tuesday night \u8220\'20\'1Cdisgraceful,\u8221\'20\'1D and that the judges had failed to grasp concepts even \u8220\'20\'1Ca bad high school student would understand.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The comments were a remarkable show of disdain by a sitting president for an independent judiciary, and they came at an awkward time for Mr. Trump, just as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/31/us/politics/supreme-court-nominee-trump.html?_r=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 his newly selected nominee}}}\uc2  for the Supreme Court, Judge Neil M. Gorsuch of the federal appeals court in Denver, was meeting with senators on Capitol Hill in the hopes of gaining support for his confirmation.\par \par \uc2 Judge Gorsuch told Senator Richard Blumenthal, Democrat of Connecticut, that he objected to Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s harsh criticism of the courts, including his attack over the weekend on a Seattle district court judge who temporarily blocked his immigration order. In a \uc2 Twitter\uc2  posting on Saturday, the president called Judge James L. Robart, a \u8220\'20\'1C{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/james-robart-judge-trump-ban-seattle.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 so-called judge}}}\uc2 \u8221\'20\'1D whose ruling was \u8220\'20\'1Cridiculous\u8221\'20\'1D and would be overturned.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s invective toward judges is jarring break from a tradition observed by presidents of both parties. Presidents have usually tried to refrain from even appearing to intervene in court cases that concern them or their policies, or from impugning the jurists charged with deciding them, according to judges and legal experts from across the political spectrum.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t ever want to call a court biased, so I won\u8217\'20\'19t call it biased,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump told a gathering of sheriffs and police chiefs on Wednesday in Washington. \u8220\'20\'1CBut courts seem to be so political, and it would be so great for our justice system if they would be able to read a statement and do what\u8217\'20\'19s right.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump, who opened his remarks reciting the passage of the United States code that gives the president the power to restrict immigration whenever he deems the influx of foreigners detrimental to the country, said he had watched \u8220\'20\'1Cin amazement\u8221\'20\'1D Tuesday night as a three-judge federal appeals panel heard arguments on his executive order and the limits of presidential power in cases of national security.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI listened to a bunch of stuff last night on television that was disgraceful,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump said. \u8220\'20\'1CI think it\u8217\'20\'19s sad. I think it\u8217\'20\'19s a sad day. I think our security is at risk today.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis is highly unusual,\u8221\'20\'1D said Michael W. McConnell, a former federal judge who directs the Constitutional Law Center at \uc2 Stanford \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CMr. Trump is shredding longstanding norms of etiquette and interbranch comity.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s partly good manners, but more importantly, the separation of powers works better when the branches aren\u8217\'20\'19t in a spitting match,\u8221\'20\'1D added Mr. McConnell, who was nominated to his judicial post by President George W. Bush.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump appears bent on engaging in just such a confrontation with independent judges who hold the fate of his travel ban in their hands.\par \par \uc2 His comments came the morning after a lively, roughly hourlong hearing \u8212\'20\'14 the audio of which was carried live on national television \u8212\'20\'14 during which three judges on the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit expressed skepticism about the arguments of a Justice Department lawyer defending Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s order.\par \par \uc2 A federal judge in Seattle blocked the travel ban on Friday, and the appeals court is considering whether to uphold that action. The panel said Tuesday that it would rule as soon as possible. Mr. Trump on Wednesday appeared incensed about the challenge, saying, \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s really incredible to me that we have a court case that is going on so long.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 At one point during Tuesday\u8217\'20\'19s arguments, August E. Flentje, the Justice Department lawyer, appeared to acknowledge he was making little headway with the judges, commenting, \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m not sure I\u8217\'20\'19m convincing the court.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump took aim at one of the judges without specifying which one, saying, \u8220\'20\'1CI will not comment on the statements made by, certainly one judge.\u8221\'20\'1D The panel was made up of Judge William C. Canby Jr., appointed by \uc2 Jimmy Carter\uc2 ; Judge Richard R. Clifton, named by George W. Bush; and Michelle T. Friedland, nominated by \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf these judges wanted to, in my opinion, help the court in terms of respect for the court, they\u8217\'20\'19d do what they should be doing,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump said. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s so sad.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 By contrast, he lavished praise on a federal judge in Boston who last week ruled that the travel ban could stay in place. \u8220\'20\'1CRight on \u8212\'20\'14 they were perfect,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump said of that judge\u8217\'20\'19s comments.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s not illegal, it\u8217\'20\'19s not a violation of the law to do these things, but it\u8217\'20\'19s bad policy because it raises questions about the independence of the courts, and it raises questions about the judicial system as a whole when the president says this,\u8221\'20\'1D said \uc2 Peter Wallison\uc2 , who served as White House counsel to President Ronald Reagan.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump defended the process that yielded the executive order, saying he had initially wanted to wait a week or even a month before issuing the travel ban. But the president said he was told by law enforcement officials that doing so would prompt a flood of people, including some with \u8220\'20\'1Cvery evil intentions,\u8221\'20\'1D to rush into the United States before the restrictions took effect.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe do things well; we did things right,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump said. \u8220\'20\'1CI suggested a month, then I said, \u8216\'20\'18Well, what about a week?\u8217\'20\'19 They said no, you can\u8217\'20\'19t do that because then people are going to pour in before the toughness goes on.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 That account appears to be at odds with the one given by several senior officials, who have said they were not fully briefed on the details of Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s order until the day the president signed it at the Pentagon.\par \par \uc2 The president told the law enforcement officers that he was acting solely out of a concern about terrorism, a threat he said had deepened since he took office and gained access to information about the risks facing Americans.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBelieve me, I\u8217\'20\'19ve learned a lot in the last two weeks, and terrorism is a far greater threat than the people of our country understand,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Trump said. \u8220\'20\'1CBut we\u8217\'20\'19re going to take care of it. We\u8217\'20\'19re going to win.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/us/politics/trump-immigration-ban-hearing-appeal.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Appeals Court Panel Appears Skeptical of Trump\u8217\'20\'19s Travel Ban}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/us/politics/donald-trump-centcom.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Trump Says Journalists \u8216\'20\'18Have Their Reasons\u8217\'20\'19 to Play Down Terror Threat}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/us/politics/donald-trump-health-care-law-repeal-replace-plan.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Trump Says Health Law Replacement May Not Be Ready Until Next Year}}}\par \par \uc2 President Trump stepped up his criticism of the United States judicial system a day after his travel ban on people from seven Muslim-majority countries faced close scrutiny from an appeals court. | By REUTERS \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28004jx\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
