\par\par \uc2 us\par {\*\bkmkstart toc5}{\*\bkmkend toc5}\b \uc2 Love, Interrupted: A Travel Ban Separates Couples\b0\par\par\uc2 By JACK HEALY and ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS \par \uc2 1,441 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par \uc2 International New York Times\par \uc2 INHT\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 AURORA, Colo. \u8212\'20\'14 It took 11 days of calling lawyers, beseeching immigration officials and trying to book one-way plane tickets, but on Tuesday, Osman Nasreldin got the love of his life back.\par \par \uc2 His fianc\u233\'00\'E9e, Sahar Fadul, had been detained late last month after arriving at Dulles International Airport from her parents\u8217\'20\'19 home in Sudan and put on a plane back to Africa, the visa it had taken a year for her to acquire stamped \u8220\'20\'1CCANCELLED\u8221\'20\'1D in purple ink.\par \par \uc2 They were reunited on a mild afternoon in Colorado, joining a flood of other travelers taking advantage of the temporary suspension of President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s immigration order restricting the entry of refugees and arrivals from seven largely Muslim countries in the Middle East and Africa. Other couples across the world were still in limbo.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat does it mean if you live in heaven and don\u8217\'20\'19t have the person you love?\u8221\'20\'1D asked Mr. Nasreldin, a Sudanese-born dental hygienist in Aurora.\par \par \uc2 For couples of different nationalities trying to navigate America\u8217\'20\'19s immigration system, the president\u8217\'20\'19s executive order and the legal upheaval it created have thrown relationships and marriages into turmoil.\par \par \uc2 Americans with Syrian and Sudanese partners outside the United States are staying up past midnight to buy one-way plane tickets and plan harried reunions while enforcement of the order is still suspended. Legal challenges aside, couples of mixed Iranian and American backgrounds are rethinking their plans to build lives together in a country where one partner no longer feels welcome. Engagement parties abroad have been scrapped, a wedding dress returned.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Nasreldin and Ms. Fadul were among those racing to reunite, hoping to bind themselves together no matter the outcome of federal court cases challenging the legality of Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s temporary ban.\par \par \uc2 Many of the couples touched by the executive order are accustomed to living apart. They had met online, on business trips or on return visits to countries that one or both had left years ago. What changed, they said, was their certainty they would make it through the immigrant vetting process and one day live together in the United States.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s all up in the air,\u8221\'20\'1D said Guy R. Croteau, a psychotherapist in Boston who met his fianc\u233\'00\'E9, an Iranian, through \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and became engaged after a few whirlwind visits in Istanbul and Malaysia.\par \par \uc2 His fianc\u233\'00\'E9 \u8212\'20\'14 Mr. Croteau publicly refers to him as \u8220\'20\'1CM\u8221\'20\'1D because he is concerned about M\u8217\'20\'19s safety as a gay man living in Iran \u8212\'20\'14 received a K-1 fianc\u233\'00\'E9 visa that is valid until July, one of 30,000 to 40,000 such visas . But the couple are unsure whether the visa will still be valid after the administration\u8217\'20\'19s 90-day immigration hold passes. They are waiting it out apart.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe don\u8217\'20\'19t know,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Croteau said. \u8220\'20\'1CWill there be additional vetting? We don\u8217\'20\'19t know.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, couples are trying to bridge the divide digitally. Olivia Cross chats by video with her husband, Yahya Abedi, an Iranian, as she walks between classes at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Michigan\uc2 . Mr. Abedi has taped photos of the couple\u8217\'20\'19s wedding to the wall of his apartment in Bandar Abbas so Ms. Cross, an American citizen, can see them when she calls.\par \par \uc2 After meeting online, they married last February in Tbilisi, Georgia, and had been threading their way through the visa process when Mr. Trump signed the order. Iran retaliated, saying it would bar American citizens from traveling there. And there went the couple\u8217\'20\'19s plans for a reunion in Iran this May.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI just feel like whatever I do, however I try to pivot, it\u8217\'20\'19s all blocked,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Cross said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe just want to be able to live our life together.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When Michelle Brady chats by video with her husband, a Sudanese-born aid worker recovering in Poland after heart surgery, their 21-month-old son, Jad, recognizes his father\u8217\'20\'19s pixelated face on the screen. When they disconnect, Jad tries to find his father in the computer.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe\u8217\'20\'19s crying and upset that his dad is not there,\u8221\'20\'1D said Ms. Brady, who is now unsure when her husband can join them at their home in the Washington area.\par \par \uc2 Even those who aren\u8217\'20\'19t separated say the order has scrambled their plans for weddings and engagements. Relatives from Iran or Syria aren\u8217\'20\'19t sure whether they will be able to attend summer weddings in the United States. Couples with immigrant parents say they are hesitant about traveling to their familial homelands to celebrate.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Arash Afshinnik, who leads a neurointensive care unit in Fresno, was married three weeks ago in California and planned to fly to Iran with his wife, Sandra Shahinpour, for a second ceremony with her family. He has been in the United States since he was 3 months old, but she spent part of her 20s in Iran and is close to friends and cousins who had wanted to celebrate.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19ve scrapped the plans,\u8221\'20\'1D Dr. Afshinnik, 40, said. His wife returned the dress she had bought for the ceremony. \u8220\'20\'1CWhile everything\u8217\'20\'19s getting sorted out, what hasn\u8217\'20\'19t changed is the uncertainty. Why even dip your toe in the pool? It just seems too hot.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 For much of their 21-month courtship, Jehan Mouhsen and Khaled Almilaji lived apart. She studied medicine in Montenegro. Dr. Almilaji, 35, a Syrian physician well known among humanitarian-aid workers, was in Turkey, saving lives, he said, by supporting doctors in the Syrian conflict zone. He is a romantic who sent Dr. Mouhsen, 26, \u8220\'20\'1Cbuckets of roses\u8221\'20\'1D and surprised her with visits to Montenegro.\par \par \uc2 They married in July, and in August they settled in Rhode Island, where Dr. Almilaji had received a scholarship for a master\u8217\'20\'19s degree in public health at \uc2 Brown \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 , studying on a student visa. He was excited to be sharpening skills to help rebuild his country. She was excited because it seemed their days apart were over.\par \par \uc2 Now Dr. Almilaji is stranded in Gaziantep, Turkey, near the Syrian border, after what was supposed to be a one-week visit to take care of personal and professional affairs. His original return visa was not honored. He went to the American Consulate in Istanbul on Jan. 20 to get a new visa to return, and has not heard back.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Mouhsen fled the loneliness of their apartment in Providence to stay with friends in New York City, where she is studying for her medical board exams and wrestling with morning sickness. She is pregnant.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe tells me to eat fruits and vegetables, take care of me and the baby,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Although Dr. Mouhsen has Montenegrin roots, they both grew up in Aleppo, Syria, and plan to return someday. In 2013, Dr. Almilaji\u8217\'20\'19s early detection system found that polio was making a comeback in war-ravaged Syria, and he coordinated a campaign the next year that vaccinated more than a million Syrian children. Though his work was supported by powerful organizations like the \uc2 United States Agency for International Development\uc2 , \uc2 Unicef\uc2 , the \uc2 World Health Organization\uc2  and the \uc2 Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation\uc2 , there is little they can do to help him now.\par \par \uc2 Early in the civil war, Dr. Almilaji was arrested, tortured and jailed for six months by the regime. But he says he feels even more powerless now that his wife is suffering from an abrupt separation caused by the action of the United States government.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19ve been arrested, and I\u8217\'20\'19ve been tortured and everything,\u8221\'20\'1D he said in a phone conversation from Turkey. \u8220\'20\'1CBut my wife, she doesn\u8217\'20\'19t have to suffer this.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Jack Healy reported from Aurora, and Anemona Hartocollis from New York.\par \par \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-articleLarge.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-jumbo.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-superJumbo.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-moth.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-articleInline.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-sfSpan.jpg\uc2  | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/05STARCROSSED/05STARCROSSED-filmstrip.jpg\uc2  | Jehan Mouhsen during a video chat with her husband, Khaled Almilaji, who was stranded in Turkey. | Damon Winter/The New York Times | \uc2 https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/02/05/us/00STARCROSSED3/00STARCROSSED3-articleLarge.