\par\par \uc2 Fashion & Style\par {\*\bkmkstart toc7}{\*\bkmkend toc7}\b \uc2 A Designer, and a Collection, Inspired by an Immigrant Father\b0\par\par\uc2 By VALERIYA SAFRONOVA \par \uc2 1,536 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 15:07\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 For those who want their fashion designers to be both creative and political, Kerby Jean-Raymond is a case study.\par \par \uc2 The designer, who turned 30 last year, and founded his label in 2013, first made waves with his spring 2016 show, which featured a short film about race relations in the United States. Since then, he has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/22/fashion/after-a-tragedy-like-the-charlie-hebdo-shooting-come-the-products.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 designed T-shirts}}}\uc2  that listed the names of victims of police brutality; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/18/fashion/erykah-badu-debut-new-york-fashion-week.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 traveled to North Dakota}}}\uc2  with supplies for the Dakota Access Pipeline protesters; and created a collection that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/13/fashion/new-york-fashion-week-hood-by-air-altuzarra.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 explored the theme of economic inequality}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This season, Mr. Jean-Raymond drew inspiration from his father, Jean-Claude Jean-Raymond, 59, who arrived in New York from Haiti in 1980 and who raised Kerby alone after his wife, Vania Moss-Pierre (Pyer Moss is her namesake), died when his son was seven. The collection is titled \u8220\'20\'1CMy Father as I Remember, 1980-1999,\u8221\'20\'1D and is the first part of a multiseason series called \u8220\'20\'1CStories About My Parents.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It is also a timely reminder of the importance of the melting pot in the current conversation around immigration.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CMy dad was always so strict that I was scared to speak to him,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Jean-Raymond said recently, driving through East Flatbush, Brooklyn, where he grew up. \u8220\'20\'1CHaitian parents are very, \u8216\'20\'18This is adults\u8217\'20\'19 business; this is kids\u8217\'20\'19 business.\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 At the apartment where his father has lived since 1982, Mr. Jean-Raymond scrolled through his phone as Jean-Claude Jean-Raymond looked on. \u8220\'20\'1CHe randomly sent me these pictures on WhatsApp a few months ago and I started designing my collection around them,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Jean-Raymond said, scrolling through the messaging app. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s an ode to the cars that he drove, the excessive amount of jewelry he wore.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI grew up thinking my father was tacky,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Jean-Raymond said. \u8220\'20\'1CThere was no color coordination. It was whatever was cool. \u8216\'20\'18These sweatpants are cool. I\u8217\'20\'19ll wear them with these shoes that are cool.\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D Only recently did Kerby begin to truly admire his father\u8217\'20\'19s style. \u8220\'20\'1CHe had less inhibitions,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CI wasn\u8217\'20\'19t respectful of his swag then.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When Jean-Claude Jean-Raymond would take Kerby and his stepbrother to a store called Dr. Jay\u8217\'20\'19s to buy new clothes for school, Kerby always ran to the back. \u8220\'20\'1CMy stepbrother would head for Phat Farm, FUBU, those sections, and I would look for anything that was made in Italy,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CThere wasn\u8217\'20\'19t much to pick from. That kind of stuff they kept behind the counter.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI grew up in a different Flatbush,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Jean-Raymond added. \u8220\'20\'1CWhen we went outside for recess there would be drug dealers in the yard. We used to take milk crates and hang them on the fence to play basketball.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 His father said, \u8220\'20\'1CThere was an area nearby called Vietnam,\u8221\'20\'1D referring to a stretch of several blocks near Flatbush Avenue. \u8220\'20\'1CDay or night, you couldn\u8217\'20\'19t walk in this area. It was too dangerous. But the same area now, there\u8217\'20\'19s a \uc2 Starbucks\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI never sold drugs,\u8221\'20\'1D Kerby Jean-Raymond said. \u8220\'20\'1CThere were times when gangs would approach me, but my father was way stronger than them. They would come make threats and stuff, and I was like: \u8216\'20\'18You don\u8217\'20\'19t know the opposition I\u8217\'20\'19ve got upstairs. I\u8217\'20\'19m not scared of you.\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He did, however, have a lifelong obsession with sneakers, financed starting when he was 13 by an after-school job at a sneaker store on Flatbush Avenue called Ragga Muffin (he told the hiring manager that he was 15). \u8220\'20\'1CThe way I was raised, you get a new pair of sneakers when the old one gets messed up,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Jean-Raymond said. \u8220\'20\'1CBut when I got to high school, I started dating girls and trying to fit in, and I realized everybody was collecting Jordans. When I would get my paychecks, I wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t even take money. I would just trade them for sneakers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s completely different,\u8221\'20\'1D he said of today\u8217\'20\'19s Ragga Muffin. Still, he credited the place with inspiring his career path. Seeing the less-than-high-quality pieces that sold while he worked there, he thought to himself: \u8220\'20\'1CI can make something better.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Jean-Raymond had always been an impatient, antsy child, and to channel his energy, his homeroom teacher at the High School of Fashion Industries in Manhattan had him work as an intern with the designer Kay Unger, who became a mentor.\par \par \uc2 Though he attended \uc2 Hofstra \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  and earned a degree in business law and entrepreneurship, he continued to freelance for \uc2 Marc Jacobs\uc2 , Theory, Kenneth Cole and others, helping with showroom preparation, draping and pattern making. Then came Pyer Moss, now based in Manhattan\u8217\'20\'19s garment district.\par \par \uc2 Back at the office, Mr. Jean-Raymond went over several pieces-in-progress with his team. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m taking classic cuts, but I\u8217\'20\'19m doing them in textures that remind me of him,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, referring to his father. A bright silver, furry jacket lay on a table. Nearby was a sleek tracksuit in black and purple, and a large leather jacket purposely left unfinished. Also part of the collection: a hand-drawn patch featuring an image of his father in his youth with his nickname, \u8220\'20\'1CDidi,\u8221\'20\'1D printed below.\par \par \uc2 He picked up a dark burgundy and black coat, inspired by a Maison Margiela style his father wore when Mr. Jean-Raymond was a child, and put it on. Maison Magiela and Yohji Yamamoto are the only two labels Mr. Jean-Raymond now wears besides his own.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt was the first time I saw the word Margiela,\u8221\'20\'1D he said of the original piece. \u8220\'20\'1CI could tell you exactly what he would wear it with. A cream suit and a Van Heusen shirt and brown corduroy pants.\u8221\'20\'1D He did not love the look, back in the day. \u8220\'20\'1CNow, I think that\u8217\'20\'19s fly.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 After wrapping up at his studio, Mr. Jean-Raymond headed to Le Soleil Restaurant on 10th Avenue for lunch.\par \par \uc2 The Haitian restaurant is owned by his uncle, Alphonse Duval, and his aunt, Rolande Bissereth, who is also Mr. Jean-Raymond\u8217\'20\'19s godmother. What his father did not provide in emotional connection she provided in spades, he said. He spent weekends with her at her home in Queens and at the restaurant, working behind the counter, cleaning up and serving food. \u8220\'20\'1CIf she was here now, I wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t be sitting,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Jean-Raymond ordered a selection of Haitian dishes: plantains, fried goat with onions, conch, rice and beans, deep-fried accra (a root vegetable) and a side of spicy chili sauce. One of his future collections in the \u8220\'20\'1CStories About My Parents\u8221\'20\'1D series will be about his godmother and his mother.\par \par \uc2 For now, Mr. Jean-Raymond is still focused on unraveling the complex relationship he has with his father. \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19ve never had an open line of communication,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CI hope this shows him that I\u8217\'20\'19ve cared the whole time. I just didn\u8217\'20\'19t say anything.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Continue following our fashion and lifestyle coverage on \uc2 Facebook{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/nytimesstyles"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 (Styles}}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/modernlove"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Modern Love}}}\uc2 ), \uc2 Twitter\uc2  ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/nytstyles"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Styles}}}\uc2 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/nytfashion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Fashion}}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/nytimesvows"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Weddings}}}\uc2 ) and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://instagram.com/nytimesfashion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Instagram}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This season, Kerby Jean-Raymond drew inspiration from his father, who arrived in New York from Haiti in 1980, and who raised Kerby alone after his mother died. | Sasha Arutyunova for The New York Times | \u8220\'20\'1CMy dad was always so strict that I was scared to speak to him,\u8221\'