\par\par \uc2 Fiction & Nonfiction\par \uc2 Books; Book Review\par {\*\bkmkstart toc8}{\*\bkmkend toc8}\b \uc2 Drawn Into the Middle East: A Novel, a Memoir and an Account of Life in the Region\b0\par\par\uc2 By JANINE DI GIOVANNI \par \uc2 1,431 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 13:23\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 THE ATTACK\par \par \uc2 Written by Lo\u239\'00\'EFc Dauvillier\par \par \uc2 Illustrated by Glen Chapron\par \par \uc2 Adapted from the novel by Yasmina Kadra\par \par \uc2 152 pp. Firefly Books. $24.95.\par \par \uc2 THE ARAB OF THE FUTURE 2\par \par \uc2 A Graphic Memoir: A Childhood in the Middle East (1984-1985)\par \par \uc2 By Riad Sattouf\par \par \uc2 Translated by Sam Taylor\par \par \uc2 154 pp. Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt & Company. Paper, $26.\par \par \uc2 ROLLING BLACKOUTS\par \par \uc2 Dispatches From Turkey, Syria, and Iraq\par \par \uc2 By Sarah Glidden\par \par \uc2 298 pp. Drawn & Quarterly. $24.95.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf I locked you up, it was so you could taste hate,\u8221\'20\'1D Dr. Amin Jaafari\u8217\'20\'19s captor says in the extraordinary graphic novel version of Yasmina Kadra\u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1CThe Attack.\u8221\'20\'1D \u8220\'20\'1CAnything can happen if you scratch at someone\u8217\'20\'19s self-esteem. Especially if they are feeling powerless.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 This is not just a simplified explanation of the complex motivations of a suicide bomber. These words, in a sense, exemplify the brutal cycle of the Middle East tragedy: Injustice leads to powerlessness, to frustration to rage, and finally to acts of violence that undercut any attempts at peace or reconciliation.\par \par \uc2 Except this time, Dr. Amin \u8212\'20\'14 an Israeli Arab surgeon whose wife, Sihem, mysteriously disappears down the rabbit hole of radical extremism and violence \u8212\'20\'14 is being held in a darkened room by Palestinian radicals in the West Bank city of Jenin, not by the \uc2 Shin Bet\uc2 , the \uc2 Israeli Security Agency\uc2 . He has embarked on a quest across the Occupied Territories to try to unravel how and why his wife blew herself up along with innocent bystanders on a crowded Tel Aviv street. His voyage into the abyss starts in the emergency room at the hospital where he works, desperately trying to save victims of a suicide bomber, before discovering through Israeli friends that it was his wife who in fact murdered and harmed all these people.\par \par \uc2 The genius of \u8220\'20\'1CThe Attack\u8221\'20\'1D is that while you are led, Odysseus-like, through the back streets and alleys of Bethlehem and Jenin, meeting radicals and thugs, families who have turned violent out of deep resentment and frustration, people whose homes are bulldozed by Israeli soldiers, you are following Amin\u8217\'20\'19s inner journey in real time. You are also descending into the rabbit hole.\par \par \uc2 What incident prompted Sihem to turn from a wife, beautiful and bright, into a killer? How did Amin lose his own Arab identity by closing himself off to the tragedy of those living in Gaza and Jenin while he pursued a secular, noninvasive life, safely cocooned in his hospital? Or, as one of the radicals tells him, \u8220\'20\'1CNow .\u8200\'20\'08.\u8200\'20\'08. you have experienced a bit of the horrors that your job has protected you from.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 There is no grand finale, no morality play, no lessons learned on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict in these pages. There is, in fact, no judgment of who is wrong and who is right. There is just the deep sense of loss, horror, bereavement and finally, shock.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI have no intention of .\u8200\'20\'08.\u8200\'20\'08. taking down the group,\u8221\'20\'1D Amin says to his best friend, Kim, a Jewish surgeon, of his quest to find out who indoctrinated Sihem. \u8220\'20\'1CI just want to know how the love of my life excluded me from hers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe Attack\u8221\'20\'1D is not even the story of how radicals take up arms, or why Sihem strapped on that explosive vest \u8212\'20\'14 was it out of love for another man, or was it her own true calling? \u8220\'20\'1CThe Attack,\u8221\'20\'1D ultimately, is a story of lost innocence.\par \par \uc2 On one of his endless wanderings, this time through an olive grove near Bethlehem, Amin meets an old Jewish man, a friend of his father\u8217\'20\'19s. \u8220\'20\'1CAll Palestinian Jews are a bit Arab and Israeli Arabs cannot deny being a little bit Jewish,\u8221\'20\'1D he muses. The old man agrees with him, but asks: \u8220\'20\'1CSo why is there so much hate in the same lineage?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Riad Sattouf, a former contributor to the French satirical magazine \uc2 Charlie Hebdo\uc2 , which sustained a terrorist attack in 2015 leaving 12 people dead, wrote \u8220\'20\'1CThe Arab of the Future\u8221\'20\'1D first in French in 2014. The story, of a half-Syrian, half-French kid growing up in Libya in the strange, dark days of Qaddafi\u8217\'20\'19s rule from 1978 to 1984, was an instant success in France. He has come back with Part 2, which picks up in 1984.\par \par \uc2 By now, the Sattouf family has returned to Ter Maaleh, Syria, the paternal village in the Homs countryside. The father, Abdel-Razak, an unappetizing bully from Page 1, teaches at a local \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He bemoans his lack of stature and money, and the fact that his sleazier relatives closer to the Assad regime have better sunglasses, houses and cars. He fantasizes about the vast garish villa he will soon build, but never does.\par \par \uc2 The mother, Cl\u233\'00\'E9mentine, a depressed Frenchwoman in exile, yearns for saucisson in a Muslim culture that bans pork. She tries to span the cultural gap, cooking pots of lentils over a portable stove, weaving a tapestry that she never completes and yearning for a washing machine or a generator.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAre you crazy?\u8221\'20\'1D her husband screeches. \u8220\'20\'1CIt is forbidden! If someone reported us, I could go to prison!\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CYou\u8217\'20\'19re just saying that because it\u8217\'20\'19s expensive,\u8221\'20\'1D she retorts.\par \par \uc2 In between are their baffled children \u8212\'20\'14 6-year-old Riad and his tiny brother, nicknamed Yahya. Riad has trouble sleeping. He tries to play with his Legos from France, but the children\u8217\'20\'19s games he plays with his cousins always involve killing Jews. The cultural shift from his previous life in France, or even the oddity of Libya, is a divide he finds too hard to traverse. Why are the teachers so brutal, beating children with sticks while teaching them patriotic songs? Why are they taught never to criticize Hafez Assad or his family? And why are people so afraid?\par \par \uc2 The teacher is intrigued by his blond hair. \u8220\'20\'1CTell me, what is your religion?\u8221\'20\'1D she asks him. \u8220\'20\'1CAre both your parents Syrian?\u8221\'20\'1D The question, of course, is does he have any Jewish blood.\par \par \uc2 This volume of Sattouf\u8217\'20\'19s graphic memoir is more than just a coming-of-age story. It is a window into life under the Assads in a time of the Hama massacre, where thousands of Sunni men were butchered. It ends with a village tragedy, but one that could be a metaphor for the tragedy of Syria.\par \par \uc2 Less poignant but impressive in its own na\u239\'00\'EFve way is \u8220\'20\'1CRolling Blackouts: Dispatches From Turkey, Syria, and Iraq,\u8221\'20\'1D by Sarah Glidden.\par \par \uc2 Glidden is a West Coast cartoonist who teams up with a gang of independent reporters to traverse the war-torn Middle East. Ethics aside \u8212\'20\'14 is this war tourism? \u8212\'20\'14 there is something heady about Glidden\u8217\'20\'19s learning curve.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s so weird for me to come to places where you just can\u8217\'20\'19t talk about certain things,\u8221\'20\'1D one of her friends muses. \u8220\'20\'1CBecause people just spout their mouths off left and right in America about any damned thing they want to.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Her two-month voyage is a Middle East 101, a kind of \u8220\'20\'1CLet\u8217\'20\'19s Go: Middle East for Millennials.\u8221\'20\'1D It\u8217\'20\'19s a child\u8217\'20\'19s vision, a comic book about statistics and data of refugees in Turkey; the Kurdish question; the lingering damage of the Iraq invasion told through the eyes of her fellow traveler, a former Marine called Dan who has obvious but vital observations like: \u8220\'20\'1CWhat would be best for our foreign policy would be if we moved away from all the military stuff and started programs that would help these people.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s hard not to utter to oneself, \u8220\'20\'1CDuh,\u8221\'20\'1D as Glidden gradually takes on the multilayered complexities of the Middle East. But there is something fresh in her narrative. In the midst of her cultural wanderings \u8212\'20\'14 the endless cups of heavily sugared tea and the bewilderment she constantly feels \u8212\'20\'14 Glidden pieces together something that newspaper reporters often miss while trying so hard to analyze. By talking to people and living their lives, she unearths very real people and their real stories.\par \par \uc2 Janine di Giovanni\uc2  is the Middle East editor of Newsweek and the author, most recently, of \u8220\'20\'1CThe Morning They Came for Us: Dispatches From Syria.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Amin grieves after Israeli soldiers destroy a village elder\u8217\'20\'19s house in retaliation for a suicide bombing. | From \u8220\'20\'1CThe Attack,\u8221\'20\'1D written by Lo\u239\'00\'EFc Dauvillier and illustrated by Glen Chapron | From \u8220\'20\'1CThe Att