\par\par \uc2 Times Insider\par {\*\bkmkstart toc12}{\*\bkmkend toc12}\b \uc2 A Good Meal is Hard to Find \u8212\'20\'14 at least on New York\u8217\'20\'19s Upper West Side\b0\par\par\uc2 By PETE WELLS \par \uc2 749 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 08:54\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 I\u8217\'20\'19ve been wondering when the Upper West Side was going to complain about me. Until my {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/dining/white-gold-butchers-review-april-bloomfield-restaurant.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 review of White Gold}}}\uc2  this week, I\u8217\'20\'19d never, in my five years as The Times\u8217\'20\'19s restaurant critic, written a full, starred review of any restaurant north of Lincoln Center but south of \uc2 Columbia \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (I don\u8217\'20\'19t count {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/t/tavern_on_the_green/index.html?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Tavern on the Green}}}\uc2 , even though the driveway is on the Upper West Side.)\par \par \uc2 Honest, I\u8217\'20\'19ve tried. Anytime I hear about a new restaurant on Amsterdam or Columbus that sounds out of the ordinary, I check it out. And it\u8217\'20\'19s not that the restaurants have been bad. In fact, truly disastrous scouting trips have sometimes led to reviews, since a restaurant that\u8217\'20\'19s gone off the rails can make interesting reading. Nothing on the Upper West Side has been like that. In general, the meals I\u8217\'20\'19ve had have fallen into the category that \uc2 Gael Greene\uc2  once described, if I remember correctly, as \u8220\'20\'1Cneither good enough nor bad enough to write about.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sometimes you hear the neighborhood called a \u8220\'20\'1Crestaurant wasteland.\u8221\'20\'1D Usually that comes from people who live there, but it\u8217\'20\'19s not true. There are loads of restaurants on the Upper West Side. The trouble is that, in my experience, they are \u8230\'20\'26 just good enough. Most of them seem content to be the place you go when you\u8217\'20\'19re too busy or tired to cook. Not very many aspire to be the place where you try to impress your friends, or yourself.\par \par \uc2 This is one way to think about the divide between neighborhood restaurants and destination restaurants. I don\u8217\'20\'19t like those terms \u8212\'20\'14 destination in particular is too ambiguous to be useful. People tend to use it to mean a place that takes itself seriously, but a destination restaurant could also be a modest little spot that serves a cuisine you can\u8217\'20\'19t find in every neighborhood.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/01/nyregion/cafe-mingala-offers-a-rare-and-constant-taste-of-myanmar.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Caf\u233\'00\'E9 Mingala}}}\uc2 , a Burmese restaurant on the Upper East Side, was this kind of destination before it closed last year. Every neighborhood has its pad Thai and egg rolls and pizza, but Burmese tea leaf salad is a rare thing, and, in my book, made Mingala worth traveling for. Another destination along those lines, although it could be a bit hit-or-miss, was Gazala\u8217\'20\'19s Place, which used to serve some Druse specialties across from the Museum of Natural History.\par \par \uc2 If restaurants that go out of their way to impress are rare on the Upper West Side, it\u8217\'20\'19s not the fault of the people who live there. I\u8217\'20\'19m not sure whose fault it is, but we might start with the restaurant owners who choose to stay away from the mean streets of the west 70s and 80s. Ken Friedman and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/april_bloomfield/index.html?inline=nyt-per"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 April Bloomfield}}}\uc2 , who opened White Gold, are among the few restaurateurs who succeeded downtown before coming to the Upper West Side.\par \par \uc2 Crucially for my purposes, they did this with an original idea (a restaurant inside a butcher shop) rather than a clone of one of their existing restaurants like The Spotted Pig or The Breslin. I tend not to review second or third locations. This is why I never wrote about {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/25/dining/reviews/parm-restaurant-review-nyc.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Parm}}}\uc2  or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/07/dining/reviews/redfarm-in-the-west-village-turns-up-the-flavors.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 RedFarm}}}\uc2  in the west 70s; I\u8217\'20\'19d already had my say about the downtown originals.\par \par \uc2 There are larger historical forces at work here. Back when Mimi Sheraton and Bryan Miller held my job, they would often find themselves at addresses on the Upper East or Upper West Sides, not to mention Midtown, to review significant and groundbreaking new restaurants. But for at least two decades, maybe longer, the center of gravity of the Manhattan dining scene has been heading south. Places with high ambitions or novel ideas now tend to open below 23rd Street \u8212\'20\'14 or across the East River.\par \par \uc2 I can\u8217\'20\'19t entirely explain why this has happened, but at this point the pattern is undeniable. There\u8217\'20\'19s one great exception, though. The Harlem dining scene has flourished lately. Maybe the tide is turning, and risk-taking restaurateurs will start to look uptown again. For the sake of my friends on the Upper West Side, I hope so. But if I lived there, I wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t sit around at home waiting, because it could take a long time.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/dining/white-gold-butchers-review-april-bloomfield-restaurant.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 White Gold Butchers Slices to the Point: Meats Cooked Simply}}}\par \par \uc2 Liz Barclay for The New York Times \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed2800461\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
