\par\par \uc2 U.S.; Politics\par {\*\bkmkstart toc13}{\*\bkmkend toc13}\b \uc2 ISIS Detainees May Be Held at Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo, Document Shows\b0\par\par\uc2 By CHARLIE SAVAGE \par \uc2 1,084 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 08:46\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 WASHINGTON \u8212\'20\'14 The Trump White House is nearing completion of an order that would direct the Pentagon to bring future Islamic State detainees to the Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo Bay prison, despite warnings from national security officials and legal scholars that doing so risks undermining the effort to combat the group, according to administration officials and a draft executive order obtained by The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 White House officials have spelled out their thinking about a new detainee policy in an evolving series of drafts of an executive order being circulated among national security officials for comment. While previous versions have shown that the draft has undergone many changes \u8211\'20\'13 including {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/politics/black-site-prisons-cia-terrorist.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 dropping language about reviving C.I.A. prisons}}}\uc2  \u8211\'20\'13 the plan to add Islamic State detainees to the Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo population has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/us/politics/cia-detainee-prisons.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 remained constant}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3455640-Revised-draft-Trump-EO-on-detainees-and-Gitmo.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 latest version of the draft}}}\uc2 , which circulated this week, would direct Defense Secretary \uc2 Jim Mattis\uc2  to use Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo to detain suspected members of \u8220\'20\'1CAl Qaeda, the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 , and associated forces, including individuals and networks associated with the Islamic State.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The White House has kept similar language in the draft order despite warnings from career government national security officials that carrying out its plan would give federal judges an opportunity to reject the executive branch\u8217\'20\'19s theory that the war against the Islamic State is legal, even though Congress never explicitly authorized it. The issue could arise when reviewing an inevitable habeas corpus lawsuit filed by an ISIS detainee.\par \par \uc2 The Obama administration first argued in late summer 2014 that the Islamic State was part of the existing armed conflict that Congress authorized in 2001 against Al Qaeda and the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 . But while the Islamic State got its start as Al Qaeda\u8217\'20\'19s affiliate in Iraq a decade ago, that theory is disputed because the two groups later split and went to war with each other.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt raises huge legal risks,\u8221\'20\'1D said Jack Goldsmith, a Harvard Law School professor and former senior Justice Department official in the Bush administration. \u8220\'20\'1CIf a judge says the Sept. 11 authorization does not cover such a detention, it would not only make that detention unlawful, it would weaken the legal basis for the entire war against the Islamic State.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sean Spicer\uc2 , the White House press secretary, did not respond to an email seeking comment on the issue.\par \par \uc2 The Times {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/politics/black-site-prisons-cia-terrorist.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 reported on Feb. 4}}}\uc2  that the White House had limited the draft order so that it focused on carrying out President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s vow to keep the Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo prison open and use it for newly captured detainees. That draft of the order dropped the ideas of reopening C.I.A. prisons and permitting interrogators to use harsher techniques than those now allowed in the Army Field Manual.\par \par \uc2 That report was based on accounts by people familiar with a version that circulated last week. But a new draft order circulated this week, titled \u8220\'20\'1CProtecting America Through Lawful Detention of Terrorist and Other Designated Enemy Elements,\u8221\'20\'1D includes some revisions. The latest version, unlike the previous one, explicitly revokes President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s January 2009 executive order directing the government to close the prison by January 2010, a deadline it failed to meet.\par \par \uc2 The revised text also dropped references to revitalizing the use of the military commissions system at Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo for prosecuting terrorism suspects, and instead focused exclusively on detention policy \u8212\'20\'14 like its directive to use the prison to detain captured Islamic State suspects without trial.\par \par \uc2 In the 2012 version of the annual National Defense Authorization Act, Congress {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/15/us/politics/obama-wont-veto-military-authorization-bill.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 bolstered the government\u8217\'20\'19s power}}}\uc2  to imprison suspected members of Al Qaeda, the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  and associated forces by authorizing such detentions without reference to the Sept. 11 attacks. But while it has provided funds for military operations against the Islamic State, it has never explicitly authorized combat or detention operations against it.\par \par \uc2 In summer 2014, when the group swept out of Syria and began rapidly conquering swaths of Iraq, Mr. Obama launched a bombing campaign to curtail its advances. At the time, he put forth the theory that the group\u8217\'20\'19s early ties to Al Qaeda were sufficient to bring it under the Sept. 11 war authorization without new action from Congress.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, in 2015, the Obama administration asked Congress to enact an authorization for use of military force against the Islamic State. Lawmakers disagreed about whether it should place limits on the use of ground forces or impose an expiration date, and Congress never acted on the proposal. Congress has continued to give no sign that it has the will or the consensus to explicitly authorize war on the Islamic State.\par \par \uc2 Last year, an army captain {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/05/us/islamic-state-war-powers-lawsuit-obama.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 sued Mr. Obama}}}\uc2 , arguing that the war was illegal because Congress had not authorized it. A Federal District Court judge {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/politics/judge-lawsuit-war-isis.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 dismissed the lawsuit }}}\uc2 without ruling on the legal merits, saying the plaintiff lacked standing to bring the case.\par \par \uc2 But any Islamic State detainee at Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo would have legal standing to get a court to rule on the question of whether the group State is legitimately part of the war against Al Qaeda.\par \par \uc2 Ryan Goodman, a New York \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  law professor who worked at the Pentagon during the Obama administration, said were other reasons bringing an Islamic State detainee to Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo for indefinite detention, as opposed to prosecuting him in civilian court, might raise problems: Foreign allies, he said, might refuse to turn over prisoners or assist in detention operations if that was the administration\u8217\'20\'19s goal.\par \par \uc2 But even if that turns out not to be the case, he said, the legal risks of bringing a suspected member of the Islamic State, sometimes referred to as ISIL, are \u8220\'20\'1Cvery serious.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf I were in the administration, I would advise that bringing ISIL fighters to Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo raises too many legal risks,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CIf a court finds the 2001 statute does not apply to ISIL because of the extraordinarily remote links between ISIL and the original Al Qaeda, then it would put into legal jeopardy the executive branch\u8217\'20\'19s basis for lethal operations as well as detention operations.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Follow Charlie Savage on \uc2 Twitter{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/charlie_savage"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 @charlie_savage}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/politics/judge-lawsuit-war-isis.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Suit Calling War on ISIS Illegal Is Rejected}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/05/us/islamic-state-war-powers-lawsuit-obama.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 An Army Captain Takes Obama to Court Over ISIS Fight}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/25/us/politics/cia-detainee-prisons.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Trump Poised to Lift Ban on C.I.A. \u8216\'20\'18Black Site\u8217\'20\'19 Prisons}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/04/us/politics/black-site-prisons-cia-terrorist.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 White House Pulls Back From Bid to Reopen C.I.A. \u8216\'20\'18Black Site\u8217\'20\'19 Prisons}}}\par \par \uc2 An Army captain at the U.S. detention center at Guant\u225\'00\'E1namo Bay, Cuba. | Ben Fox/Associated Press \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed280040h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
