\par\par \uc2 Adolescence\par \uc2 Well; Family\par {\*\bkmkstart toc14}{\*\bkmkend toc14}\b \uc2 When a Teenager\u8217\'20\'19s Coping Mechanism Is SpongeBob\b0\par\par\uc2 By LISA DAMOUR \par \uc2 1,170 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 06:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Parents are often surprised to find that, even late into high school, teenagers return to the books, movies and TV shows they enjoyed when they were younger. When I ask adolescents to share how they like to recharge when feeling stressed, they consistently volunteer that they reread juvenile books like Percy Jackson, rewatch their favorite \uc2 Disney\uc2  movies, or mine \uc2 Netflix\uc2  for goofy shows like \u8220\'20\'1CSpongeBob SquarePants.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As Samantha Eisner, a 15-year-old student at Laurel School in Shaker Heights, Ohio, explained, childhood pleasures offer comfort because \u8220\'20\'1Cthey take you back to the days when the biggest problem you had was choosing what crayon to color your dress in your third grade self-portrait.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When teenagers aren\u8217\'20\'19t revisiting their early days, they sometimes turn to simple or repetitive activities to escape the ever-rising and shifting expectations that come with adolescence. In their efforts to gain a sense or mastery and control, some teenagers will go outside to drop in dozens of layups while others will rearrange their closets for the umpteenth time. \u8220\'20\'1CWhen I have really had it,\u8221\'20\'1D one adolescent told me, \u8220\'20\'1CI rip up a piece of paper and tape it back together again.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Being a teenager isn\u8217\'20\'19t easy. Thanks to puberty, neurological and hormonal developments introduce teenagers to an era of emotional fragility so it\u8217\'20\'19s no surprise that adolescents find handy, if sometimes quirky, ways to reset when they are feeling overwhelmed.\par \par \uc2 Should parents stand back and admire their teenagers\u8217\'20\'19 inventive coping styles or should they step in with support and guidance? The answer, according to experts, depends on how much control the teenagers have over the source of their stress.\par \par \uc2 When teenagers can actually do something about the challenges they face, new research confirms what common sense suggests: That adolescents feel better if they face their problems head-on.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10902-015-9630-z"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  One recent study}}}\uc2  found that teenagers who engage in approach coping \u8211\'20\'13 working to solve their problems, or actively addressing their emotions about the challenges they face \u8211\'20\'13 feel more satisfied with their lives than teenagers who rely on avoidance coping strategies such as ignoring or simply worrying about their problems.\par \par \uc2 According to Michael Lyons, the study\u8217\'20\'19s lead author and an assistant professor of education at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Virginia, \u8220\'20\'1Capproach coping is about trying to change the stressor itself.\u8221\'20\'1D For example, a teenager in a fight with a friend might talk with the peer about the conflict or \u8220\'20\'1Clook to others to find a different way to make sense of the situation.\u8221\'20\'1D By contrast, Dr. Lyons notes that teenagers who rely on avoidance coping might instead dodge the friend, or \u8220\'20\'1Cengage in a negative way, such as gossiping about the peer or ruminating about the problem.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But what about when teenagers face stressors that defy straightforward solutions, such as unrelenting school or social pressures? In that case, looking at old photos or playing an easy video game might be just what the doctor ordered.\par \par \uc2 Bruce Compas, a professor of psychology and pediatrics at Vanderbilt \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the author of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4038902/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 a research review}}}\uc2  on teenage coping notes that adolescents may \u8220\'20\'1Cjust need to take a break from something that is stressful, particularly if they can\u8217\'20\'19t change it or control it.\u8221\'20\'1D Dr. Compas\u8217\'20\'19s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4241756/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 research demonstrates}}}\uc2  that teenagers facing chronic or unavoidable stress feel better when they find positive distractions that can help \u8220\'20\'1Clift their spirits and get them out of a down or depressed mood.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Of course, a coping strategy stops being adaptive if it gets in the way of real responsibilities. A teenager in the middle of an unpredictable social drama can easily loose track of time while taking refuge in the known plots and predictable twists of \u8220\'20\'1CGray\u8217\'20\'19s Anatomy\u8221\'20\'1D reruns. Under these conditions, a parent might gently say something in the spirit of: \u8220\'20\'1CI know that what you are doing helps you to relax. Just be careful not to pile on more stress by running out of time to tackle tonight\u8217\'20\'19s homework.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Teenagers who are casting about for useful strategies to deal with stress may benefit from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://self-compassion.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Galla-2016.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 mindfulness training}}}\uc2  or{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1550830716301070"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  yoga programs}}}\uc2  that have been found to help adolescents decompress. Yet, as Dr. Lyons observes, \u8220\'20\'1Cthere\u8217\'20\'19s a lot of individual variability in how people respond to stressors. What is an effective strategy for one may not be an effective strategy for another.\u8221\'20\'1D I\u8217\'20\'19ve learned that some teenagers reset by playing with the family dog while others like to bake. Some adolescents restore themselves with having a good cry in a long shower while others rinse off the day\u8217\'20\'19s stresses by listening to their sad, angry or happy playlists.\par \par \uc2 Parents can suggest ways for teenagers to regain their equilibrium while being sensitive to the fact that coping strategies tend to be highly personal. When I\u8217\'20\'19ve asked groups of students how they like to rebound from a hard day, it\u8217\'20\'19s not unusual for the bulk of the group to recoil in horror when a peer volunteers that he straightens up his room to feel better. According to Dr. Lyons, these conversations between parent and teenager about coping strategies might be \u8220\'20\'1Cless about moving a teenager toward one approach and more about walking alongside them to discover what works best.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It falls to adults to be on the lookout for teenagers who are dealing with stressors far beyond what any adolescent should be expected to handle, such as traumatic events, the death of a loved one or even extraordinary academic pressures. And we should marshal professional support for teenagers who rely on self-destructive tactics, such as abusing substances or harming themselves, to cope with emotional discomfort.\par \par \uc2 But most of the time, parents are helping their teenagers weather the normal trials that come with adolescence. As we take up this day-to-day work, Dr. Compas encourages us to remind teenagers that there are two types of problems: Those we can do something about and those we need to find a way to accept. \u8220\'20\'1CThen we can ask our teens,\u8221\'20\'1D he says, \u8220\'20\'1Cwhat do you want to do about the ones you can change, and how are you going to manage the ones you can\u8217\'20\'19t?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Parents cannot shield teenagers from ordinary stress, nor should we try to. Yet we can still lend support. According to Dr. Compas, \u8220\'20\'1Cif parents can guide kids to slow down and simply size up the nature of the stress, that, in and of itself, would help an enormous amount.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Lisa Damour (@LDamour) is a psychologist in private practice in Shaker Heights, Ohio, a senior adviser to the Schubert Center for Child Studies at \uc2 Case Western Reserve \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the director of Laurel School\u8217\'20\'19s Center for Research on Girls. She is the author of \u8220\'20\'1CUntangled: Guiding Teenage Girls Through the Seven Transitions Into Adulthood.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/14/well/family/what-do-teenagers-want-potted-plant-parents.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 What Do Teenagers Want? Potted Plant Parents}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/well/family/talking-about-sex-with-daughters-and-sons.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Talking With Both Daughters and Sons About Sex}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/14/well/family/when-teenagers-bristle-at-how-was-school.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 When Teenagers Bristle at \u8216\'20\'18How Was School?\u8217\'20\'19}}}\par \par \uc2 Kim Murton \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28003e9\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
