\par\par \uc2 N.Y. / Region\par {\*\bkmkstart toc15}{\*\bkmkend toc15}\b \uc2 A New York Battle to Thwart Migrants of a Different Type\b0\par\par\uc2 By SARAH MASLIN NIR \par \uc2 1,474 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Some are disarmingly named, like the cutesy {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/35888.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Chinese m}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/35888.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 itten c}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/35888.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 rab}}}\uc2 . Others have names more indicative of their undesirable nature, like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/16/science/16invasive.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 r}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/16/science/16invasive.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 ock }}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/16/science/16invasive.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 snot}}}\uc2 , an algae that slimes up cool forest streams.\par \par \uc2 They are some of more than 100 invasive species that conservationists must battle in New York State, which teems with a growing number of plants, birds, fish, insects, mosses, molds and fungi that actually belong somewhere else.\par \par \uc2 With some of the busiest airports and ports in the United States, New York has far more invasive species than any other state, federal officials say. Carried inside airplane wheels or in the ballast water of large boats, many creatures and spores show up here first, making New York a laboratory of sorts where scientists and others strive to devise methods to banish the outsiders or risk losing native flora and fauna to invading hordes.\par \par \uc2 Underscoring the increasing menace posed by persistent pest species, \uc2 Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo\uc2 , a Democrat, recently announced a $2 million grant challenging groups and institutions to come up with fresh strategies to fight living things like habitat-choking zebra mussels and a catastrophic fungus that causes even the most ancient oaks to wilt away. Last year, the state budget for invasive species control was nearly doubled from 2015, to $12 million.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNew York State is a real epicenter for everything invasive, whether it\u8217\'20\'19s aquatic, forest or terrestrial, because of where we sit in terms of international and interstate commerce,\u8221\'20\'1D said Robert Davies, director of the division lands and forests for the state\u8217\'20\'19s Department of Environmental Conservation. \u8220\'20\'1CThe world is getting smaller and one of the downsides of the world getting smaller is this.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Invasive species have long been a threat; unwanted visitors, once they arrive, sometimes stay forever. The Asian long-horned beetle was first discovered in New York in 1996 and has been devouring hardwood trees nationwide ever since. In the last century, chestnut blight, a fungus, wiped out{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/23/planting-chestnuts-in-city-where-the-trees-blight-began/?_r=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  nearly all of New York\u8217\'20\'19s American chestnuts}}}\uc2 , once the most populous tree in the state. And gypsy moths, introduced from France in the 1860s, are still here, decimating leafy trees.\par \par \uc2 Despite strict rules about what can be brought into the United States and the screening of goods and packages by federal authorities at entry points, the sheer volume of traffic makes it virtually impossible to erect a fool-proof barrier. \u8220\'20\'1CAs a global hub for international trade and travel, New York is on the front lines of protecting our nation,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 Mr. Cuomo said in a statement.\par \par \uc2 The state mobilized in December after the discovery that oak trees in Brooklyn and in Suffolk County on Long Island were infected with oak wilt, a deadly fungus that chokes off trees\u8217\'20\'19 internal water supply. There is no known cure; contaminated trees must be cut down and their root systems killed to prevent the fungus from spreading. The state issued an order forbidding the transporting of oak wood out of the affected counties.\par \par \uc2 In Brooklyn, the outbreak was detected in a northern red oak tree \u8212\'20\'14 just one so far \u8212\'20\'14 inside the Green-Wood Cemetery, the final resting place for many luminaries. Now, only a stump is left of a once-stately shade tree that was over 50 years old. It was cut down last month to prevent the wilt\u8217\'20\'19s spread. The stump will get a coat of herbicide that will kill the root system, which is still infected.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe potential for the devastation here is immediately impactful, but it\u8217\'20\'19s also the significance for the oaks throughout the city,\u8221\'20\'1D said Joseph Charap, the director of horticulture for the cemetery, who first noticed the diseased oak.\par \par \uc2 He stood among the graves on a recent morning, while in the bare canopy of an uninfected oak tree above him, teams of hard-hatted men tethered to the upper branches sawed off limbs. The discovery had set off a race to prune all 664 of the cemetery\u8217\'20\'19s oak trees while they are dormant for the winter as a barricade against the spread of disease. The branches that are trimmed are treated with a special paint to guard against the fungus entering the trees.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe potential to lose our oak collection is unthinkable,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Charap said.\par \par \uc2 Across the country, invasive species cause over $100 billion in damage every year, according to the \uc2 United States Department of Agriculture\uc2 , from blighted crops to boats covered with sharp zebra mussels. New York State does not keep a total for damages caused, but the annual bill just to control one species \u8212\'20\'14 the sea lamprey, a parasitic fish \u8212\'20\'14 is $500,000 a year. The overall budget for invasive species control is about $5.5 million.\par \par \uc2 While the state is at the epicenter of the problem, there are hot spots, including other parts of the East Coast, California and Texas. Sitting at the intersection of so many streams of commerce, New York has had to innovate under the pressures of invasive species. In 2009 it introduced a novel law forbidding the transporting of any firewood more than 50 miles from its source to prevent the spread of disease. (The oak at Green-Wood cemetery, Mr. Charap believes, was probably infected by firewood improperly brought to the city.)\par \par \uc2 Inside a laboratory at \uc2 Cornell \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 , tiny, nut-brown Galerucella birmanica beetles from China are kept under quarantine as their appetite for water chestnut is tested. An invasive aquatic species most likely introduced to New York in the 1880s, the water chestnut continues to clog the state\u8217\'20\'19s fresh waterways. Someday, the bugs may be released as a biological means to control the plant. The state Conservation Department has also created an app that allows people to log sightings of plants and animals they suspect might not belong in their yards or any natural areas. Last year, over 300 people reported more than 12,000 such sightings.\par \par \uc2 On the ground, the battle is fought with teams of forestry experts going tree-to-tree inoculating root systems against fungus. In the air, the Conservation Department uses State Police helicopters to conduct seasonal patrols to spot shriveled trees on mountainsides or to search for animals that do not belong here, such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/docs/lands_forests_pdf/eurasianboarfact.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Eurasian }}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/docs/lands_forests_pdf/eurasianboarfact.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  b}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dec.ny.gov/docs/lands_forests_pdf/eurasianboarfact.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 oar}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Such efforts do pay off. It\u8217\'20\'19s been several years since the last boar sighting for \uc2 Bill Burns\uc2 , 75, a farmer who grows corn and other crops on over 600 acres in Spafford, N.Y., on the eastern edge of the Finger Lakes. Mr. Burns estimates that the animals, which are native to Russia and are believed to have been introduced here by game farmers who were careless with their fences, have caused more than $100,000 in damages to his crops over the years. \u8220\'20\'1CThey will go right down the corn planter tracks and suck the seed right out of the ground,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Burns said. He shot and killed several of them \u8212\'20\'14 \u8220\'20\'1Cthey taste rewarding,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said \u8212\'20\'14 but it took a concerted effort by the state and federal authorities, which sent in specially trained trappers and dogs to round up the animals, to achieve true relief.\par \par \uc2 The pigs have been eradicated from the state, according to the Conservation Department. Still, from his kitchen window, Mr. Burns can look across Skaneateles Lake and see stands of dead ash trees. He believes they have been killed by swarms of emerald ash borers, a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/01/science/the-slow-process-of-countering-the-emerald-ash-borer.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 jewel-toned Asian beetle}}}\uc2  first confirmed to have colonized New York State in 2009, according to \uc2 Cornell \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The insects are one of the state\u8217\'20\'19s top priorities.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Burns fears it is too late. \u8220\'20\'1CI am irritated and disappointed in just about everybody in the world that is careless,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Joseph Charap, the director of horticulture for Green-Wood Cemetery in Brooklyn, standing near the remains of an oak tree that had to be cut down last month to prevent the spread of oak wilt, a deadly fungus. | Christian Hansen for The New York Times | Workers from Emerald Tree Care Company pruned an oak tree at Green-Wood Cemetery. Over 600 trees had to be pruned at the cemetery after one was discovered to have a fungus that chokes off a tree\u8217\'20\'19s water supply. | Christian Hansen for The New York Times | Bill Burns, 75, on a piece of his 600-acre property in upstate New York. For years the land was menaced by Eurasian boars, which Mr. Burns said had caused over $100,000 in damages to his crops, until state and federal authorities sent in help. | Heather Ainsworth for The New York Times | The thorny vines of the multiflora rose, an invasive species native to eastern Asia, grow on Mr. Burns\u8217\'20\'19s property in Spafford, N.Y. | Heather Ainsworth for The New York Times \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28002sc\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
