\par\par \uc2 Feature\par \uc2 Magazine\par {\*\bkmkstart toc16}{\*\bkmkend toc16}\b \uc2 The Preacher and the Sheriff\b0\par\par\uc2 By NATHANIEL RICH \par \uc2 6,999 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 No one would tell The Rev. Victor White how his son died. Everyone seemed to know \u8212\'20\'14 but no one would tell him.\par \par \uc2 When a detective from the Louisiana State Police spoke to him at sunrise on a Monday morning, she wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t say much; she said his son was dead and his body transported to a hospital. White, in disbelief, did not give the full story to his wife, Vanessa, but he could tell she feared the worst. During the two-hour drive to New Iberia, where his son and his son\u8217\'20\'19s infant daughter lived, neither parent spoke.\par \par \uc2 At the \uc2 Iberia Medical Center\uc2 , nobody would answer White\u8217\'20\'19s questions. An administrator directed him to the admitting doctor, who directed him to the attending state trooper, who directed him to an investigator from the coroner\u8217\'20\'19s office, who directed him back to the trooper. White left Vanessa sobbing in the waiting room and at last was taken to the morgue. He was allowed to view the corpse only from the neck up, but that was enough; he could see that his son had been beaten. A bruise extended from his left eyebrow to his jaw. His lips and nose were swollen, and, White says, his left eye was bashed in. When White returned to the waiting room, his wife was gone. She had been taken away to be sedated.\par \par \uc2 The coroner\u8217\'20\'19s investigator approached White. \u8220\'20\'1CIt was like he wanted to say something, without saying it,\u8221\'20\'1D White says. \u8220\'20\'1CHe said: \u8216\'20\'18I\u8217\'20\'19m so sorry.\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D White said the investigator mumbled this repeatedly for several minutes. \u8220\'20\'1CI can\u8217\'20\'19t say anything,\u8221\'20\'1D the official said finally, \u8220\'20\'1Cbut you should look into your son\u8217\'20\'19s death.\u8221\'20\'1D (A lawyer for the coroner\u8217\'20\'19s office, citing litigation, declined to respond to questions for this article.)\par \par \uc2 The Louisiana State Police never did tell White what happened to his son. He learned of their account through a news release posted online that evening, March 3, 2014. The police said that Victor White III, while detained in the back seat of a locked police car, his hands shackled behind his back, had committed suicide by shooting himself in the back with a handgun that an officer had not found during an earlier search.\par \par \uc2 New Iberia, a small city surrounded by sugar cane 100 miles west of New Orleans, is bisected by railroad tracks. North of the tracks, where residents are predominantly white, most believed that Victor White III committed suicide. In the largely black neighborhoods south of the tracks, most residents shared the Whites\u8217\'20\'19 conviction that their son was executed by the cops. In the months of heartbreak and rage that followed, New Iberians tended to believe the official account of the \u8220\'20\'1CHoudini suicide\u8221\'20\'1D to the extent that they approved of the performance of Louis Ackal, the sheriff of Iberia Parish.\par \par \uc2 Ackal \u8212\'20\'14 who declined multiple requests for comment for this article \u8212\'20\'14 was the most powerful man in town and perhaps the most popular. A fourth-generation New Iberian, he was a southern Louisiana politician in the old mold: charismatic and irascible, given to country bromides and plain-spoken provocations, antagonistic to the regional press and civil-liberties groups, chummy with the political class, a friend to many and a bully to the rest. He smoked cigars and kicked his boots onto his desk during meetings. He had come to office as a reformer, pledging to bring integrity to the police force and criminals to justice \u8212\'20\'14 to, as he put it in a campaign speech, clean up \u8220\'20\'1Ca terrible mess.\u8221\'20\'1D To the satisfaction of a plurality of voters, he had succeeded.\par \par \uc2 At Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s request, the state police opened an investigation into the death. Additional investigations were later started by the F.B.I., the United States attorney\u8217\'20\'19s office for the Western District of Louisiana and the \uc2 Justice Department\u8217\'20\'19s civil rights division\uc2 . But the man best suited to investigate the strange death of Victor White III \u8212\'20\'14 the man with the most intimate knowledge of New Iberia, its legacy of racial conspiracy, the inner workings of the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office \u8212\'20\'14 was the victim\u8217\'20\'19s father. The Rev. Victor White was motivated by grief, anger and a desire for justice, but that was not all. He was also haunted by the fear that his own actions, his own history in New Iberia, might have led to his son\u8217\'20\'19s death.\par \par \uc2 Victor White III, whom everyone called Little Vic, was the sixth of nine children and the Whites\u8217\'20\'19 youngest son. (One of the older brothers, Victor White Jr., is known as Junior.) Little Vic inherited his father\u8217\'20\'19s tall, rangy stature; his large, expressive eyes; his exuberant manner. When the brothers got in trouble \u8212\'20\'14 when, for instance, they were caught playing in the attic with a sword their father brought back from Korea \u8212\'20\'14 Little Vic always took the blame, though he was a terrible liar. He did manage to convince his parents of one thing: After attending a Baptist service and witnessing all the jumping, shouting and singing, he begged his parents to change denominations. Not only did they agree, but Victor Sr., a mental-health and substance-abuse counselor, became ordained as a Baptist minister.\par \par \uc2 The Whites are not from New Iberia but the longleaf pine region of central Louisiana. They lived in Alexandria, a somewhat larger city with a somewhat broader perspective on questions of class and race. White can trace his family line back to a plantation outside the nearby town of Cheneyville. \u8220\'20\'1CMy grandmother,\u8221\'20\'1D he told me, \u8220\'20\'1Cwas a slave. She was born around 1900. She worked in the cotton field and worked domestic as well.\u8221\'20\'1D I took this to mean that she worked under slavelike conditions. White responded forcefully: \u8220\'20\'1CShe was a slave.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In late 2006, a pastor in New Iberia called White with a desperate request. The city, which had a long history of racial brutality, was in the throes of a new crisis. The source of the tension, as it had been so many times before, was the annual Louisiana Sugar Cane Festival. The festival was really two festivals: The official festival, held downtown, featured parades, a boat procession down the Bayou Teche and a fais do-do, presided over by the members of a royal court, many drawn from the ancien r\u233\'00\'E9gime families of prominent planters. The second festival was held across the tracks in the West End, on land that once belonged to the Hopkins sugar plantation. During the Jim Crow era, this second celebration was formalized as the Brown Sugar Festival, with its own parade and a Queen Brown Sugar. In recent years, it had been a looser affair, an occasion for block parties, D.J. sets and joy riding down Hopkins Street, past the shacks with rusted tin roofs, the overgrown lots, the bodegas advertising daiquiris and Wings cigarettes.\par \par \uc2 On the final day of that year\u8217\'20\'19s festival, after traffic on Hopkins Street came to a standstill, deputies of the New Iberia sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office fired grenades of tear gas into the black crowds. The sheriff, Sid Hebert, claimed his deputies gassed the revelers out of concern for their health. \u8220\'20\'1CIt was only a matter of minutes,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, \u8220\'20\'1Cbefore someone in the crowd would fire a weapon.\u8221\'20\'1D In a federal lawsuit, later dismissed, 160 West End residents claimed to have suffered injuries. The oldest claimants grew up under Jim Crow; the youngest was 8 months old.\par \par \uc2 Hebert expressed remorse about the incident and agreed to meet with local ministers to improve his department\u8217\'20\'19s relationship with the West End. White, who had developed a reputation among Baptist ministers in southern Louisiana for engaging law enforcement on civil rights issues, was asked to serve as mediator. In early 2007, he moved his family to New Iberia. Little Vic was 15.\par \par \uc2 White helped to open a community center on Hopkins and ran a substance-abuse program that attracted clients from both sides of the tracks, including members of some of the most prominent white families. He began to understand the nature of power in New Iberia and the sinuous channels it pursued. He wanted to make sure his children understood too. He made a point of taking them to the Sugar Cane Festival. Almost immediately, they were stopped and questioned by the police. \u8220\'20\'1CIt took them for a loop,\u8221\'20\'1D White says. \u8220\'20\'1CThey\u8217\'20\'19d never seen stuff like that in Alexandria. They said: \u8216\'20\'18Daddy, what are they stopping us for?\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The Whites rented a house just off Hopkins; there was a working sugar-cane field at the end of their block. They held barbecues and kept their doors open. They spoke about the need to establish a public-transportation system, to rebuild the local elementary school, to encourage children to develop professional ambitions. \u8220\'20\'1CIf we could get those kids,\u8221\'20\'1D White says, \u8220\'20\'1Cwe could get their parents.\u8221\'20\'1D White felt he was making progress, particularly when it came to restoring faith in the Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department. He had the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s cellphone number and called it often. He says he provided leads for criminal investigations and complained when cops behaved arrogantly. But Hebert\u8217\'20\'19s term was up in 2008, and a new sheriff came to town.\par \par \uc2 In downtown New Iberia, where the millionaires lived, and in the less ostentatious, leafy City Park neighborhood, north of the Bayou Teche, Louis Ackal was welcomed home in 2008 as a savior. Most New Iberians grew up knowing his family, which arrived in south Louisiana in the late 1880s, during the first wave of Lebanese immigration to the United States. For 60 years, the Ackals owned a department store and a shoe store on Main Street. A local bridge that spans the Teche is named for Elias Ackal Jr., known as Bo, who served for more than two decades in the Louisiana House of Representatives. \u8220\'20\'1CThey were part of the old guard,\u8221\'20\'1D says Jarrod Alleman, an oil-field safety specialist who attended school with members of the Ackal family. \u8220\'20\'1CAll of our elected officials came out of a pool of people who were connected, and it had been like that forever. He was part of the ruling elite.\u8221\'20\'1D Yet Alleman, like many on the north side, saw Ackal as a reformer. \u8220\'20\'1CHe was worldly. He had been places, had done other things. He seemed like a professional, not just someone\u8217\'20\'19s brother-in-law.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Ackal passed for worldly in New Iberia because he left town three decades earlier to work as a state trooper, serving at one point in the governor\u8217\'20\'19s office, before retiring to a small mountain town in northwest Colorado. He came out of retirement, he said, because he was disturbed by the \u8220\'20\'1Chorror stories\u8221\'20\'1D he had heard about residents\u8217\'20\'19 encounters with the police in his hometown. There was a sense in the community that crime rates were unusually high for a place the size of New Iberia. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m not a big fan of politics,\u8221\'20\'1D Ackal said in a campaign speech. \u8220\'20\'1CThe reason I ran was because people told me they were scared in their own homes.\u8221\'20\'1D Besides, he added, he missed the \u8220\'20\'1Ccrawfish and crabs and gumbo, and Cajun music.\u8221\'20\'1D Ackal ran as a change candidate, pledging to strengthen the internal-affairs unit and repair the relationship between the Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department and residents. He vowed to hire a public-information officer to communicate regularly with the press. He promised transparency, professionalism, strength.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CA lot of people had faith in him,\u8221\'20\'1D Julie Comeaux, a stay-at-home mother in the City Park neighborhood, told me. \u8220\'20\'1CPeople looked to him to move us forward.\u8221\'20\'1D If anyone could move the community forward, it was the sheriff. Louisiana sheriffs have a staggering measure of power and few checks on it. They collect taxes, run the jails and command the police force. In the smaller cities and parishes, they often hold greater political clout than mayors, parish presidents and businessmen \u8212\'20\'14 a power that derives in no small part from their ability to pursue criminal investigations of mayors, parish presidents and businessmen. As Sheriff \uc2 Harry Lee\uc2  of Jefferson Parish once put it, when asked why he declined to run for statewide office: \u8220\'20\'1CWhy would I want to be governor when I can be king?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It helped that Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s family was respected on both sides of town. \u8220\'20\'1CThe Ackals I knew were just wonderful people, personable, sweet,\u8221\'20\'1D says Phebe Hayes, a former professor at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Louisiana at Lafayette\uc2  and amateur historian of African-American life in the parish. \u8220\'20\'1CThey didn\u8217\'20\'19t feel very Old South. More Old World.\u8221\'20\'1D Two generations earlier, when black-owned restaurants, upholstery shops and pharmacies thrived in the West End and Count Basie and Ella Fitzgerald played in the nightclubs, before it fell into an eerie dilapidated vacancy, the Ackals ran a general store on Hopkins. Ackal boasted of the store while stumping for votes on the West End, White says, which made him suspicious.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe was intimidating, very arrogant,\u8221\'20\'1D White says. \u8220\'20\'1CHe walked into peoples\u8217\'20\'19 yards. He\u8217\'20\'19d say: \u8216\'20\'18My grandfather owned that store. When y\u8217\'20\'19all went in to go shopping, who you think it was? That was my people. We were helping y\u8217\'20\'19all. Y\u8217\'20\'19all owe me.\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 White was appalled to find that this argument was persuasive among his neighbors. They told him that he didn\u8217\'20\'19t understand, because he was an outsider. \u8220\'20\'1CI said: \u8216\'20\'18I do understand. This is what I\u8217\'20\'19m trying to get you out of. Y\u8217\'20\'19all are 40 years behind Alexandria.\u8217\'20\'19 But they thought he was going to help them. That was when I became the villain.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 White met Ackal for the first time at the community center, shortly after the election. It was a brief conversation. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m going in a different direction,\u8221\'20\'1D White says Ackal told him. Ackal reassigned the West End community liaison, installed a police substation within the community center and fought to increase the size of the jail. White, refusing to concede defeat, remained in New Iberia, working as a substance-abuse counselor.\par \par \uc2 On the north side of town, many residents felt that Ackal was making good on his promises. He bought new uniforms and squad cars, to which he affixed bumper stickers reading, \u8220\'20\'1CIn God We Trust.\u8221\'20\'1D When \uc2 the American Civil Liberties Union\uc2  complained, Ackal defended the stickers by saying that his officers had accepted God into their lives. \u8220\'20\'1CIf there is no God,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, \u8220\'20\'1Cthen we don\u8217\'20\'19t have a good police officer, do we?\u8221\'20\'1D There were rumors of police brutality, though most people on the north side didn\u8217\'20\'19t know anyone who had suffered. \u8220\'20\'1CWe figured he was corrupt,\u8221\'20\'1D says Jarrod Alleman. \u8220\'20\'1CWe started hearing that things were going on. But they weren\u8217\'20\'19t happening where we were. When I got pulled over for speeding, the cop took a look at my license and said: \u8216\'20\'18You live on Oak? I grew up down the street.\u8217\'20\'19 If I were someone else, maybe of a different color, and lived in the West End, I\u8217\'20\'19m 100 percent positive it would have gone down differently.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It did go down differently in the West End, where the police came to be seen as an occupying army. The jail population surged, the cells becoming so overcrowded that inmates were forced to sleep on the floor. Following Arizona\u8217\'20\'19s Sheriff Joe Arpaio, Ackal punished prisoners by dressing them in hot pink jumpsuits and making them sleep in a pink cell he called the Flamingo Hotel. He boasted about denying ice to inmates in hot weather. \u8220\'20\'1CA state inspector came in and said: \u8216\'20\'18Sheriff Ackal, you need to put ice chests, ice buckets and scoops in the cells,\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D he told a crowd of supporters, to laughter. \u8220\'20\'1CI said: \u8216\'20\'18Lady, I don\u8217\'20\'19t know where you come from, but this is not the [Hotel] Monteleone. It\u8217\'20\'19s the Iberia Parish Jail.\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D At the 2011 Sugar Cane Festival, Ackal sent his officers to the West End to break up the celebration. They blasted sirens to drown out the music and, once again, fired tear gas into the crowd.\par \par \uc2 White finally gave up and moved his family back to Alexandria. Little Vic and his brother Leonard were unhappy: Each had a girlfriend from Iberia Parish who didn\u8217\'20\'19t want to leave. In 2013, after the birth of his daughter, Arianna, and against his parents\u8217\'20\'19 desperate warnings, Little Vic returned.\par \par \uc2 White could not believe that his son committed suicide, because every aspect of Little Vic\u8217\'20\'19s life seemed oriented toward the future. Upon returning to New Iberia, he enrolled in a welding program at the local community college, planning to work on offshore rigs. He took a job at a Waffle House, often pulling double shifts. His final conversation with his father took place at 7 a.m. on the last morning of his life. Little Vic had just received a tax rebate and was eager to buy a used \uc2 Chrysler\uc2  from a man who fixed up broken-down cars. He had taken cash with him \u8212\'20\'14 $1,400 \u8212\'20\'14 but after a test drive, he suspected there was a problem with the transmission. White warned him to wait until the seller provided a warranty. \u8220\'20\'1CO.K., Dad,\u8221\'20\'1D said Little Vic. That was it.\par \par \uc2 Little Vic\u8217\'20\'19s only previous encounter with the police after returning to New Iberia occurred about five months before, in November, when he was stopped for making an illegal U-turn. He did as his father had told him: He announced that he was the son of the Rev. Victor White and demanded the cops call his father. The officers, unmoved, arrested him. \u8220\'20\'1CWhen Little Vic knows he\u8217\'20\'19s right,\u8221\'20\'1D says Vanessa, who speaks of her son in the present tense, \u8220\'20\'1Che has a way of getting under your skin.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The officers who arrested him were named Justin Ortis and Jason Javier. The same men stopped Little Vic near the train tracks that split New Iberia at 11:31 p.m. on the night of March 2, 2014. Minutes earlier, Little Vic and an acquaintance named Isaiah Lewis were buying cigarillos at a nearby Texaco gas station when a fight broke out in the parking lot. Ortis, suspecting that White and Lewis were involved, patted them down. Nothing was found on Lewis, and he was released.\par \par \uc2 After that, in the police\u8217\'20\'19s version of events, officers found a small quantity of narcotics \u8212\'20\'14 marijuana and cocaine \u8212\'20\'14 in White\u8217\'20\'19s pocket, and he was detained. Because he asked to speak with narcotics detectives, the officers did not take him to the Iberia Parish Jail, where arrestees are booked, but to the patrol center downtown. When they arrived, according to police statements, White \u8220\'20\'1Cbecame uncooperative and refused to exit the deputy\u8217\'20\'19s patrol vehicle.\u8221\'20\'1D He wanted them to promise that he would not be sent to jail. When a deputy said he could not make that promise, White said to \u8220\'20\'1Ctell his people that he loved them.\u8221\'20\'1D He said: \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t want to go to jail,\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m gone.\u8221\'20\'1D Next, the deputies claim in the police report, they heard a gunshot.\par \par \uc2 The state police also later claimed that Leonard White volunteered to investigators that his brother was carrying a .25-caliber pistol that night that matched the description of the weapon found next to Little Vic\u8217\'20\'19s body in the back seat. (White\u8217\'20\'19s family denies this.)\par \par \uc2 Victor White, not trusting the police, immediately began his own investigation of the case. He uncovered a number of apparent inconsistencies in the official narrative. Among the most glaring was the assertion that Little Vic had shot himself in the back. Before making the autopsy results public, the parish coroner at the time, Carl Ditch, told White that the bullet entered his son\u8217\'20\'19s chest, White says, contradicting the original news release. Ditch noted that the bullet had entered the side of his chest, beneath the right nipple, and exited under his left armpit. But Little Vic was left-handed. White was incredulous: \u8220\'20\'1CYou\u8217\'20\'19re trying to tell me that my son, while handcuffed, reached his left hand all the way around the front of his chest and shot himself from the right? I said: \u8216\'20\'18No, sir.\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 There were inauspicious coincidences. The incident took place in a part of the patrol-center parking lot that had no surveillance cameras. The back-seat camera in the cruiser in which White died was turned off, as was the microphone. When White picked up his son\u8217\'20\'19s possessions, Little Vic\u8217\'20\'19s wallet contained only $91. But White believed that his son was carrying about $1,400. When White told the officer that there had been a mistake, she withdrew the bag and disappeared momentarily into the property room, exclaiming: \u8220\'20\'1COh! I must have missed these before.\u8221\'20\'1D She pulled a pair of $100 bills from the wallet. \u8220\'20\'1CI just looked at her,\u8221\'20\'1D White says. \u8220\'20\'1CI said: \u8216\'20\'18Ma\u8217\'20\'19am, do you really think I believe that?\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 After the state police cleared the Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department of wrongdoing, Louis Ackal released a statement. \u8220\'20\'1CIn my opinion,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, \u8220\'20\'1Cthis was a tragic loss of life, and it is difficult to understand why it happened.\u8221\'20\'1D Ackal extended \u8220\'20\'1Chis deepest sympathy\u8221\'20\'1D to the White family.\par \par \uc2 White says that he was not surprised by what he believes happened to his son. \u8220\'20\'1CNot at all,\u8221\'20\'1D he says. \u8220\'20\'1CBecause I knew the type of person Louis Ackal was.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 White\u8217\'20\'19s family filed a civil suit against Ackal and Ortis. (In court papers, Ackal and Ortis, who is no longer employed by the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office, denied White\u8217\'20\'19s allegations. A lawyer representing the defendants declined to comment.) White shared the results of his investigation with F.B.I. agents, and he said they assured him that they would follow up on his findings. But in December 2015, 21 months after his son\u8217\'20\'19s death, the Justice Department announced that it had not found sufficient evidence \u8220\'20\'1Cto prove beyond a reasonable doubt that any officer fired a weapon at Mr. White.\u8221\'20\'1D It declined to prosecute.\par \par \uc2 When the White family\u8217\'20\'19s attorney, Carol Powell Lexing, pushed for an explanation, the federal officers conceded that they had accepted the state police\u8217\'20\'19s conclusions at face value. Powell Lexing found this \u8220\'20\'1Ccrazy,\u8221\'20\'1D because she believed that the state police had incentive to protect Ackal, their colleague for 23 years. Powell Lexing says federal officers \u8220\'20\'1Cadmitted they never saw the gun. They only saw a picture of the gun in the police report. Based on a picture, how could you link it to White?\u8221\'20\'1D (At the time this article went to press, the Department of Justice had declined to provide, in response to Freedom of Information Act requests filed last May, any documents that might explain its decision. Spokespeople for the F.B.I. and the Department of Justice had no comment.)\par \par \uc2 While the Justice Department investigated the White case, Powell Lexing was frequently contacted by New Iberians eager to tell of abuse suffered at the hands of the Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department. She forwarded these accounts to the F.B.I. White was at least the eighth person to die in custody during Sheriff Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s administration. She didn\u8217\'20\'19t think this was a coincidence.\par \par \uc2 Three months after declining White\u8217\'20\'19s case, the Justice Department announced it was indicting Louis Ackal on charges of deprivation of rights and conspiracy against rights \u8212\'20\'14 in about a dozen incidents unrelated to White\u8217\'20\'19s. Eight of Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s officers had pleaded guilty to civil rights violations and agreed to testify in exchange for reduced sentences. The indictment described a police department that operated like an organized-crime syndicate, with Ackal as kingpin.\par \par \uc2 According to court papers, Ackal ordered deputies to beat at least five pretrial detainees inside the Iberia Parish Jail. Many of the beatings took place in the prison\u8217\'20\'19s chapel \u8212\'20\'14 not because the officers had accepted God into their lives but, the indictment claimed, because the chapel was one of the few places in the prison without surveillance cameras. One inmate was targeted for making what the indictment described as a \u8220\'20\'1Clewd comment,\u8221\'20\'1D another for sending letters complaining of poor conditions in the jail. An inmate accused of \u8220\'20\'1Clooking\u8221\'20\'1D at a guard was attacked by a police dog, a grisly episode captured on video later leaked to the press. The indictment described an incident in which three drunk off-duty cops beat up a couple of young black men for kicks, a second in which Ackal ordered the assault of a personal rival and a third in which Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s former chief of staff, Lt. Col. Gerald Savoy, known as Bubba, was accused of having ordered the arrest of a man who punched him at a bar. His officers beat the man, shackled him to a bench and ordered him to lick his own blood off the wall.\par \par \uc2 The judge stripped Ackal of his gun, but he continued to serve as sheriff \u8212\'20\'14 even after, according to court papers, he was recorded threatening to shoot a federal attorney prosecuting his case, Mark Blumberg, \u8220\'20\'1Cright between your [expletive] Jewish-eyes-look-like-opossum bastard.\u8221\'20\'1D Last May, after White helped to organize a protest demanding he leave office, Ackal released a one-sentence statement: \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19ll be a cold day in hell when I resign.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 On a hot day last July, White joined a fledgling effort to recall Ackal. He needed to collect the signatures of 16,000 registered voters \u8212\'20\'14 about a third of the population of Iberia Parish \u8212\'20\'14 by the end of the year to put the measure on a ballot. It was a long shot, and not only because of Louisiana\u8217\'20\'19s high thresholds for political recalls: Though Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s popularity had declined, he had still managed in 2015 to win a runoff election to his third consecutive term as sheriff. White did not care. He drove each weekend to New Iberia and set up a table with voter-registration forms and signature sheets in a West End parking lot. He wore a T-shirt bearing an oversize photograph of his son across his chest.\par \par \uc2 The parking lot, opposite a red-brick public housing development and framed by abandoned storefronts, belonged to Kevin Broussard, a barbershop owner and school-bus driver who served as the unofficial mayor of his corner of the neighborhood. \u8220\'20\'1CSo many people are afraid,\u8221\'20\'1D Broussard said. \u8220\'20\'1CThey don\u8217\'20\'19t know their rights.\u8221\'20\'1D He had voted for Ackal twice, though he grew suspicious on the night of the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s first re-election. \u8220\'20\'1CIt was like a dream. He drove by in a limo, sticking a cigar out the window like Lex Luthor. I said: \u8216\'20\'18This dude has too much paper.\u8217\'20\'19 You get to be king, you don\u8217\'20\'19t think no one can stop you.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Many passing through the lot spoke of regular raids by the narcotics unit, which functioned as a kind of paramilitary force within the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office. \u8220\'20\'1CThey called it \u8216\'20\'18Jump-Out Boys Days,\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D Broussard said. \u8220\'20\'1CIn other words, jump out on the black boys. They\u8217\'20\'19d say: \u8216\'20\'18How much money you made this week? You made enough for me to hit you up?\u8217\'20\'19 That\u8217\'20\'19s how bold they were.\u8221\'20\'1D He said narcotics officers barged into homes without warrants, stealing most of the cash they found.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey\u8217\'20\'19d kick in your door, tear your house up,\u8221\'20\'1D said a large man named Whitney Lee. \u8220\'20\'1CThey would come back here with assault rifles and bulletproof vests in their little Desert Storm outfits like they\u8217\'20\'19re coming to war.\u8221\'20\'1D He gave the rueful laugh that tended to accompany discussions of the police in the West End. \u8220\'20\'1CI ain\u8217\'20\'19t going to lie, I was scared of them. Because I know they could just as soon kill me.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Lee has filed a civil suit against Ackal and two of his deputies, one of 30 or so that have been filed since he took office; at least 10 have been settled, for a cumulative sum of about $1.1 million. Lee\u8217\'20\'19s suit involved an episode that occurred while he was serving time. He was taken to the recreation yard while prison officials searched his cell for contraband, and he was told to lie on the ground and put \u8220\'20\'1Cyour ass in the air for your girlfriend.\u8221\'20\'1D Lee, citing his asthma, complained that he couldn\u8217\'20\'19t breathe and was beaten. (In court papers, the defendants\u8217\'20\'19 lawyer denied the charges.)\par \par \uc2 Broussard waved a laminated paper with a photograph of Victor White III and other men who had died in custody, surrounded by photographs of the indicted officers. He had titled the page \u8220\'20\'1COrganized Crime.\u8221\'20\'1D Beside the officers\u8217\'20\'19 heads, he had written nicknames for them. Byron Benjamin Lassalle, who pleaded guilty to forcing an inmate to fellate a baton, was Crazy Boy. Ackal was the Don. There was little known publicly about the inner workings of the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office, but everyone in New Iberia was connected to everyone else; everyone had secret stories. Since his son\u8217\'20\'19s death, White had received periodic text messages from an anonymous phone number with tips from within the Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department. Oneal Davis, an officer who had recently retired from Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s department, told me the most corrupt, violent cops were the ones Ackal chose for promotion, a system that encouraged ever-increasing levels of brutality, a pyramid scheme of violence.\par \par \uc2 (In court papers, Ackal has denied that he failed to properly supervise the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office. The public-information officer for the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office wrote, in emailed statements: \u8220\'20\'1CIf there is a question of possible wrongdoing by members of our agency, Sheriff Ackal will welcome an independent investigation from an outside law-enforcement agency. Sheriff Ackal does not condone any illegal activities by his employees and will not hesitate to have an employee arrested if it is proved that they are involved in illegal activities.\u8221\'20\'1D The officer added that \u8220\'20\'1CSheriff Ackal strives for all of his deputies to be as professional as possible and expects them to treat every citizen within his jurisdiction equally.\u8221\'20\'1D)\par \par \uc2 Also pictured on Broussard\u8217\'20\'19s sheet was Michael Jones, a mentally ill inmate who, according to court papers, died after an outburst in which he ran from his cell naked and screaming. Two former officers, Wesley and Jesse Hayes, along with a former warden, slammed him to the floor, beat him, handcuffed him, put him in a chokehold and sat on top of him until he died. The Hayes brothers had a side career as Da Bayou Boys, a tag-team wrestling duo; after victories, they stuffed their opponents\u8217\'20\'19 mouths with boudin sausage. A judge awarded Jones\u8217\'20\'19s family $61,000 in a wrongful-death suit. In Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s federal case, the Hayes brothers pleaded guilty to other incidents of excessive force; Wesley filed a whistle-blower suit claiming that he was fired for reporting misconduct.\par \par \uc2 One of the petition organizers working with White, Khadijah Rashad, has for more than 20 years kept in a roller suitcase, locked in a secret compartment of her bedroom closet, an archive of racial violence in the parish. Ackal is the third consecutive sheriff to be taken to court on alleged civil rights violations. Before Hebert\u8217\'20\'19s stunt at the 2006 Sugar Cane Festival, his predecessor, Errol Romero, settled a lawsuit in which he and his jail warden were indicted on charges related to their forcing prisoners to sit in restraint chairs for weeks at a time, and hogtying prisoners with their mouths taped and football helmets placed backward over their heads.\par \par \uc2 After five hours, White was still leaping through traffic, hailing passers-by, collecting signatures. The recall event had expanded into a more general protest \u8212\'20\'14 a protest of parish history, Louisiana history, national history. \u8220\'20\'1CYou got these ignorant people in positions of power, and they\u8217\'20\'19re abusing it,\u8221\'20\'1D Whitney Lee said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey call it corruption,\u8221\'20\'1D Rashad said. \u8220\'20\'1CI call it racism.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Though neither the iberia Parish President Nor the mayor of New Iberia called for Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s removal from office, the Louisiana Sugar Cane Festival replaced his department on the security detail for last year\u8217\'20\'19s festival with officers from Youngsville, a small town 15 miles northwest. Ackal, by then, had bigger problems. He had asked the judge to reconsider the decision to confiscate his gun \u8220\'20\'1Cin view of what\u8217\'20\'19s happening across the country,\u8221\'20\'1D referring to the recent shootings of police officers; two months earlier, Louisiana passed a Blue Lives Matter law, the first in the nation, which gave the police hate-crime protections. The judge was unsympathetic to Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s argument. A week before the festival, federal prosecutors added additional details to the indictment, charging that Ackal had ordered the destruction of the department\u8217\'20\'19s internal-affairs files and routinely instructed his officers to falsify police reports.\par \par \uc2 As the parades marched downtown, the West End was in a circumspect mood. A few blocks from Kevin Broussard\u8217\'20\'19s parking lot, three women sat in a field next to two homes and a beauty salon that had flooded to a height of four feet during the major Louisiana rain event a month earlier. The homes and the salon belonged to twin sisters named Wonderful and Wonderlynn Galentine. Repairs to the properties were funded by the West End Council of Neighborhoods Association, a nonprofit organization that serves the West End. It formed in 2008, when Ackal took office. \u8220\'20\'1CWecna is here to do those things that government is not doing,\u8221\'20\'1D said Eva Lewis, the association\u8217\'20\'19s president, who was checking on the progress to Wonderful\u8217\'20\'19s home. She was joined by Robby Carrier-Bethel, a Wecna member and second-generation activist \u8212\'20\'14 her mother, Clara Lee DeGay Carrier, a member of the school board, was the first African-American elected to office in the parish. \u8220\'20\'1CThere is a huge breakdown in the West End,\u8221\'20\'1D Carrier-Bethel said. \u8220\'20\'1CEverybody who lives in Iberia Parish has to bear some shame. We have to ask ourselves: How could anyone know anything and turn a blind eye?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Carrier-Bethel is pursuing a criminal-justice degree; the previous night, she stayed up late to finish a paper about Kantian moral philosophy. \u8220\'20\'1CIn order to get justice, you need to have truth.\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CChildren should not have to live in fear of law enforcement. That is the worst thing that could ever happen to a community.\u8221\'20\'1D She began to cry. \u8220\'20\'1CYou have to watch what you say and who you say it to. You have to swallow it. And you know that, as hard as you try, things are not getting better.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The women hadn\u8217\'20\'19t attended the Sugar Cane Festival for years. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat they\u8217\'20\'19re celebrating is not very respectful to what African-Americans experienced in this parish,\u8221\'20\'1D Carrier-Bethel said, measuring her words. As recently as the late 1960s, some sugar-plantation workers were paid in scrip that could be exchanged only at plantation-owned stores. \u8220\'20\'1CThe history is not the scary part. It\u8217\'20\'19s the ignorance of the history. You hope that things change, but when you go to a parade and you see a sea of whiteness, it reminds you that there\u8217\'20\'19s still a lack of respect for who you are as a person. Until we begin to be brutally honest about what is happening in our parish \u8212\'20\'14 what is happening in America \u8212\'20\'14 it will always be a sea of whiteness.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Across town, following the 4-H Live Stock Show and Sale and the Blessing of the Crops, the 75th annual Sugar Cane Festival reached its culmination with the coronation of Queen Sugar. The pageant was held at the festival\u8217\'20\'19s own theater in City Park, which quickly filled to capacity. The men wore oxford shirts in shades of violet, gray and white, with ties and without jackets; the women wore pearls, floral-patterned gowns, bouffant hair. Some had brooches identifying them as \u8220\'20\'1CFormer Queen Sugar.\u8221\'20\'1D The atmosphere was galvanized, giddy. It seemed that everyone knew nearly everyone else. It seemed that every single person was white.\par \par \uc2 The curtain opened on the Sugar Lumps, a troupe of middle-aged women dressed in black spandex and emerald sequin vests performing a synchronized dance to Pitbull\u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1CCelebrate.\u8221\'20\'1D On the stage behind them, stands of sugar cane were set against silver draping. In the center stood a throne for King Sucrose and Queen Sugar, who magnanimously waved their scepters.\par \par \uc2 There followed a procession of visiting queens: Miss Cajun Hot Sauce Queen, Miss Creole Gumbo Queen, Miss Crawfish Queen, Miss Gonzales Jambalaya Queen. After the entrance of the three judges, each a representative of the sugar industry, the contestants for Queen Sugar introduced themselves:\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhere the sugar cane grows in all directions, and our two mills process it in sweet confections, the cane may be much taller than me, but I can promise you that I\u8217\'20\'19m just as sweet. Proudly representing Assumption Parish, I am \u8212\'20\'14\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re going to make your life sooo sweet, when you shake it on down to sugar town. Feel free to stomp your feet to that good old Cajun beat. Proudly representing Terrebonne Parish, I am \u8212\'20\'14\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The daughters of the old planter families held elaborate curtsies while announcers read their biographical statements. When asked whom they would most like to meet, three contestants chose Jean \u201\'00\'C9tienne de Bor\u233\'00\'E9, who made sugar cane commercially viable in Louisiana in 1795.\par \par \uc2 At last the M.C. requested the envelope. The contestants smiled bravely. The audience quivered in anticipation. The winner was announced: Caroline Marcello of Lafourche Parish. She was handed a bouquet of roses, a silver tiara with bejeweled sugar-cane stalks, a cape embroidered with glittering white petals. The audience stood as one. In the back row, an ecstatic woman tried to get the attention of an elderly man beside her. He was confused; he had not heard the result.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CShe won!\u8221\'20\'1D the woman shouted, putting her arms around the man\u8217\'20\'19s neck. \u8220\'20\'1CShe won! We won!\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In late October, five days before the trial was set to begin, Bubba Savoy pleaded guilty to striking an inmate in the testicles with his baton, leaving only Ackal to stand trial. During his officers\u8217\'20\'19 testimony, Ackal sat passively, spitting tobacco into a foam cup. Narcotics officers testified that Ackal encouraged them to terrorize the West End, lie in depositions to cover up excessive use of force and beat whomever they liked. \u8220\'20\'1CHe wanted to take the streets back from the [expletive],\u8221\'20\'1D said the former narcotics officer Marion Borel. \u8220\'20\'1CThey were animals,\u8221\'20\'1D explained a former deputy, Jason Comeaux, \u8220\'20\'1Cand they needed to be treated like animals.\u8221\'20\'1D He recalled an interrogation in which a supervising officer pointed at a discoloration on the floor and told the suspect: \u8220\'20\'1CYou see that stain there? That\u8217\'20\'19s from the last [expletive] I shot.\u8221\'20\'1D When asked how it felt, beating up black people, a former officer named Jacob Huckaby called it \u8220\'20\'1Cliberating, I guess, to have a little extra power on somebody.\u8221\'20\'1D One federal prosecutor estimated that hundreds of victims had been beaten on Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s watch.\par \par \uc2 The deputies testified for four days. On the fifth day, Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s lawyer, John McLindon, argued that the narcotics unit was a rogue division within the department, operating without Ackal\u8217\'20\'19s knowledge. He said that no one ever claimed that Ackal himself beat an inmate.\par \par \uc2 After four hours of deliberation, the jury found Ackal not guilty on all counts. \u8220\'20\'1CGod bless it,\u8221\'20\'1D Ackal said, after court was adjourned. \u8220\'20\'1COur judicial system worked today.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Carol Powell Lexing was poleaxed. \u8220\'20\'1CYou\u8217\'20\'19ve got the most corrupt Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department in the state of Louisiana, probably in the country, and you have the deputies testify about all the corruption \u8212\'20\'14 and he still gets off. It\u8217\'20\'19s totally incredible.\u8221\'20\'1D She denied that she was discouraged about her own case, which is scheduled for trial in August. \u8220\'20\'1CI feel encouraged, more than ever. Because now you have the deputies\u8217\'20\'19 testimony about the culture of corruption and violence in the department.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 White was stunned. \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t understand how the jury could have acquitted,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CIt was like they weren\u8217\'20\'19t paying attention.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The effort to recall Ackal failed to secure enough signatures by the deadline. As White awaits the civil trial, he continues to organize protests against Ackal through an organization he has formed to fight police brutality. It\u8217\'20\'19s called Justice for Victor White. I asked whether he thought justice for his son was possible. \u8220\'20\'1CTrue justice,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, \u8220\'20\'1Cwould be to bring my son\u8217\'20\'19s life back.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Ackal, meanwhile, was triumphant. He spoke of cleaning house, of greater transparency. He emphasized the need for better relations between the police and the West End. \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re losing our black children,\u8221\'20\'1D he told a reporter.\par \par \uc2 Then he returned to the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s office, where he was given back his gun.\par \par \uc2 Sign up for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/magazine"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 our newsletter}}}\uc2  to get the best of The \uc2 New York Times Magazine\uc2  delivered to your inbox every week.\par \par \uc2 Nathaniel Rich is a writer at large for the magazine and the author of \u8220\'20\'1COdds Against Tomorrow.\u8221\'20\'1D He last wrote for the magazine about the Aliso Canyon methane-gas leak.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/02/us/louisianian-seeks-answers-in-death-of-son-said-to-have-shot-himself-while-cuffed.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Father Seeks Answers in Death of Son, Who Police Say Shot Himself While Cuffed}}}\par \par \uc2 The Rev. Victor White at the railroad tracks that divide New Iberia. | Ruddy Roye for The New York Times | The Hop-In Texaco station where Little Vic and Isaiah Lewis bought cigarillos before being picked up by the police in New Iberia, La. | Ruddy Roye for The New York Times | The activist Khadijah Rashad (above) at home in Lafayette, La.; Kevin Broussard, a community leader, outside his home in New Iberia. | Ruddy Roye for The New York Times | An emotional Robby Carrier-Bethel (above), a West End resident and neighborhood activist; Little Vic with his niece Aurielle Conley in 2013. | Ruddy Roye for The New York Times. Little Vic: Victor White. | Sheriff Louis Ackal leaving the United States District Court in Lafayette, La., after being arraigned in March 2016. | Duane Fatherree/The Daily Iberian, via Associated Press \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28002s7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
