\par\par \uc2 Talk\par \uc2 Magazine\par {\*\bkmkstart toc17}{\*\bkmkend toc17}\b \uc2 Willie J. Parker Changed His Mind About Abortion\b0\par\par\uc2 Interview by ANA MARIE COX \par \uc2 773 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Your book, \u8220\'20\'1CLife\u8217\'20\'19s Work,\u8221\'20\'1D is rooted in the fact that you have a moral and spiritual argument in favor of abortion rights, and you talk about your shift from someone who, for religious reasons, didn\u8217\'20\'19t want to provide abortion to someone who, for religious reasons, did. Why did you consider that a \u8220\'20\'1Cconversion\u8221\'20\'1D? I had to come to a crisis moment regarding a religious understanding that left me unable to help women when I felt deeply for their situation. So I needed to convert from a religious understanding that left me paralyzed to act on my deepest sense of connection to one that empowered me to do what I felt to be the right thing. It felt as life-altering for me to move from being unable to do abortions to being able to do them as it did to move from being a nonbeliever to becoming a believer.\par \par \uc2 You concede in the book that abortion is, actually, a life-ending process. Here\u8217\'20\'19s the thing: Life is a process, not an event. If I thought I was killing a person, I wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t do abortions. A fetus is not a person; it\u8217\'20\'19s a human entity. In the moral scheme of things, I don\u8217\'20\'19t hold fetal life and the life of a woman equally. I value them both, but in the precedence of things, when a woman comes to me, I find myself unable to demote her aspirations because of the aspirations that someone else has for the fetus that she\u8217\'20\'19s carrying.\par \par \uc2 You talk about \u8220\'20\'1Cverbicaine\u8221\'20\'1D during procedures, or conversations with patients in which you try to lighten the mood, even despite the narrative that makes abortion seem morbid and tragic. Rather than allowing your fear to amplify any sensation that you\u8217\'20\'19re having, you\u8217\'20\'19re having a conversation with me, you\u8217\'20\'19re asking yourself, Why isn\u8217\'20\'19t this guy treating me with judgment and stigma like I expected him to? When I say I\u8217\'20\'19m done and you were expecting something else, you\u8217\'20\'19re now asking me, Are you sure you\u8217\'20\'19re done? It\u8217\'20\'19s over. That\u8217\'20\'19s verbicaine.\par \par \uc2 Along those lines, sometimes you talk about \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Alabama\uc2  football. I think Coach Nick Saban would understand that I\u8217\'20\'19m clued in to something he understands: that in Alabama, football is larger than life.\par \par \uc2 Why do you think that elite white women and the sacralization of motherhood has done some of the most serious damage to abortion access? When women acquiesce to a role determined primarily by their biology of reproduction \u8212\'20\'14 even if it\u8217\'20\'19s unconsciously \u8212\'20\'14 they judge each other for rejecting that primary identity. So if you think that the most essential role for a woman is to procreate, and humanity doesn\u8217\'20\'19t go on unless you do that, then anything to interrupt that process is to be counterintuitive or immoral. The biggest insult is the notion that there\u8217\'20\'19s such a thing as a black genocide, as if the people who care about abortion really care about black women and black babies.\par \par \uc2 Tell me about the connection between your heritage as a descendant of slaves and the idea that abortion is ultimately about ownership of a body. People often struggle with why, as a man, I am deeply committed to feminism, reproductive justice and gender equality. I come from a heritage of people who know what it\u8217\'20\'19s like to have your life controlled by somebody else. What\u8217\'20\'19s most proximate to that reality right now is the direct control of women\u8217\'20\'19s bodies and their reproduction, because if you don\u8217\'20\'19t control your reproduction, you don\u8217\'20\'19t control anything else about your life.\par \par \uc2 I can\u8217\'20\'19t help mentioning that you\u8217\'20\'19re not married, which you say is part of the reason you can do what you do. Is that a choice on your part? Because you seem pretty cool! I jokingly call myself the best-kept secret in Alabama. I didn\u8217\'20\'19t consciously choose not to be partnered or not to have kids \u8212\'20\'14 some things in life should declare themselves. But I try to be of the quality of somebody that I would like to meet. I\u8217\'20\'19ve had some good people in my life; I just haven\u8217\'20\'19t crossed that threshold. But if you know any takers, give me a call.\par \par \uc2 Sign up for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/magazine"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 our newsletter}}}\uc2  to get the best of The \uc2 New York Times Magazine\uc2  delivered to your inbox every week.\par \par \uc2 Interview has been condensed and edited.\par \par \uc2 Willie J. Parker | Raymond McCrea Jones for The New York Times \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28002s4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
