\par\par \uc2 DEAL PROFESSOR\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par {\*\bkmkstart toc25}{\*\bkmkend toc25}\b \uc2 Decade After Meltdown, No Resolution for Fannie and Freddie\b0\par\par\uc2 By STEVEN DAVIDOFF SOLOMON \par \uc2 1,176 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2 , the gigantic government-sponsored mortgage service entity, has guaranteed $1 billion of debt backed by \uc2 Invitation Homes\uc2 , the single-family rental business owned by the giant private equity firm Blackstone. In making the guarantee, Fannie is taking a big leap into the growing home rental market, in which Blackstone is the biggest player. But it's also a sign that the true comeback kids are not the Super Bowl champion New England Patriots but \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  and its cousin, \uc2 Freddie Mac\uc2 , both of which were supposed to be left for dead a decade ago.\par \par \uc2 Fannie and Freddie, as you may remember, were buffeted by the financial crisis. In September 2008, the government put the two entities into receivership and provided a $187.5 billion bailout. The choice was based on a careful legal and economic calculus. The government could not afford to liquidate the entities, which had trillions of dollars in mortgage assets, without further damage to the economy. However, the government also decided not to fully nationalize them. The reasons were political: The government did not want to look as if it owned these two entities, and nationalizing Fannie and Freddie would also have added trillions of dollars in debt to the government's balance sheet, blowing up the national debt ceiling.\par \par \uc2 Fannie and Freddie were, thus, cast into purgatory. They were put under the supervision of the government, but the public still owned 20.1 percent of them.\par \par \uc2 The idea was to gradually run down the entities' debt and come up with a better idea for developing a healthy and growing mortgage market free of the implicit government backing they long enjoyed. At the time, Treasury Secretary \uc2 Henry M. Paulson Jr\uc2 . said ''there is a consensus today that these enterprises pose a systemic risk and they cannot continue in their current form'' and that the government would make a ''grave error'' if they did not ''permanently address'' issues involving the government-sponsored enterprises, or G.S.E.s.\par \par \uc2 Fast-forward almost nine years, and the unfortunate reality is that the G.S.E.s are still the largest suppliers of mortgages today. In 2016, Fannie and Freddie issued mortgage-backed securities worth $974 billion, up 18 percent from 2015.\par \par \uc2 And that brings us back to the Blackstone deal, which illustrates Fannie's mission creep from helping people buy homes to helping people rent them. The guarantee was disclosed with Blackstone's sale of 25 percent of \uc2 Invitation Homes\uc2  in an initial public offering last week. Fannie is making the guarantee on collateral of about 50,000 rented single-family homes that Blackstone bought in foreclosure in the last few years. Never mind that the deal is a big subsidy for Blackstone and \uc2 Invitation Homes\uc2 . The downside -- the government being liable for at least part $1 billion if there is a default -- is real.\par \par \uc2 Fannie's take: ''This transaction is a great opportunity to continue to serve the growing single-family rental market.'' It added that the transaction would provide it with more information on the rental market itself.\par \par \uc2 That's an expensive price tag just to learn about a market.\par \par \uc2 There is no good solution that can satisfy the politics of a national mortgage market. The government is not willing to fully nationalize Fannie and Freddie because it is unwilling to acknowledge or accept the truth that the current mortgage market depends on government support. Private lenders are often unwilling to extend credit to many borrowers for the 30-year fixed-rate terms that have become the standard of American homeownership. Without support, there would be fewer mortgages made, and they would be shorter term and floating-rate, as they are in other countries.\par \par \uc2 Privatization of the G.S.E.s raises the same problems. Fannie and Freddie could be recapitalized and set free in the private markets with strict capital controls and restrictions, turning them into quasi-utilities, but they would still have the government's implicit guarantee. A lot of other ideas have emerged for Fannie and Freddie, including making them share more risk with the private sector, which was the subject of a bill introduced in Congress in December. Another proposal is to merge them and have the combined entity extend mortgage credit while selling off its risks.\par \par \uc2 But none of these solutions are easy, and they all require a hard acknowledgment that the government is committed to supporting the mortgage market.\par \par \uc2 Fannie's and Freddie's only competitor has been the \uc2 Federal Housing Administration\uc2 , which underwrote $245 billion in loans in 2016, up from $59.8 billion in 2007. The F.H.A. has been actively competing to take away \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  and \uc2 Freddie Mac\uc2  business through low down-payment lending. That's hardly a nongovernmental solution.\par \par \uc2 With the election of Donald J. Trump there is some sentiment in the markets that the government will do something with the G.S.E.s. Indeed, the share price of Fannie hit a high of $5.50 a share shortly after the November election, up from about 20 cents during the financial crisis. The increase is a bet that the government will privatize \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  and \uc2 Freddie Mac\uc2  and allow the public holders to keep their shares. That would benefit fund managers like Bruce R. Berkowitz, a big owner of \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  preferred stock. \uc2 Steven T. Mnuchin\uc2 , the nominee for Treasury secretary, was on the \uc2 Sears Holdings\uc2  board with Mr. Berkowitz, and the expectation was that he would favor a spinout and recapitalization.\par \par \uc2 In his Senate confirmation hearings Mr. Mnuchin demurred. Instead, he stated that he never endorsed ''recap and release.''\par \par \uc2 But he added that Fannie and Freddie were among the administration's top 10 priorities.\par \par \uc2 So that leaves the companies still in limbo.\par \par \uc2 If the government really wants to preserve the 30-year mortgage market, it should simply limit these two entities to that loan product, and only that 30-year loan product. Everything else seems not only to preserve the tenuous position of Fannie and Freddie, but also to risk making them just instruments for unrestrained housing policy with lots of unintended consequences and risks.\par \par \uc2 A simple limitation like this would make sense, but don't count on it. Given how hard it is for the government to even acknowledge what the problem is, expect the next administration in four to eight years to still be talking about what to do as Fannie and Freddie continue to be the key players in a multitrillion-dollar mortgage market, while still being government-owned. At least until the next crisis or scandal.\par \par \uc2 Steven Davidoff Solomon is a professor of law at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of California, Berkeley. His columns can be found at nytimes.com/dealbook. Follow @stevendavidoff on \uc2 Twitter\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Steven Davidoff Solomon is a professor of law at the University of California, Berkeley. His columns can be found at nytimes.com/dealbook. Follow @stevendavidoff on Twitter.\par \par \uc2 DRAWING (DRAWING BY HARRY CAMPBELL) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170208ed2800049\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
