\par\par \uc2 TRILOBITES\par \uc2 Science Desk; SECT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc33}{\*\bkmkend toc33}\b \uc2 Newly Discovered Gecko Escapes Danger Naked and Alive\b0\par\par\uc2 By NICHOLAS ST. FLEUR \par \uc2 487 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 The New York Times on the Web\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The fish-scale gecko has a freaky way of eluding danger. When snatched by an attacker, it rips off its scales and skin so it can slip away unscathed. Basically, it streaks to survive.\par \par \uc2 ''It looks like a fish until you grab it, and then it looks like a naked chicken breast,'' said Mark D. Scherz, a doctoral candidate at \uc2 Ludwig Maximilian \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Munich\uc2 . The torn-away scales reveal the gecko's pink flesh, and through its translucent tissue you can see its spine and blood vessels. ''It's bizarre, it's really surprising, and it's quite uncomfortable when you see them,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 It may seem like a gruesome getaway, but it doesn't hurt the lizard. It loses its skin and scales with extreme ease and regenerates them in full a few weeks later. The new scales grow in with a different pattern than the previous ones, but other than that are nearly indistinguishable from the originals.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Scherz and his colleagues discovered a new species of fish-scale gecko in the limestone karst of northern Madagascar, and published their findings Tuesday in the journal \uc2 PeerJ\uc2 . Known as Geckolepis megalepis, it has the largest scales of any fish-scale gecko, some of which measure about 8 percent of its body length. That would be like a person having scales about the size of hands covering parts of the body, according to Mr. Scherz.\par \par \uc2 ''You would think they are somehow protective but really they are a decoy there for blocking the teeth or claws of whatever wants to eat them,'' Mr. Scherz said of the giant scales. ''They get stuck in those jaws or claws and allow the gecko to escape naked and alive.''\par \par \uc2 Fish-scale geckos have long mesmerized herpetologists with their Houdiniesque escapes, but scientists are still not sure how many species of the lizards exist. A genetic analysis in 2013 suggested there might be about 10 species, but, including the new discovery, only five have been recognized so far. Researchers are working to confirm the new species through different methods.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Scherz and his colleagues ascertained that G. megalepis was its own species by using a micro-CT scan to compare its skeletal structure with the previously recognized species of Geckolepis. The subtle differences they found in its eye bones and other parts of its body, in addition to the enormous size of its scales, led them to determine that it was distinct, and the first new Geckolepis to be discovered in about 75 years.\par \par \uc2 Though Mr. Scherz has never grabbed G. megalepis in the wild, he said he had had plenty of experiences trying to snag their kin. Because of their speed, agility and tearaway scales, ''they are nightmares to catch.''\par \par \uc2 Like the Science Times page on \uc2 Facebook\uc2 . | Sign up for the Science Times newsletter.\par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170208ed2800034\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
