\par\par \uc2 Fixes\par \uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc34}{\*\bkmkend toc34}\b \uc2 Preparing Young Americans for a Complex World\b0\par\par\uc2 By DAVID BORNSTEIN \par \uc2 1,702 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2017\par 02:21\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Last year, \uc2 the Council on Foreign Relations\uc2  and National Geographic commissioned a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.cfr.org/society-and-culture/college-aged-students-know-world-survey-global-literacy/p38241"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 survey}}}\uc2  to assess the global literacy of American college students. Over 1,200 people participated; less than 30 percent earned a passing grade. Below are six questions they included, each of which a majority of respondents answered incorrectly. See how you, or your students or children, do. (Answers below.)\par \par \uc2 1. In which of these countries is a majority of the population Muslim?\par \par \uc2 a) South Africa\par \par \uc2 b) Armenia\par \par \uc2 c) India\par \par \uc2 d) Indonesia\par \par \uc2 2. Which language is spoken by the most people in the world as their primary language?\par \par \uc2 a) Russian\par \par \uc2 b) Mandarin Chinese\par \par \uc2 c) English\par \par \uc2 d) Arabic\par \par \uc2 3. Which country is the largest trading partner of the United States, based on the total dollar value of goods and services?\par \par \uc2 a) Canada\par \par \uc2 b) China\par \par \uc2 c) Mexico\par \par \uc2 d) Saudi Arabia\par \par \uc2 4. Approximately what percentage of the United States {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/f/federal_budget_us/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 federal budget}}}\uc2  is spent on foreign aid?\par \par \uc2 a) 1 percent\par \par \uc2 b) 5 percent\par \par \uc2 c) 12 percent\par \par \uc2 d) 30 percent\par \par \uc2 e) 40 percent\par \par \uc2 5. Which countries is the United States bound by treaty to protect if they are attacked? (select all that apply)\par \par \uc2 a) Canada\par \par \uc2 b) China\par \par \uc2 c) Japan\par \par \uc2 d) Mexico\par \par \uc2 e) North Korea\par \par \uc2 f) Russia\par \par \uc2 g) South Korea\par \par \uc2 h) Turkey\par \par \uc2 6. True or False: Over the past five years, the number of Mexicans leaving the United States and returning to Mexico has been greater than the number of Mexicans entering the United States.\par \par \uc2 Why is it so important to understand the world and the United States\u8217\'20\'19 role in it today?\par \par \uc2 To begin with, the American economy is inextricably linked to the global economy. It\u8217\'20\'19s estimated that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://asiasociety.org/files/uploads/127files/JobsFinal.png"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 one-fifth}}}\uc2  of jobs here are now tied to international trade. Moreover, many of the world\u8217\'20\'19s major challenges \u8212\'20\'14 climate change, instability in financial markets, food and water insecurity, infectious diseases, migration, war and terrorism \u8212\'20\'14 are complex, interdependent and borderless. And with 40 million foreign-born residents, the United States is itself a global society with deep emotional ties to many nations and cultures. To survive and thrive, Americans have to learn how to manage greater complexity and collaborate across lines of difference.\par \par \uc2 During the Obama administration, the federal{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www2.ed.gov/about/inits/ed/internationaled/international-strategy-2012-16.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  Department of Education}}}\uc2  recognized this imperative. Since 2012, its strategy has emphasized \u8220\'20\'1C{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sites.ed.gov/international/global-and-cultural-competency/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 global and cultural competency}}}\uc2 \u8221\'20\'1D as a core educational priority. In 2018, the Program for International Student Assessment, an international testing system that sets benchmarks for student performance in which the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/education_department/index.html?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Department of Education}}}\uc2  participates, will add {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.oecd.org/pisa/oecd-proposes-new-approach-to-assess-young-peoples-understanding-of-global-issues-and-attitudes-toward-cultural-diversity-and-tolerance.htm"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 global competence}}}\uc2  as a new domain.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, many American schools have remained {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://asiasociety.org/mapping-nation/about?_ga=1.81117716.2068574226.1486409919"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 poorly prepared}}}\uc2  to deliver education in \u8220\'20\'1Cglobal competence\u8221\'20\'1D ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://asiasociety.org/files/book-globalcompetence.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 defined}}}\uc2  by American education leaders as \u8220\'20\'1Cthe capacity and disposition to understand and act on issues of global significance.\u8221\'20\'1D) The focus on traditional achievement and test scores has narrowed the delivery of instruction at a time when students need to learn to think more broadly. In the wake of \u8220\'20\'1CBrexit\u8221\'20\'1D and the election of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/person/donald-trump?inline=nyt-per"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Donald Trump}}}\uc2  (both far more popular among older voters than among the young) \u8212\'20\'14 and amid the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.economist.com/news/international/21710276-all-around-world-nationalists-are-gaining-ground-why-league-nationalists"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 global rise of nationalist movements}}}\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 schools need to help students navigate the forces shaping the world they will inherit.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat are the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://static1.squarespace.com/static/541b08ace4b03814779bda86/t/5425b0ade4b0a13786495f02/1411756205854/World+Savvy+Global+Competence+Matrix+2014.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 values, attitudes, skills and behaviors}}}\uc2  that must be cultivated if we\u8217\'20\'19re going to live in a peaceful world?\u8221\'20\'1D asked Dana Mortenson, one of the -founders of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.worldsavvy.org/home"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 World Savvy}}}\uc2 , an organization that has worked with thousands of teachers to integrate global competence into their lessons.\par \par \uc2 What\u8217\'20\'19s needed is not just scoring well on standardized tests. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s an openness to new opportunities and ideas,\u8221\'20\'1D she added. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s a desire to engage. It\u8217\'20\'19s self-awareness about culture and respect for different perspectives. It\u8217\'20\'19s comfort with ambiguity. It\u8217\'20\'19s the skill to investigate the world through questions. Empathy and humility are big pieces of all of it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Teaching these higher-level skills and attitudes might seem a tall order for schools that struggle with the basics. But World Savvy has seen {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.worldsavvy.org/results/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 impressive results}}}\uc2  among its partner schools, a majority of them in high-poverty areas. By raising the bar, teachers say, it becomes easier to engage students.\par \par \uc2 That\u8217\'20\'19s been the experience of Carla Kelly, a special-education teacher at DeWitt Clinton High School in the Bronx who completed a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.worldsavvy.org/certificate-program"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Global Competence Certificate}}}\uc2 , a 15-month graduate-level program developed by World Savvy, the Asia Society and Teachers College at \uc2 Columbia \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI saw that I needed to teach so that my students could contribute anywhere in the world,\u8221\'20\'1D Kelly said.\par \par \uc2 Kelly teaches a variety of subjects \u8212\'20\'14 including science, health, Spanish and life skills \u8212\'20\'14 in a school that has students and faculty members from 46 countries. She tries to integrate global competence {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://vimeo.com/106641394"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 concepts}}}\uc2  throughout her teaching.\par \par \uc2 In a unit on nutrition, for instance, students explore foods from around the world, graphing diets against life spans. \u8220\'20\'1CWe compared diets high in starchy vegetables with places where they eat dark green or sea vegetables,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. The connections the students drew were powerful: They learned that people in China live longer than black people in America. They discovered that wherever the American diet was introduced, life spans declined.\par \par \uc2 In a unit on death, Kelly added an exploration of 11 funeral rites. Students learned that in Ghana, caskets are woven in the shape of objects beloved by the deceased; in South Korea, a person\u8217\'20\'19s remains may be pressed into jewelry; and in Tibet, the mountaintop \u8220\'20\'1Csky burial\u8221\'20\'1D in the open allows a dead person\u8217\'20\'19s soul to exit the body and be reincarnated. \u8220\'20\'1CI asked them to choose five rituals that would be a good fit with their values and cultures,\u8221\'20\'1D Kelly said. \u8220\'20\'1CI wanted them to make connections, to see how other cultures see life and death.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CEvery class that I\u8217\'20\'19ve revised to include international representation,\u8221\'20\'1D she added. \u8220\'20\'1CI found that the students made more connections because they had a cultural anchor. And when I assessed what they retained I got content-specific vocabulary because it stuck, especially where they could see aspects of themselves and of people they knew. And the questions I got were better. I stopped getting \u8216\'20\'18what\u8217\'20\'19 questions and started getting \u8216\'20\'18why\u8217\'20\'19 questions, and \u8216\'20\'18what if\u8217\'20\'19 questions.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 At Mill Valley Middle School in California, two teachers, Rod Septka and Maggie Front, working with more affluent students, have seen this approach evoke a similar response. When the recent drought in California was daily news, they looked at how people in the state were conserving water. Then they examined how people cope with water-related problems in Bangladesh, Israel, Sudan, Bolivia, China, Ethiopia, Indonesia, Peru and Syria. The students did extensive research and data gathering. One student was astonished that so many people around the world couldn\u8217\'20\'19t just go into their kitchen and get water from a tap. Then the water crisis in Flint, Mich., became news, and they looked at water access in terms of wealth and race. That led a student who had been previously disengaged in school to discover her activist voice, said Front. And studying water rights brought her to a related concern: women\u8217\'20\'19s rights.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CA lot of this helps the kids to understand what actions they can take toward solving world issues,\u8221\'20\'1D said Front. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s not the mission to create activism, but that tends to come out of it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In a culminating experience, the students, working in twos, carried five-gallon buckets of water for half a mile. They experimented with ways to do it efficiently, while minimizing spillage, and collected data about time, distance and volume to calculate how long it would take them to provide water for their family. \u8220\'20\'1CIt was a lot harder than they thought,\u8221\'20\'1D said Septka. \u8220\'20\'1CIt gave them a newfound appreciation for people who have to do things differently than we do.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Each of these teachers described learning alongside the students, making mistakes, and improving their own global competence in the process.\par \par \uc2 For now, teacher education that is focused on this area remains at a nascent stage, says William Gaudelli, an associate professor at Teachers College at \uc2 Columbia \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  who is a founder of the college\u8217\'20\'19s Global Competence Certificate program and the author of a book titled \u8220\'20\'1C{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.routledge.com/Global-Citizenship-Education-Everyday-Transcendence/Gaudelli/p/book/9781138925946"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Global Citizenship Education: Everyday Transcendence}}}\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBy and large, our curriculum in the United States is a European great civilization approach \u8212\'20\'14 Plato to \uc2 NATO\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 with some add-ons for cultural diversity,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CBut the condition we live in is fundamentally global. There\u8217\'20\'19s literally nothing that\u8217\'20\'19s not connected far beyond our borders. When people 100 years look back on our generation, they\u8217\'20\'19re going to wonder: How did they know so much about what was going on and do so little to educate about it?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 For Mortenson, a core hurdle is moving beyond the \u8220\'20\'1Caversion to complexity in our education system.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe system was set up that way because the idea was to standardize knowledge,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CThat was appropriate when someone was being trained for a job they might hold for 40 or 50 years. But the world has changed in such profound ways that developing an understanding of complexity is paramount. Whatever the policy, the idea that things are simple, or black and white, and we can put a blanket on them and feel that it\u8217\'20\'19s going to have the desired impact \u8212\'20\'14 that idea can become very dangerous.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 *Answers, with percentage of respondents who gave the correct answer.\par \par \uc2 1. d (29 percent)\par \par \uc2 Experiene2. b (49 percent)\par \par \uc2 3. a (10 percent)\par \par \uc2 4. a (12 percent)\par \par \uc2 5. a (47 percent), c (28 percent), g (34 percent), h (14 percent)\par \par \uc2 6. True (34 percent)\par \par \uc2 Join {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.facebook.com/home.php#!/pages/Social-Change-New-York-Times/147881585260868"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Fixes on Facebook}}}\uc2  and follow updates on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/nytimesfixes"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 twitter.com/nytimesfixes}}}\uc2 . To receive email alerts for Fixes columns, sign up {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://eepurl.com/ABIxL"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 here.}}}\par \par \uc2 Follow The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  Opinion section on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/nytopinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Facebook}}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/NYTOpinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Twitter}}}\uc2  (@NYTOpinion), and sign up for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/opiniontoday/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Opinion Today newsletter}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 David Bornstein is the author of \u8220\'20\'1CHow to Change the World\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1CThe Price of a Dream: The Story of the \uc2 Grameen Bank\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D and co-author of \u8220\'20\'1CSocial Entrepreneurship: What Everyone Needs to Know.\u8221\'20\'1D He is a co-founder of the Solutions Journalism Network, which supports rigorous reporting about responses to social problems.\par \par \uc2 Getty Images \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170208ed28002js\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
