\par\par \uc2 Op-Ed Contributor\par \uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc35}{\*\bkmkend toc35}\b \uc2 Mike Pence\uc2 , the Tiebreaker\b0\par\par\uc2 By JOEL K. GOLDSTEIN \par \uc2 714 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2017\par 18:36\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The modern-day vice president serves primarily as a close presidential adviser and assistant. The vice president\u8217\'20\'19s move from Capitol Hill to the White House has allowed the office to become a significant institution. But this week, \uc2 Mike Pence\uc2  reminded Americans of an older role the vice president also sometimes serves: that of legislative officer who can preside over the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Vice President Pence on Tuesday {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/us/politics/betsy-devos-education-secretary-confirmed.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&clickSource=story-heading&module=first-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 saved the administration}}}\uc2  and Betsy DeVos, President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s nominee for secretary of education, from an embarrassing defeat. It was a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/us/politics/mike-pence-tie-break-betsy-devos.html?rref=collection%2Fnewseventcollection%2FThe%20Trump%20White%20House&action=click&contentCollection=Politics&module=Collection&region=Marginalia&src=me&version=newsevent&pgtype=article"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 historic moment}}}\uc2 : None of Mr. Pence\u8217\'20\'19s 47 predecessors has ever cast a tiebreaking vote to install a cabinet officer over the opposition of 50 percent of the Senate.\par \par \uc2 The close split in the Senate and controversial nature of the DeVos nomination gave Mr. Pence this unique opportunity on Day 18 of his vice presidency. By contrast, his predecessor, \uc2 Joseph R. Biden Jr\uc2 ., served 2,922 days in the nation\u8217\'20\'19s second office (after having been elected to seven terms in the Senate) without getting to break a single Senate tie. Mr. Biden was one of only 12 vice presidents not to break a tie of any sort.\par \par \uc2 The tiebreaking performances of some vice presidents contributed to the familiar lore disparaging the second office. Vice President John C. Calhoun cast the decisive vote to defeat President Andrew Jackson\u8217\'20\'19s nomination of his close ally, Martin Van Buren, to be ambassador to Britain in 1832. The setback to Van Buren\u8217\'20\'19s career was only temporary; the following year he replaced Calhoun as Jackson\u8217\'20\'19s vice president and, four years later, became president.\par \par \uc2 Charles G. Dawes began his vice presidency in March 1925 by alienating the Senate with an Inauguration Day lecture criticizing its rules. Less than a week into his vice presidency, he was napping in his hotel room when the Senate deadlocked on President Calvin Coolidge\u8217\'20\'19s nomination of Charles Warren to be his attorney general. By the time Dawes arrived to break the tie, a vote had shifted against Warren, defeating the nomination, leaving Dawes embarrassed and Pence with the history-making honor he achieved yesterday.\par \par \uc2 The close party division in the Senate and the controversy over some other presidential nominations may give Vice President Pence other opportunities to break Senate ties. In fact, some of his recent predecessors, like Dick Cheney (8), Al Gore (4) and George H.W. Bush (7) cast decisive votes, in some instances on important matters. The close association between the president and the vice president now effectively allows the administration to prevail in the Senate if it can produce an even split. The Constitution confers the vice president\u8217\'20\'19s power to break Senate ties. And Mr. Pence, and his successors, can be expected to exercise that prerogative when it serves the administration\u8217\'20\'19s interests.\par \par \uc2 Ultimately, Mr. Pence\u8217\'20\'19s importance will turn on his ability to serve as a presidential adviser and operator. That new definition of the office began with the vice presidency of Walter F. Mondale and continued during the next five presidencies as Mr. Bush, Dan Quayle, Mr. Gore, Mr. Cheney and Mr. Biden acted as close presidential counselors and assistants. Six presidents, evenly divided between the two parties, have followed this new vice-presidential model because they have seen the value an able adviser and operator can provide.\par \par \uc2 Whether Vice President Pence achieves similar success will depend on President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s willingness to continue to follow this new model (as he so far seems inclined to do), the continuing relationship between Mr. Trump and Mr. Pence and the vice president\u8217\'20\'19s skill in handling his duties. Those are questions for the future.\par \par \uc2 Follow The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  Opinion section on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/nytopinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Facebook}}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/NYTOpinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Twitter}}}\uc2  (@NYTOpinion), and sign up for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/opiniontoday/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Opinion Today newsletter}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Joel K. Goldstein, a law professor at Saint Louis \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  School of Law, is the author of \u8220\'20\'1CThe White House Vice Presidency: The Path to Significance, Mondale to Biden.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/us/politics/betsy-devos-education-secretary-confirmed.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Betsy DeVos Confirmed as Education Secretary; Pence Breaks Tie}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/07/us/politics/mike-pence-tie-break-betsy-devos.html"