\par\par \uc2 EDITORIAL\par \uc2 Editorial Desk; SECTA\par {\*\bkmkstart toc36}{\*\bkmkend toc36}\b \uc2 Mr. Trump's Real Fear: The Courts\b0\par\par\uc2 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD \par \uc2 736 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2017\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 20\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 CORRECTION APPENDEDWhen President Trump doesn't get what he wants, he tends to look for someone to blame -- crooked pollsters, fraudulent voters, lying journalists. Anyone who questions him or his actions becomes his foe.\par \par \uc2 Over the past few days, he's added an entire branch of the federal government to his enemies list.\par \par \uc2 On Friday, a federal judge in Seattle, James Robart, blocked Mr. Trump's executive order barring entry to refugees and immigrants from seven predominantly Muslim nations. The next day the president mocked Judge Robart, a George W. Bush appointee, in a statement on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  as a ''so-called judge'' who had made a ''ridiculous'' ruling.\par \par \uc2 That was bad enough, but on Sunday, Mr. Trump's taunts became more chilling. ''Just cannot believe a judge would put our country in such peril,'' he tweeted. ''If something happens blame him and court system. People pouring in. Bad!''\par \par \uc2 Where to begin? In the same week that he announced his nominee for the Supreme Court, the president of the United States pre-emptively accused not only a judge, but the whole judicial branch -- the most dependable check on his power -- of abetting the murder of Americans by terrorists. It's reasonable to wonder whether Mr. Trump is anticipating a way to blame meddling courts for any future attack.\par \par \uc2 There was, in fact, a terrorist attack shortly after Mr. Trump issued his immigration order: a white supremacist, officials say, armed himself with an assault rifle and stormed a mosque in Quebec City, slaughtering six Muslims during their prayers. Mr. Trump has not said a word about that massacre -- although he was quick to tell America on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  to ''get smart'' when, a few days later, an Egyptian man wielding a knife attacked a military patrol in Paris, injuring one soldier.\par \par \uc2 In the dark world that Mr. Trump and his top adviser, Stephen Bannon, inhabit, getting ''smart'' means shutting down immigration from countries that have not been responsible for a single fatal attack in the United States in more than two decades. As multiple national security experts have said, the order would, if anything, increase the terrorism threat to Americans. And contrary to Mr. Trump's claim, no one is ''pouring in'' to America. Refugees and other immigrants already undergo a thorough, multilayered vetting process that can take up to two years.\par \par \uc2 But Mr. Trump's threats are based on fear, not rationality, which is the realm of the courts.\par \par \uc2 Judge Robart is not the first judge Mr. Trump has smeared. During the presidential campaign last year, he pursued bigoted attacks on a federal judge presiding over a class-action fraud lawsuit against his so-called Trump \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The judge, Gonzalo Curiel, could not be impartial, Mr. Trump claimed, because he ''happens to be, we believe, Mexican,'' and Mr. Trump had promised to build a border wall and deport millions of undocumented Mexican immigrants. (Judge Curiel was born in Indiana, and Mr. Trump settled the lawsuit in November for $25 million.)\par \par \uc2 Coming from a candidate, this was merely outrageous; coming from the president, it is a threat to the rule of law. Judges can now assume that if they disagree with him, they will face his wrath -- and perhaps that of his millions of \uc2 Twitter\uc2  followers.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Trump's repeated attacks on the judiciary are all the more ominous given his efforts to intimidate and undermine the news media and Congress's willingness to neutralize itself, rather than hold him to account.\par \par \uc2 Today, at least, the new administration is following the rules and appealing Judge Robart's decision to the federal appeals court. But tomorrow Mr. Trump may decide -- out of anger at a ruling or sheer spite at a judge -- that he doesn't need to obey a court order. Who will stop him then?\par \par \uc2 Follow The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  Opinion section on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Twitter\uc2  (@NYTOpinion), and sign up for the Opinion Today newsletter.\par \par \uc2 Correction: February 8, 2017, Wednesday\par \par \uc2 This article has been revised to reflect the following correction: An editorial on Tuesday about President Trump's ban on travelers and refugees from seven predominantly Muslim nations incorrectly described attacks in the United States by people from those nations. There have been no such fatal attacks in more than two decades, but there have been nonfatal attacks.\par \par \uc2 DRAWING (DRAWING BY JUN CEN) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170208ed270002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
