\par\par \uc2 Theater\par {\*\bkmkstart toc38}{\*\bkmkend toc38}\b \uc2 Broadway\u8217\'20\'19s Bathroom Problem: Have to Go? Hurry Up, or Hold It\b0\par\par\uc2 By MICHAEL PAULSON \par \uc2 1,531 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2017\par 17:26\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 A revolution is taking place on Broadway, and not just at \u8220\'20\'1CHamilton.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Theater owners, confronted day after day by long lines of women (and, sometimes, men) clogging lobbies and snaking down stairwells while nervously waiting for an available bathroom, are excavating, annexing, converting and renovating their buildings to remedy the chronic inconvenience. The biggest landlords are also retraining ushers, experimenting with new methods of crowd control, and even reversing the genders on restrooms.\par \par \uc2 Broadway has never been busier \u8212\'20\'14 last season brought a record audience of 13.3 million people \u8212\'20\'14 and that means added pressure on its theaters. And nowhere are the grand but geriatric buildings weaker than in their paucity of bathroom facilities, particularly for women.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI hate to say this, but it\u8217\'20\'19s the standard everywhere,\u8221\'20\'1D Amy Braswell, 41, from Abingdon, Va., said while lined up for the bathroom in the mobbed upstairs lobby at the Brooks Atkinson Theater during intermission at \u8220\'20\'1CWaitress\u8221\'20\'1D last week. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m just used to waiting.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Kate Hellman, 30, from Olathe, Kan., agreed: \u8220\'20\'1CPatience is definitely a virtue. Obviously, it would be great to have more stalls.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Most Broadway theaters were built nearly a century ago, when consumer expectations and habits were different, and many of the buildings are landmarks, making structural change difficult.\par \par \uc2 Several factors work against the theater owners: Broadway houses seat from 600 to 1,900 people, many of whom want to relieve themselves during the same 15-minute period. Audiences are now 67 percent female, according to the Broadway League. And liquid consumption \u8212\'20\'14 both hydration and libation \u8212\'20\'14 has also changed.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CPeople didn\u8217\'20\'19t eat and drink like they do today,\u8221\'20\'1D said \uc2 Robert E. Wankel\uc2 , the president of the Shubert Organization, which owns or operates 17 of Broadway\u8217\'20\'19s 40 houses. \u8220\'20\'1CNow everybody runs to the restroom. It\u8217\'20\'19s a part of going to the theater.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As a result, theater owners have been overhauling their buildings one by one.\par \par \uc2 The Hudson Theater, last used for Broadway shows 49 years ago, is reopening this weekend (for \u8220\'20\'1CSunday in the Park With George,\u8221\'20\'1D starring Jake Gyllenhaal) after a major renovation that included a significant increase in toilets, from 12 to 27 (16 for women, 11 for men). The theater\u8217\'20\'19s new operator, the Ambassador Theater Group, converted an old men\u8217\'20\'19s smoking lounge into restrooms, knocking through a wall to gain space, and then demolished a dress-circle level area previously used for air conditioning units to add more stalls.\par \par \uc2 The Helen Hayes Theater, now being renovated after being sold to the nonprofit Second Stage Theater, is also getting a major upgrade: The cramped women\u8217\'20\'19s room, which had five toilets, has been demolished and will reopen with 10; the men\u8217\'20\'19s room, which had one toilet and three urinals, will reopen with two toilets and four urinals. The theater is also adding two bathrooms with access for those with disabilities.\par \par \uc2 And more is ahead: Jujamcyn Theaters plans to add three additional women\u8217\'20\'19s stalls, one men\u8217\'20\'19s stall and three urinals to the St. James, as well as reconfigure that building\u8217\'20\'19s lobby to allow bathroom lines to flow better, as it expands the theater between a run of \u8220\'20\'1CPresent Laughter\u8221\'20\'1D and the much-anticipated stage adaptation of \u8220\'20\'1CFrozen.\u8221\'20\'1D \uc2 The Nederlander Organization\uc2  expects to renovate the Palace Theater, currently home to a revival of \u8220\'20\'1CSunset Boulevard,\u8221\'20\'1D as part of a development project that will involve lifting the theater 29 feet and will create more space for bathrooms. And the Shuberts anticipate renovations at three theaters: the Ambassador, the Cort and the Lyceum.\par \par \uc2 The challenge is clearly visible these days at many shows, including \u8220\'20\'1CWaitress,\u8221\'20\'1D a hit musical that, with a story about empowerment, a song about pregnancy testing and a joke about estrogen asphyxiation, is drawing a heavily female crowd.\par \par \uc2 At one evening performance last week, the line for women zigzagged from one side of the mezzanine to the other and back again, contained by ropes, organized by ushers, overflowing into stairwells, hemmed in by a bar. Two ushers controlled the line; a third stood at the bathroom entrance directing women to specific stalls.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe do this eight times a week,\u8221\'20\'1D an usher said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe have a system.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As the lights dimmed for Act II to begin, an usher sent six women still waiting in line to the men\u8217\'20\'19s room.\par \par \uc2 That scene has been playing out throughout the run of the show \u8212\'20\'14 at a matinee performance last year, several women sitting in the orchestra section bolted down the aisle as soon as \u8220\'20\'1CBad Idea,\u8221\'20\'1D the final song in the first act, began to play; during the intermission, ushers were radioing stage managers to give updates about the line progress.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis is dangerous \u8212\'20\'14 a man almost pushed me down the stairs,\u8221\'20\'1D Bonnie Young of Philadelphia said as she slowly moved ahead. Carol Kauffmann, also of Philadelphia, said she was going to dash over to a nearby restaurant and offer them $10 to let her use the bathroom. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s my birthday, and my girlfriends brought me to a fancy lunch,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CI have to pee.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Most Broadway theaters were built in the early 20th century, and featured spaces where men could smoke and women could rest or touch up their makeup, but limited stalls, because women, based on the customs of the times and the complexity of their garments (corsets, anyone?), were less likely to use public toilets, theater owners say.\par \par \uc2 Now, when there is a break between productions, and sometimes even while a longtime show is still running, the theater owners try to add stalls. Shubert has increased the number of women\u8217\'20\'19s stalls in its houses over time to 265 from 114. Jujamcyn added 46 women\u8217\'20\'19s stalls at its five houses.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s an issue in every theater, for every theater owner,\u8221\'20\'1D said Nick Scandalios, the executive vice president of Nederlander, which has nine Broadway theaters. Nederlander has just finished adding 14 stalls at the Minskoff Theater \u8212\'20\'14 not an easy task to pull off while the long-running \u8220\'20\'1CThe Lion King\u8221\'20\'1D fills the house six days a week.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CEvery time we restore or renovate, we\u8217\'20\'19re always adding as many stalls as we can within the limitation of the square footage we have, but you can never add enough,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Scandalios said.\par \par \uc2 The availability and accessibility of restrooms in public spaces have become public policy issues, prompting changes in design practices and a flurry of so-called \u8220\'20\'1Cpotty parity\u8221\'20\'1D laws.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis is an issue that discriminates against women, who have to spend most of the intermission waiting in line and can\u8217\'20\'19t enjoy the other amenities,\u8221\'20\'1D said Kathryn H. Anthony, a specialist on gender-related design issues at the architecture school of the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. \u8220\'20\'1CAnd it\u8217\'20\'19s not a pleasant way to end Act I, from a psychological point of view \u8212\'20\'14 having to dart to the restroom to try to avoid the line does divert your attention from what\u8217\'20\'19s onstage.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The issue is forcing creative approaches. At the 1,079-seat Gerald Schoenfeld Theater, Shubert spent months digging beneath the orchestra and under an alley, even building a ramp for an excavating machine, to find space to increase the number of women\u8217\'20\'19s stalls from 8 to 20.\par \par \uc2 A mezzanine locker room for ushers was turned into a women\u8217\'20\'19s room. The theater got permission from the city\u8217\'20\'19s Buildings Department to relocate fire protection equipment to create more space, and added a staircase in the hope of reducing congestion.\par \par \uc2 Jujamcyn added more women\u8217\'20\'19s stalls to each of its theaters during renovations from 1990 to 2000. At the Al Hirschfeld Theater, the company switched the bathrooms, converting the large men\u8217\'20\'19s room in the basement, which had a smoking lounge and a bar, into a women\u8217\'20\'19s room, and remaking the upstairs women\u8217\'20\'19s room, which had few stalls but many counters and mirrors for nose-powdering, into a men\u8217\'20\'19s room.\par \par \uc2 Some patrons, meanwhile, have resorted to creative alternatives.\par \par \uc2 Carter A. Prescott, a regular theatergoer, will seek out a nearby \uc2 Starbucks\uc2  or a hotel bar \u8212\'20\'14 she likes the Crowne Plaza Times Square \u8212\'20\'14 in a pinch, finding it faster than lining up with fellow audience members.\par \par \uc2 Inside the theater, she said: \u8220\'20\'1CYou just see endless women, and no men of course, and then some women go into the men\u8217\'20\'19s room. You don\u8217\'20\'19t want to get to the point where you\u8217\'20\'19re wearing Depends.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Joshua Barone contributed reporting.\par \par \uc2 * Broadway Defies the Odds With Another Record-Breaking Season\par \par \uc2 * The Senate Bathroom Angle\par \par \uc2 * Making Bathrooms More \u8216\'20\'18Accommodating\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 * A \u8216\'20\'18Women Only\u8217\'20\'19 Restroom Renovation Tips the Balance at Grand Central\par \par \uc2 A line for the women\u8217\'20\'19s restroom at the Imperial Theater, where \u8220\'20\'1CLes Mis\u233\'00\'E9rables\u8221\'20\'1D played last year, extended down the hallway and staircase and into the lobby at a performance. | Hilary Swift for The New York Times | A line for the women\u8217\'20\'19s restroom before a recent matinee performance of \u8220\'20\'1CWaitress\u8221\'20\'1D at the Brooks Atkinson Theater. | Rebecca Smeyne for The New York Times | A recently renovated women\u8217\'20\'19s restroom at the Schoenfeld Theater. | Sara Krulwich/The New York Times \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170207ed27008sp\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
