\par\par \uc2 The Public Editor\par \uc2 Public Editor\par {\*\bkmkstart toc42}{\*\bkmkend toc42}\b \uc2 When Details in a Story Can Put People at Risk\b0\par\par\uc2 By LIZ SPAYD \par \uc2 835 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2017\par 08:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 When reporters are writing about private individuals they don\u8217\'20\'19t typically publish the person\u8217\'20\'19s exact street address. First, it\u8217\'20\'19s usually irrelevant to the article, and more crucially, announcing the home address of anyone can be dangerous. Here\u8217\'20\'19s the guidance from The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  stylebook: \u8220\'20\'1CIn writing about a person whose family might face harassment or harm, consider a general neighborhood reference instead. If an exact address seems newsworthy because of a crime or other visible event, carefully consider the potential for harm before publishing it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 That wasn\u8217\'20\'19t the approach taken when the Times reporter Patricia Leigh Brown {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/03/education/edlife/daca-undocumented-university-of-california-merced-fiat-lux-scholars.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 described}}}\uc2  academic life for some undocumented students on the campus of the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of California, Merced. The 22 students, mostly first-generation immigrants from impoverished families, share life together on the top two floors of a single dorm. And each time Brown described a student, she included their dorm room number, adding some visual geography as she described their modestly decorated surroundings.\par \par \uc2 Brown writes an engaging piece, not only about these students\u8217\'20\'19 unlikely path to a campus of an acclaimed \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but also about education policy, which is not always easy to make engaging. Brown shows it\u8217\'20\'19s possible.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s too bad that an otherwise strong piece was weakened by a decision to describe the students not just by their name, but by what is essentially their home address.\par \par \uc2 Two \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2  administrators I contacted, both of whom were involved with The Times\u8217\'20\'19s story, said they believe that inclusion of the dorm name and room numbers puts the undocumented students in danger.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe didn\u8217\'20\'19t think she (the reporter) would even use the name of the residence hall,\u8221\'20\'1D said Alejandro Delgadillo, who oversees services for undocumented students on the campus. \u8220\'20\'1CTo include the room numbers puts a target on these students. We engage with a great deal of media and never felt that students were at risk by the information that we were sharing. This really violated that.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Charles Nies, the interim vice chancellor for student affairs, said one can look no further than the comments on the story to see the animosity directed toward this group.\par \par \uc2 He\u8217\'20\'19s right. Here\u8217\'20\'19s one commenter who goes by \u8220\'20\'1CThe cat in the hat\u8221\'20\'1D: \u8220\'20\'1CMy neighbor\u8217\'20\'19s spending 50k a year to send her daughter to college. But don\u8217\'20\'19t worry, Mexicans. I\u8217\'20\'19m sure she\u8217\'20\'19ll be happy to spend another 50k of her own hard earned money so you that undocumented saints can have one as well!\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Several college professors wrote in, as did many Times readers. Lali DeRosier from Melbourne, Fla. wrote:\par \par \uc2 I am shocked and dismayed that the piece identifies undocumented students, and that it made public their dormitory building and room numbers. This is sensitive information that should have been protected. By publishing this information, you have put these students at great risk, especially given the attitude of the current administration to undocumented people.\par \par \uc2 All of of the students in the piece agreed to the use of their names, and those who were photographed signed a release. The students also gave their dorm numbers, but according to Delgadillo, they did not realize the reporter was going to use them in the story.\par \par \uc2 The reporter told me that she now regrets the decision. \u8220\'20\'1CI am a mother myself and the last thing I\u8217\'20\'19d want to do is jeopardize any student\u8217\'20\'19s safety or give them cause for alarm,\u8221\'20\'1D said Brown. \u8220\'20\'1CIn hindsight, understanding that the room numbers seem to have caused distress and concern, I, of course, would not have used them. I gave the students the option of not using their full names (none of them took it) and did ask for their room numbers, even double-checking them with some.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Jane Karr, an education editor at The Times, said she is comfortable with the decision to publish the dorm numbers and does not believe that they are putting the students in danger.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHaving a room number did not give you more access to the students,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s a secure building.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Phil Corbett\uc2 , associate managing editor for standards, said he too understood the decision to use the dorm address, saying that, while The Times doesn\u8217\'20\'19t want to create unwarranted risk, the details are what make a narrative compelling.\par \par \uc2 Sometimes that\u8217\'20\'19s true. But in this case, the dorm numbers were not make-or-break details. Since the students agreed to give their names, and signed a release for the use of their image, then I think The Times is certainly within good journalistic standards to use them. But saying who lives behind which door seems like an unecessary intrusion that didn\u8217\'20\'19t help the students or the story.\par \par \uc2 Follow the public editor on \uc2 Twitter{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/spaydl"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 @spaydl}}}\uc2  and reach her by email at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:public@nytimes.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 public@nytimes.com}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A sculpture entitled \u8220\'20\'1CBeginnings\u8221\'20\'1D on the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of California, Merced campus. | U.C. Merced \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170207ed27004bl\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
