\par\par \uc2 Feature\par \uc2 Magazine\par {\*\bkmkstart toc44}{\*\bkmkend toc44}\b \uc2 How a Fractious Women\u8217\'20\'19s Movement Came to Lead the Left\b0\par\par\uc2 By AMANDA HESS \par \uc2 5,963 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Hours before the start of the Women\u8217\'20\'19s March on Washington on Jan. 21, every Metro car leading to the National Mall was packed so tight that it could take on no more riders. At station after station, the train doors would open, and the passengers would look out on throngs of fellow protesters \u8212\'20\'14 women, men, children, babies, the occasional dog \u8212\'20\'14 waiting on the platform. As people emerged from underground into the morning air, it was hard to tell where to go, so they found their way by gauging the human density, moving until they reached a spot so full of people that they could no longer move at all. There was an enormous rally happening somewhere in there \u8212\'20\'14 activists and celebrities speaking into microphones \u8212\'20\'14 but much of the crowd couldn\u8217\'20\'19t see or hear anything except rumbling waves of cheers. By the time they were meant to march, the crowd was so large that it already stretched across the entire route, from the rally site near the Capitol to the Ellipse near the White House.\par \par \uc2 The signs they carried spoke to any number of issues: immigration, abortion, race, the environment, inequality, the new president. REFUGEES WELCOME, KEEP YOUR LAWS OUT OF MY VAGINA, BLACK LIVES MATTER, SCIENCE IS REAL, FLINT NEEDS CLEAN WATER, NOBODY LIKES YOU. The handmade pink \u8220\'20\'1Cpussyhats\u8221\'20\'1D that many marchers wore \u8212\'20\'14 a reference to \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s caught-on-tape boasts about grabbing unsuspecting women by the genitals \u8212\'20\'14 had been sneered at in the days before the march. They were called corny, girlie, a waste of time. Seen from above, though, on thousands of marchers, their wave of color created a powerful image.\par \par \uc2 It was, somewhat unexpectedly, one of the largest mass demonstrations in American history. Millions of protesters \u8212\'20\'14 estimates range from three to five million \u8212\'20\'14 took to the streets of Washington, Los Angeles, New York, Palm Beach, Fla., Boise, Idaho, even Fargo, N.D. Sister demonstrations were held in Thailand, in Malawi, in Antarctica. The energy of almost every group alarmed or incensed by Trump\u8217\'20\'19s election seemed to have poured into a single demonstration. That it happened on the day after his inauguration was not surprising. What was striking was that all these people had come together under the auspices of a march for women.\par \par \uc2 Just two months earlier, the left did not appear to be a unified front. The polls had barely closed before the infighting began. Some blamed \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  for ignoring Wisconsin, or the \uc2 Democratic National Committee\uc2  for boxing other candidates out of the primary field. Some blamed identity politics, which made working-class white voters \u8220\'20\'1Cfeel excluded,\u8221\'20\'1D according to Prof. Mark Lilla of Columbia. Others blamed white people, particularly the coastal ones who couldn\u8217\'20\'19t get their heartland relatives on their side.\par \par \uc2 But a crew of bummed-out, angry women was still aiming its ire at Trump. In the hours after his victory on Nov. 8, Teresa Shook, a retired lawyer in Hawaii, posted to \uc2 Facebook\uc2 , suggesting a march on Washington. Some women on the East Coast had the same idea. At first, these suggestions were so impulsive that they seemed almost metaphorical. But within days, tens of thousands of women had pledged to join in. Over the course of two months, the idea became something far bigger than initially imagined. Eventually, an entire organizing team would have permits, T-shirts, fleets of buses, portable toilets, celebrity sponsors and support from \uc2 Gloria Steinem\uc2 . Men meekly asked their female family members and \uc2 Twitter\uc2  followers: \u8220\'20\'1CAre we allowed to join?\u8221\'20\'1D By the middle of January, with the event shaping up to be the anti-Trump demonstration, the New York magazine writer Jonathan Chait worried that \u8220\'20\'1CWomen\u8217\'20\'19s March\u8221\'20\'1D was too niche an organizing principle \u8212\'20\'14 it was a \u8220\'20\'1Cbad name,\u8221\'20\'1D {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/jonathanchait/status/819306552423284737?lang=en"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 he tweeted}}}\uc2 , a divisive \u8220\'20\'1Cbrand.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The opposite turned out to be true: Women led the resistance, and everyone followed. A march for women managed to crowd a broad opposition force onto its platform. In the weeks since the march, that energy has only spread. After Trump\u8217\'20\'19s executive order halting travel from seven Muslim-majority countries, the march\u8217\'20\'19s striking proof of concept \u8212\'20\'14 hit the streets, and a surprising number of others will join you \u8212\'20\'14 fueled more spontaneous actions in unexpected places: outside courthouses, Trump hotels, airport terminals, the offices of Senator Mitch McConnell. At each protest, you were likely to see a few pink cat ears poking out of the crowd, a reminder of the opposition\u8217\'20\'19s first gathering. It seems unlikely that any other kind of march would have turned out quite this way. In this moment, it happened that \u8220\'20\'1Cwomen\u8221\'20\'1D was the one tent large enough to contain almost every major strain of protest against Trump.\par \par \uc2 Those who know their feminist history might see a paradox here. The women\u8217\'20\'19s movement has not always been a site for unity. It has been marked just as deeply by its fractures, failures and tensions. But more than a century of internal turmoil has also forced the movement to reckon with its divisions. Now, the question is whether it can bring even more Americans into the fold.\par \par \uc2 Clinton\u8217\'20\'19s loss on Nov. 8 was a pivotal, identity-shifting moment in the course of the American women\u8217\'20\'19s movement. In an evening, the would-be first female president was shoved to the side by what a sizable chunk of the nation saw as that classic historical figure: the male chauvinist pig. In parts of the popular imagination, it wasn\u8217\'20\'19t just a loss for Clinton or for the Democratic Party. It was a repudiation of feminism itself.\par \par \uc2 But Clinton has always been a wary avatar of feminism. In 2008, she didn\u8217\'20\'19t run for president as a \u8220\'20\'1Cwomen\u8217\'20\'19s candidate\u8221\'20\'1D; if anything, she campaigned with her sex in the closet and the strategist \uc2 Mark Penn\uc2  advising her to harden her image into an American Iron Lady. \u8220\'20\'1CThey do not want someone who would be the first mama,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote in one memo. Years later, HBO\u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1CVeep\u8221\'20\'1D would satirize that posture through its own fictional politician. \u8220\'20\'1CI can\u8217\'20\'19t identify myself as a woman!\u8221\'20\'1D she tells her staff. \u8220\'20\'1CPeople can\u8217\'20\'19t know that. Men hate that. And women who hate women hate that, which I believe is most women.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In the eight years between Clinton\u8217\'20\'19s first and second presidential campaigns, though, something shifted: Feminism became fashionable. By the start of the Obama era, incisive women\u8217\'20\'19s blogs like Jezebel and Feministing had already hit the web and started throwing popcorn at the big screen of American culture, covering the same topics that women\u8217\'20\'19s magazines did \u8212\'20\'14 fashion, movies, sex \u8212\'20\'14 but taking on the women\u8217\'20\'19s magazines too. By Obama\u8217\'20\'19s second term, this model had thrived and multiplied so many times over that even a co-founder of the sports website Bleacher Report started his own women\u8217\'20\'19s site, Bustle. Soon enough, no corner of culture was safe from a feminist critique, from Christmas songs to \u8220\'20\'1Cmanspreading.\u8221\'20\'1D Pop stars \u8212\'20\'14 people like Lady Gaga, Katy Perry and Taylor Swift \u8212\'20\'14 were asked if they were feminists, and if they shied away from the label, outrage would greet them online.\par \par \uc2 Feminism became increasingly popular, but in a very specific way \u8212\'20\'14 one attuned to the concerns of people with office jobs and time to spend online. The feminist priorities of this new media landscape tended to involve topics that middle-class women would experience firsthand: reproductive rights, catcalling, campus rape, professional opportunity, pop-culture representation. The writers setting its tone tended to be young women who were asked to produce large amounts of clickable copy, for not much money, in very little time, exploring feminist issues not through time-intensive reporting but through \u8220\'20\'1Ctakes\u8221\'20\'1D on the women already making news: the work-life balance of Yahoo\u8217\'20\'19s chief executive, \uc2 Marissa Mayer\uc2 ; the pay gap between Jennifer Lawrence and her male co-stars. Some content chased sexist slights down to the most passing personal concerns, like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.huffingtonpost.com/cameron-schaeffer/the-3-letter-word-that-cuts-women-down-every-day_b_8234202.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 an item from The Huffington Post}}}\uc2  that sighed: \u8220\'20\'1CThere is no proper way for a woman to cut her hair, let alone do anything right in this world.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s not that women\u8217\'20\'19s activist groups vanished or political organizing stalled. But it did become possible for an American woman to cultivate a relationship to feminism that was primarily consumerist: There were feminist TV shows to watch, feminist celebrities to follow, feminist clothes to buy. Unlike many other major social movements, women\u8217\'20\'19s liberation dovetails neatly with an important advertising demographic, a lesson capitalism absorbed more than a century ago. In 1908, the advertiser \uc2 J.Walter Thompson\uc2  hired suffragists to address the growing women\u8217\'20\'19s market. Over the next decades, the industry would slip women\u8217\'20\'19s rights messaging into ad copy. Old Dutch Cleanser offered \u8220\'20\'1Cfreedom from household drudgery\u8221\'20\'1D; Shredded Wheat promised a \u8220\'20\'1Cdeclaration of independence\u8221\'20\'1D from cooking. These days, even our bath products have achieved empowerment. Ads for Secret deodorant nudge us to ask for a raise, and those for Always prompt us to challenge stereotypes about girls. Dove wants us to feel beautiful at any size.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s telling which strand of feminism these brands have deemed marketable: the one that doubles as self-help. This is a vision of feminism in which the primary thing that needs to change is a woman\u8217\'20\'19s frame of mind. Something similar happened to the pop stars who once hesitated to call themselves feminists \u8212\'20\'14 they came around to feminism by redefining feminism around themselves. To Lady Gaga, feminism was about protecting \u8220\'20\'1Cthe integrity of women who are ambitious.\u8221\'20\'1D Taylor Swift realized, she said, that she had \u8220\'20\'1Cbeen taking a feminist stance without actually saying so.\u8221\'20\'1D Feminism was being defined down to its most benign interpretation. It was less a political platform than a brand identity.\par \par \uc2 In 2013, \u8220\'20\'1CLean In,\u8221\'20\'1D by \uc2 Sheryl Sandberg\uc2 , raised this pop-cultural subtext to the level of text. Sandberg called the book \u8220\'20\'1Csort of a feminist manifesto,\u8221\'20\'1D but it preached individual solutions to systemic problems, encouraging women to focus on \u8220\'20\'1Cinternal obstacles\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1Cdismantle the hurdles in ourselves.\u8221\'20\'1D This feminist mode, where personal success becomes synonymous with social progress, can be plugged into any number of political orientations. The latest model for the corporate-celebrity feminist brand is \uc2 Ivanka Trump\uc2 , who has built a lifestyle company under the hashtag #WomenWhoWork. A recent pitch neatly weds activist language with shoppable solutions: \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re committed to solving problems. If we can\u8217\'20\'19t find a solution, we\u8217\'20\'19ll make it ourselves (case in point: the Soho Tote, the ultimate work bag).\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 By the time the 2016 campaign rolled around, Clinton wasn\u8217\'20\'19t just permitted to run as a feminist \u8212\'20\'14 she was practically obligated to. Her messaging shifted accordingly. Years of women\u8217\'20\'19s debating the right way to be a feminist had the side effect of forcing the first female major-party candidate to the left. In 2008, she argued that she wanted abortion to be \u8220\'20\'1Csafe, legal and rare \u8212\'20\'14 and by rare I mean rare.\u8221\'20\'1D In last year\u8217\'20\'19s debates, she stopped qualifying her support. \u8220\'20\'1CI will defend \uc2 Planned Parenthood\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D she said in one. \u8220\'20\'1CI will defend Roe v. Wade, and I will defend women\u8217\'20\'19s rights to make their own health care decisions.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, her campaign mimicked the aesthetics of the pop-cultural feminist mode. The candidate affirmed her feminism in a video interview with Lena Dunham, posed in a \uc2 Kim Kardashian\uc2  selfie and made a cameo on \u8220\'20\'1CBroad City.\u8221\'20\'1D Her campaign posted a \uc2 BuzzFeed\uc2 -style listicle informing Latinos that Clinton was \u8220\'20\'1Cjust like your abuela.\u8221\'20\'1D (With the \uc2 Twitter\uc2  hashtag #NotMyAbuela, those voters begged to differ.) Her site sold embroidered pillows that said \u8220\'20\'1CA Woman\u8217\'20\'19s Place Is in the White House\u8221\'20\'1D and a T-shirt with a big \u8220\'20\'1CYAAAS, HILLARY!\u8221\'20\'1D printed over her senior portrait from high school. After Trump accused her of playing \u8220\'20\'1Cthe woman\u8217\'20\'19s card,\u8221\'20\'1D her campaign introduced a free hot-pink \u8220\'20\'1COfficial Hillary for America Woman Card\u8221\'20\'1D that drove more than $2 million in donations within days. One young woman earnestly prodded her at an Iowa campaign event: \u8220\'20\'1CIf you could choose, would you rather be the president or Beyonc\u233\'00\'E9?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Pop feminism, having been washed of its political urgency, was now being integrated back into politics at the highest level. The candidate who once shrank from feminism was positioning herself as an icon of the movement. Her image became closely aligned with two metaphors \u8212\'20\'14 the pantsuit and the glass ceiling \u8212\'20\'14 that speak to a particular kind of woman: a corporate careerist at the top of her field. A \u8220\'20\'1Csecret\u8221\'20\'1D \uc2 Facebook\uc2  group, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/pantsuitnation11.8/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Pantsuit Nation}}}\uc2 , popped up to encourage Clinton supporters to wear pantsuits to the polls. When she clinched the Democratic nomination for president last June \u8212\'20\'14 the one she would formally accept the following month, dressed in suffragist white \u8212\'20\'14 Clinton called back to the Seneca Falls convention of 1848, where \u8220\'20\'1Ca small but determined group of women, and men, came together with the idea that women deserved equal rights.\u8221\'20\'1D The feminist project started there, she implied \u8212\'20\'14 and she was going to finish it.\par \par \uc2 When Clinton lost, pop feminism suffered a crisis. As everyone pored over exit polls, some of the long-simmering fractures between different groups of women exploded into view. Ninety-four percent of black women voted for Clinton, but 53 percent of white women voted for Trump, perhaps more likely to see themselves in his vision of the world than in the pop feminism that fed Clinton\u8217\'20\'19s campaign. Despite Trump\u8217\'20\'19s palpable, eminently bloggable disrespect for women \u8212\'20\'14 and that infamous tape \u8212\'20\'14 he had successfully courted a faction of female voters. His win suggested that Americans were more comfortable with misogyny than many had thought, but it also burst the bubble of cheery pop feminism, which had achieved its huge popularity at the expense of class consciousness and racial solidarity.\par \par \uc2 In some places, you could watch the mood turn in a matter of days. The Pantsuit Nation Facebook group ceased its celebrations and became a site for sharing stories of pain and resilience. But when the group\u8217\'20\'19s founder, a Maine educator named Libby Chamberlain, announced a plan to channel the power of the group in real life, it wasn\u8217\'20\'19t exactly a call to activism \u8212\'20\'14 it was a coffee-table book. \u8220\'20\'1CYou are a force, Pantsuit Nation,\u8221\'20\'1D she wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CLet\u8217\'20\'19s see if we can harness that force within the pages of a book and see it on night stands and coffee tables all around the world.\u8221\'20\'1D The idea brought on a revolt. \u8220\'20\'1CThe N.R.A. with its five million members has a stranglehold on Congress,\u8221\'20\'1D one commenter wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CPantsuit Nation has four million members and decides its main mission is \u8216\'20\'18storytelling\u8217\'20\'19 and now, selling books. What a colossal waste.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But for some outside observers, this was a productive comeuppance. Rhon Manigault-Bryant, an associate professor of Africana studies at \uc2 Williams College\uc2  in Massachusetts, published \u8220\'20\'1CAn Open Letter to White Liberal Feminists,\u8221\'20\'1D {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.aaihs.org/an-open-letter-to-white-liberal-feminists/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 on the website Black Perspectives}}}\uc2 , expressing her disappointment that it had taken \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  to shake them into her reality. \u8220\'20\'1CI am delighted that you have received the potential awakening of a lifetime, and that now you might actually get what so many of us have been describing all along,\u8221\'20\'1D she wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CWelcome to that deep perpetual angst. Embrace it, and allow it to motivate you to a deeper form of action.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In those same November weeks, the nascent march-on-Washington project was navigating its own identity crisis. Some of the early organizers had romantic-comedy-type jobs \u8212\'20\'14 pastry chef, yoga instructor. One of the women, Bob Bland, a fashion designer, had amassed a small online following by designing \u8220\'20\'1CNASTY WOMAN\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1CBAD HOMBRE\u8221\'20\'1D T-shirts and selling them online. \u8220\'20\'1CI had this whole network of \u8216\'20\'18nasty women\u8217\'20\'19 and \u8216\'20\'18bad hombres,\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D she told me. \u8220\'20\'1CAfter the election, they were looking to me like, \u8216\'20\'18What are we going to do next?\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Disparate organizers convened around a \uc2 Facebook\uc2  event announcing a Million Women March. There was one major problem with this: In 1997, activists organized a Million Woman March in Philadelphia to address the particular concerns of black women. When this new march on Washington unwittingly chose a very similar name, it crystallized the idea that the nascent movement was being run by a handful of white women with no organizing history. Comments began pouring in from all sides.\par \par \uc2 The organizers had stumbled into a conflict that has dogged women\u8217\'20\'19s organizing from the very beginning: Of all the tensions that have coursed through the women\u8217\'20\'19s movement, none has ever been quite so pronounced as the one between white and black women. Consider what happened when Sojourner Truth showed up at a women\u8217\'20\'19s rights convention in Ohio in 1851. Frances Gage, the woman running the show, recalled the scene 12 years later: \u8220\'20\'1CThe leaders of the movement trembled on seeing a tall, gaunt black woman in a gray dress and white turban, surmounted with an uncouth sunbonnet, march deliberately into the church, walk with the air of a queen up the aisle and take her seat upon the pulpit steps.\u8221\'20\'1D A \u8220\'20\'1Cbuzz of disapprobation\u8221\'20\'1D spread through the church. White women in attendance complained that a black woman\u8217\'20\'19s testimony would distract from the convention\u8217\'20\'19s focus. \u8220\'20\'1CDon\u8217\'20\'19t let her speak, Mrs. Gage \u8212\'20\'14 it will ruin us,\u8221\'20\'1D one said. \u8220\'20\'1CEvery newspaper in the land will have our cause mixed up with abolition and niggers, and we shall be utterly denounced.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Throughout the convention, men arrived to speak out against women\u8217\'20\'19s suffrage. Women, they said, were too weak and helpless to be trusted with the power of the vote. Because \u8220\'20\'1Cthere were very few women in those days who dared to \u8216\'20\'18speak in meeting,\u8217\'20\'19\u8201\'20\'09\u8221\'20\'1D as Gage put it, their points went unchallenged until Truth stepped forward. White women hissed, but Truth\u8217\'20\'19s very identity nullified the arguments coming from both men and women in attendance. \u8220\'20\'1CThat man over there says that women need to be helped into carriages, and lifted over ditches, and to have the best place everywhere,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CNobody ever helps me into carriages, or over mud puddles, or gives me any best place. And ain\u8217\'20\'19t I a woman? Look at me! Look at my arm!\u8221\'20\'1D She rolled up her sleeve to the shoulder. \u8220\'20\'1CI have plowed and planted, and gathered into barns, and no man could head me. And ain\u8217\'20\'19t I a woman?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In that moment, Truth shattered an idea of white femininity that had been used to both underpin and undermine the cause of suffrage. As a slave, she had worked in the fields like a man; as a free black woman, she could not rely on the offerings of white male gentility. Gage wrote that Truth\u8217\'20\'19s testimony compelled the white women in attendance to embrace her \u8220\'20\'1Cwith streaming eyes, and hearts beating with gratitude.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But two years later, Truth still drew jeers from white crowds when she attended women\u8217\'20\'19s meetings. A vision of whiteness was ingrained in the leaders and the arguments of the mainstream movement. Even the suffragists\u8217\'20\'19 signature white clothes were deliberately chosen to signal purity. This ideal of feminine virtue did not extend to black women, or working-class ones. Some suffragists made their racism and classism explicit. In 1894, a white woman at a meeting of the Brooklyn Woman Suffrage Association complained that New York had become an \u8220\'20\'1Casylum for the trash of all nations,\u8221\'20\'1D arguing that women\u8217\'20\'19s suffrage ought to be restricted. \u8220\'20\'1CThink what it means to give it to all women,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1COur criminal and pauper men have wives; there are thousands of female operatives in tobacco factories and similar fields of labor; there are probably two million Negro women in this country who are but little uplifted above the plane of animals.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 One curious point of this history is that so many suffragists came from the antislavery movement. Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony, whose partnership would come to define the suffrage movement in the United States, started their activist careers as abolitionists. But after the Civil War, as black men and all women agitated for the right to vote, a political battle broke out over who would be enfranchised first. (Either way, black women would be last.) In 1865, Stanton lamented having to \u8220\'20\'1Cstand aside to see \u8216\'20\'18Sambo\u8217\'20\'19 walk into the kingdom first,\u8221\'20\'1D as she put it in The National Anti-Slavery Standard.\par \par \uc2 Over time, these racial contours would harden into lasting institutions. When women\u8217\'20\'19s social clubs spread across the United States at the turn of the century, two models emerged. Whites-only clubs leveraged middle-class women\u8217\'20\'19s leisure time to campaign for social reforms. Black women, who largely worked outside the home, came together around urgent needs. One of the first actions of the black Chicago Women\u8217\'20\'19s Club was to raise money to prosecute a police officer who killed a black man. The main distinction between clubs, the black activist Fannie Barrier Williams wrote, was that for black women, \u8220\'20\'1Cit is not a fad.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Black women distinguished themselves not only as suffragists but also as vocal critics of a movement that pushed one kind of justice aside in pursuit of another. In 1913, when thousands of suffragists marched on Washington to agitate for the vote, black women were instructed to march in the back. Ida B. Wells defied the order and marched with the delegation from Illinois, her home state. She wasn\u8217\'20\'19t just protesting for her right to vote. She was protesting the protest too.\par \par \uc2 This dynamic is not only a thing of distant history: In the thick of feminism\u8217\'20\'19s second wave, women were often still divided along lines of identity. In 1967, as the best-selling author Betty Friedan called the first meeting of the New York chapter of the \uc2 National Organization for Women\uc2 , she found herself at odds with a black activist and lawyer named Flo Kennedy, who pushed the women around her to make \uc2 common cause\uc2  with the antiwar and Black Power movements. Friedan and the meeting\u8217\'20\'19s host \u8212\'20\'14 Muriel Fox, the highest-ranking female executive at the world\u8217\'20\'19s largest public-relations agency \u8212\'20\'14 were not pleased. As Kennedy put it in her memoirs, they \u8220\'20\'1Cwent bonkers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Friedan\u8217\'20\'19s 1963 book, \u8220\'20\'1CThe Feminine Mystique,\u8221\'20\'1D had been an awakening for a class of white, married, middle-class women, and she pictured herself as the leader of what she called a \u8220\'20\'1Cmainstream\u8221\'20\'1D feminist movement. When women at one 1970 march offered her a lavender armband to wear in solidarity with a NOW member recently attacked for her bisexuality, Friedan dropped it on the ground, furious at the attempt to add gay rights to her program.\par \par \uc2 Kennedy continually pushed in the opposite direction, trying to build bridges between feminist groups and other movements. At one point, Friedan admonished her to leave the feminist movement alone and \u8220\'20\'1Cfocus her attention on matters of Black Power.\u8221\'20\'1D As the second wave matured, black women found themselves continually calling on it to consider a new approach, one that acknowledged the different needs of different women. As the black feminist and leftist Barbara Smith told the National Women\u8217\'20\'19s Studies Association in 1979, any feminism that didn\u8217\'20\'19t account for the specific concerns of black women, poor women, disabled women, lesbians and others was not really feminism \u8212\'20\'14 it was \u8220\'20\'1Cmerely female self-aggrandizement.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 There has never been one women\u8217\'20\'19s movement. It\u8217\'20\'19s difficult, for example, to say that the American feminist project started in Seneca Falls, N.Y., in 1848, because black women were not invited to that convention. It\u8217\'20\'19s hard to say that electing a woman as president would have been feminism\u8217\'20\'19s crowning achievement, because the success of one woman does not naturally trickle down to all. The history of the women\u8217\'20\'19s movement is one of warring factions and sharp self-criticism. But its 150 years of navigating internal disputes put it in a position to lead what seemed, at the end of last fall, like a highly divided left.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s embarrassing to me now to say it, but I didn\u8217\'20\'19t know the term \u8216\'20\'18intersectionality\u8217\'20\'19 when we started,\u8221\'20\'1D Bob Bland, the Women\u8217\'20\'19s March co-chairwoman, told me. Now she deployed it often to emphasize the growing diversity of the march. She told various reporters that she had met women working \u8220\'20\'1Cin so many different intersectionalities\u8221\'20\'1D and hoped to reach a \u8220\'20\'1Ca wide intersectionality of people\u8221\'20\'1D in a march that reflected \u8220\'20\'1Call of the different intersections of human rights.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 That magic word comes from a 1989 paper by the legal scholar Kimberl\u233\'00\'E9 Crenshaw that was published in The \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Chicago\uc2  Legal Forum. Crenshaw had studied cases in which black women sued their employers for what appeared to be \u8220\'20\'1Ccompound discrimination\u8221\'20\'1D \u8212\'20\'14 both racial and gender biases. But they were often told they lacked legal standing: Laws protected them from discrimination as African-Americans or as women, but not specifically as black women. Crenshaw used a traffic metaphor to describe the interlocking forms of oppression a person might face. Cars flowed through an intersection in all directions; when an accident happened, it could be caused by cars from any number of sides, or even all sides.\par \par \uc2 That metaphor would be plucked from Crenshaw\u8217\'20\'19s paper and grow in resonance over the next two decades, until \u8220\'20\'1Cintersectionality\u8221\'20\'1D became a rallying cry \u8212\'20\'14 the main point of rhetorical resistance against the tide of single-issue feminist conversation. Even beneath the shiny surface of Obama-era pop feminism, dissenters took countless shots at its racial cluelessness, its lack of class-consciousness, its sometimes shallow concerns. Women of color convened on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  under hashtags like #SolidarityIsForWhiteWomen to detail their experiences of being sidelined in feminist conversations, and many on the left criticized the way a trickle-down, professional-oriented feminism was becoming popular just as income inequality between women was ballooning. (It\u8217\'20\'19s hard to \u8220\'20\'1Clean in\u8221\'20\'1D to a job cleaning hotel rooms.) In recent years, intersectionality even popped up in People.com, on Bustle and in a tweet from Clinton.\par \par \uc2 Often the criticism that lies behind this word is brushed off, met with defensiveness, taken personally. (As the founder of Pantsuit Nation wrote to critics of her book deal: \u8220\'20\'1CThis is not the place for divisiveness.\u8221\'20\'1D) Women turn to feminism because they want to stand up and say something; it can be jarring for them be told to sit down and listen to someone else. But the concept became a useful tool for the march on Washington, which set about the task of uniting feminism\u8217\'20\'19s mainstream, popular arm and its dissenting factions \u8212\'20\'14 all in the space of two months.\par \par \uc2 Soon after the suggestion to march raced across the web, Vanessa Wruble \u8212\'20\'14 a white producer and co-founder of the media company OkayAfrica \u8212\'20\'14 made a pivotal intervention in its planning. \u8220\'20\'1CI thought the stakes were so high,\u8221\'20\'1D she told me. \u8220\'20\'1CIt needed to be an inclusive movement, or it was going to be a total disaster. I felt that it could damage the country.\u8221\'20\'1D At this critical moment, with the march quickly ballooning into something bigger than the initial organizers could handle on their own, Wruble reached out and urged them to drop the name Million Women March. Then she linked them up with her network, and soon three seasoned activists \u8212\'20\'14 Carmen Perez, Linda Sarsour and Tamika Mallory \u8212\'20\'14 got on board. These women hadn\u8217\'20\'19t necessarily supported Clinton, and they didn\u8217\'20\'19t necessarily identify as feminists. But they had experience organizing in communities of color and saw the march as an opportunity to reach a large new audience. When Sarsour got the call, she had just posted a comment on the march\u8217\'20\'19s \uc2 Facebook\uc2  page: \u8220\'20\'1CCan you include Muslim women and Muslim communities in the list?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The three women \u8212\'20\'14 one Chicana Latina, one Palestinian-American, one black \u8212\'20\'14 met through their involvement in Justice League NYC, a juvenile-justice initiative. In 2015, they organized a nine-day march from New York to Washington, ending in a rally at the Capitol that drew a small crowd. Now hundreds of thousands of women whose previous interest in justice may have been abstract at best were turning to them for leadership. The question, Perez told me, was \u8220\'20\'1CHow do we get them to understand that their liberation is bound with ours?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the three had some catching up to do with the mainstream feminist perspective. \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t have a lot of what I would consider to be deep, transformative relationships with white women,\u8221\'20\'1D Sarsour told me. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19ve been learning a lot,\u8221\'20\'1D she said, and working toward becoming \u8220\'20\'1Cmore comfortable around this movement of feminism that I always felt didn\u8217\'20\'19t particularly include Muslim women.\u8221\'20\'1D The organizers appeared on the hip-hop radio morning show \u8220\'20\'1CThe Breakfast Club\u8221\'20\'1D and loaded their \uc2 Instagram\uc2  page with black feminist heroes. But they also posed for windswept photos in Vogue, and some dropped by the Wing, a private Manhattan women\u8217\'20\'19s club with a $2,250 annual membership fee. Their rally put Angela Davis on the same stage as \uc2 Scarlett Johansson\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 When I called Kimberl\u233\'00\'E9 Crenshaw in January, she had just returned home to Los Angeles from the march on Washington, where she walked with a group of women from the African American Policy Forum. Her group was so far back in the crowd that they couldn\u8217\'20\'19t hear the rally, and \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m kind of glad about it,\u8221\'20\'1D she told me. \u8220\'20\'1CWe were in this sea of humanity.\u8221\'20\'1D Wading through the crowd, she said, \u8220\'20\'1CI saw all the different issues and people that had found their way under the banner of the Women\u8217\'20\'19s March. It was the embodiment of the intersectional sensibilities that a lot of us have been working on for a very long time.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The women\u8217\'20\'19s movement\u8217\'20\'19s tendency toward a singular perspective is \u8220\'20\'1Cnot an exceptional problem for feminism,\u8221\'20\'1D Crenshaw told me. \u8220\'20\'1CPatriarchy works in such a way that these critiques never even surface in a lot of movements led by men. This conversation isn\u8217\'20\'19t always happening in other spaces. And if the conversation leads to more robust ways of thinking about women, feminism and social justice, it can be a very good thing.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe million-dollar question is: Can these feminisms live together under an anti-Trump banner?\u8221\'20\'1D Crenshaw said. \u8220\'20\'1CIt happened for 24 hours all across the world.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When I made my way back to my hotel after the march, the cheers of the crowd fading into the distance, I opened my laptop and saw a different version of what I had just seen in person. Now it was all filtered through my own social-media bubble \u8212\'20\'14 that of a middle-class white woman who lives in Brooklyn. \uc2 Facebook\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s trending topics, tailored to fulfill each user\u8217\'20\'19s particular online habits, served me up a pop-celebrity version of the day\u8217\'20\'19s events. It pointed me toward the speeches of \uc2 Scarlett Johansson\uc2  and Madonna, and nobody else. As scenes of the march traveled through the media and across the web, the story spun out in even more directions. \uc2 Twitter\uc2  lit up with notes of internal dissent and snapshots of signs from the march: DON\u8217\'20\'19T FORGET: WHITE WOMEN VOTED FOR TRUMP and BLACK WOMEN TRIED TO SAVE Y\u8217\'20\'19ALL and I\u8217\'20\'19LL SEE YOU NICE WHITE LADIES AT THE NEXT #BLACKLIVESMATTER MARCH, RIGHT?\par \par \uc2 But for the moment, at least, Trump appears to be the great uniter. In the days and weeks since the march, its energy spilled into spontaneous actions across the country, with protesters coming together on behalf of Muslims and immigrants. Donations poured into \uc2 Planned Parenthood\uc2  and \uc2 the American Civil Liberties Union\uc2 . Congressional switchboards were inundated with calls. When {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/united-by-post-inauguration-marches-democratic-women-plan-to-step-up-activism/2017/02/01/373004e0-e766-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html?utm_term=.8f7b21293bef"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 The Washington Post polled Americans}}}\uc2  post-march, it registered a huge shift in energy among Democrats, especially Democratic women, 40 percent of whom said they planned to get more involved in activism.\par \par \uc2 But liberals are not the only ones drawing inspiration from the protests. Flip to Fox News, click around conservative blogs or browse pro-Trump \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , and you can watch the demonstrations fuel a different kind of opposition narrative. After the march, Fox News set clips of rally speeches to foreboding music. Breitbart published photos with the headline \u8220\'20\'1CSee what a massive, Hillary shaped bullet America just dodged?\u8221\'20\'1D The right-wing Media Research Center aggregated the most \u8220\'20\'1Cvile and ridiculous signs.\u8221\'20\'1D \uc2 Twitter\uc2  exploded with anti-Muslim attacks on Linda Sarsour, who was called a \u8220\'20\'1Cterrorist\u8221\'20\'1D who \u8220\'20\'1Cloves ISIS.\u8221\'20\'1D When the annual March for Life hit the Mall to demonstrate against abortion rights, The Blaze called it \u8220\'20\'1Cthe real women\u8217\'20\'19s march.\u8221\'20\'1D (The Women\u8217\'20\'19s March did, at one point, remove the name of an anti-abortion group from its list of partners, after an uproar.) {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.publicpolicypolling.com/main/2017/02/after-2-weeks-voters-yearn-for-obama.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 According to Public Policy Polling}}}\uc2 , 48 percent of Trump voters think the protesters who convened at airports to protest the travel ban were paid by \uc2 George Soros\uc2 . Trump tweeted recently: \u8220\'20\'1CProfessional anarchists, thugs and paid protesters are proving the point of the millions of people who voted to MAKE AMERICA GREAT AGAIN!\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In the first weeks of the Trump administration, the factions that split over his election are deepening along the same lines. Each side seems oddly confident in its political position. Trump supporters call themselves \u8220\'20\'1Cthe silent majority,\u8221\'20\'1D while his critics identify as the \u8220\'20\'1Cpopular vote.\u8221\'20\'1D When I called \uc2 Eleanor Smeal\uc2 , a co-founder of the Feminist Majority Foundation, and asked her whether the organization had any plans to reach out to the 53 percent of white women who voted for Trump, her response was to question the margin of error in the polls. \u8220\'20\'1CWe don\u8217\'20\'19t really know if we lost the majority or not, and I believe that we did not,\u8221\'20\'1D she told me. \u8220\'20\'1CI think they\u8217\'20\'19re with us.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 For now, the factions of the left seem to have found an accord. But to regain any power in Washington, they will need to sway the center too \u8212\'20\'14 including some of those women who voted for Trump. The white women of the left, many of whom are just now finding their footing as activists, have been eager to dissociate from that group. Mention the 53 percent, and they\u8217\'20\'19re quick to tell you that they\u8217\'20\'19re of the 47. But of all the people who marched on Washington last month, they may be among the best positioned to reach across that aisle. \u8220\'20\'1CI know of no other time when it would be more important,\u8221\'20\'1D Barbara Smith, the black feminist and leftist, told me. \u8220\'20\'1CThat\u8217\'20\'19s not my work to do, but somebody ought to do it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sign up for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/magazine"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 our newsletter}}}\uc2  to get the best of The \uc2 New York Times Magazine\uc2  delivered to your inbox every week.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/21/us/womens-march.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Women\u8217\'20\'19s March Highlights as Huge Crowds Protest Trump: \u8216\'20\'18We\u8217\'20\'19re Not Going Away\u8217\'20\'19}}}\par \par \uc2 Women\u8217\'20\'19s March on Washington, Jan. 21, 2017. | Matthew Pillsbury for The New York Times | Women\u8217\'20\'19s March on Washington, Jan. 21, 2017. | Matthew Pillsbury for The New York Times | Women\u8217\'20\'19s Strike for Equality, New York, Aug. 26, 1970. | William E. Sauro/The New York Times | Mi