\par\par \uc2 Lens\par \uc2 Multimedia\par {\*\bkmkstart toc67}{\*\bkmkend toc67}\b \uc2 Seeking Applications for the 2017 New York Portfolio Review\b0\par\par\uc2 By THE NEW YORK TIMES \par \uc2 1,189 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par 11:05\par \uc2 NYT Blogs\par \uc2 NYTB\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The New York Times Company. All rights reserved \par \par \uc2 Are you a photographer who needs a break and wants to share your work with some of the most important photo editors, publishers, gallery owners and curators in the world? Then you should apply today to the free (yes, free) fifth annual New York Portfolio Review, sponsored by The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  Lens blog and the \uc2 City \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of New York\u8217\'20\'19s Graduate School of Journalism\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Participation is open to anyone over 18 years, and all types of photography will be considered. But remember, time is running out and the deadline is Feb. 12 at 11:59 p.m. Eastern Time.\par \par \uc2 Since we believe that only the quality of your work should matter \u8212\'20\'14 not who you know, how much money you have or your race, gender, ethnic background or sexual orientation, we are again bringing together 150 talented photographers with 75 top photo editors, publishers, video producers, gallery owners and curators for two days of private sessions on April 29th and 30th.\par \par \uc2 This will be an opportunity for people in the photographic community to meet, trade ideas, help each other \u8212\'20\'14 and have fun.\par \par \uc2 The first session, on Saturday, April 29, will be held for photographers 21 and older. Each participant will receive six private critiques. The second session, on Sunday, April 30, will be solely for photographers 18 to 27 and will consist of at least four private critiques for each participant, as well as workshops on how to best present, promote and publish photographs. We will screen all applicants and choose 100 participants for Saturday and 50 for Sunday. All kinds of photographic work \u8212\'20\'14 from fine art to photojournalism \u8212\'20\'14 are encouraged.\par \par \uc2 Please note: Photographers who attended last year\u8217\'20\'19s review are not eligible to apply this year. Those who attended once in previous years can apply for this year\u8217\'20\'19s review, but they must submit new work and expectations will be higher. Those who have already attended the review twice cannot apply.\par \par \uc2 Once photographers are selected, they will submit their top choices for reviewers of their work. We will match participants with as many of those reviewers as possible.\par \par \uc2 To enter, send no more than 20 photos total, from one or two projects, using the form below. The files should be jpegs, 1,200 pixels across and 72 D.P.I. We will inform those who are accepted by March 21.\par \par \uc2 Note: Be sure to triple-check the email address you submit. In the past, people have been accepted into the review, but we couldn\u8217\'20\'19t reach them because of a misspelling in their address.\par \par \uc2 A list of reviewers is under the submission form below.\par \par \uc2 If you have any questions, you can send us an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:NewYorkPortfolioReview@gmail.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 email}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Our lineup of reviewers this year includes:\par \par \uc2 Elizabeth Avedon, correspondent, L\u8217\'20\'19Oeil de la Photographie\par \par \uc2 Felicia Anastasia, owner, Anastasia Gallery\par \par \uc2 Daniel Aycock, owner, Front Room Gallery\par \par \uc2 Stacey Baker, photo editor, The \uc2 New York Times Magazine\par \par \uc2 Sam Barzilay, creative director, United Photo Industries and Photoville\par \par \uc2 Jacqueline Bates, photography director, The California Sunday Magazine\par \par \uc2 Liz Baylen, director of video enterprise, The \uc2 New York Times\par \par \uc2 Deborah Bell, president and owner, Debor