n. In Ontario, Adam Capay, a 24-year-old First Nations man, has been kept in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/ontarios-sickening-mistreatment-of-adam-capay/article32498319/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 solitary confinement}}}\uc2  for the last four years. Charged with killing a fellow inmate in a prison altercation, he has still not gone to trial.\par \par \uc2 Comparing Canada with the United States is reasonable \u8212\'20\'14 we\u8217\'20\'19re close enough, and share a similar history and geography \u8212\'20\'14 but suggesting that Canada has figured something out that other nations haven\u8217\'20\'19t is not. True, everything the United States does is louder than in Canada: America\u8217\'20\'19s food is radioactive, its television is more aggressive (and, well, objectively better), so it makes sense that America\u8217\'20\'19s politics are more overtly noxious. But that hardly makes Canada a refuge.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s a meme circulating on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  and \uc2 Facebook\uc2  that you see more than ever now that people are arguing that Canada\u8217\'20\'19s politics are such a stark contrast to America\u8217\'20\'19s. It involves posting a link to a goofy Canadian story \u8212\'20\'14 often involving a moose, why not? \u8212\'20\'14 with accompanying text that reads, \u8220\'20\'1CMeanwhile in Canada.\u8221\'20\'1D While America burns, Canadians calmly shovel their driveways and buy {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://mentalfloss.com/article/81468/why-do-canadians-drink-milk-bags"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 bagged milk}}}\uc2  for their kids.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s like being considered the gentler, kinder sibling. In reality, we\u8217\'20\'19re just more passive-aggressive, too frightened to acknowledge how we fail our citizens day after day.\par \par \uc2 There is no Canadian exceptionalism. What\u8217\'20\'19s happening here now has been happening for decades: Bias and discrimination are rooted in our history and government. All that\u8217\'20\'19s true about America\u8217\'20\'19s broken system is true, too, of Canada\u8217\'20\'19s. The only real difference is the illusion that Canada is intrinsically better.\par \par \uc2 America has elected a dangerous demagogue to its highest office. In Canada, we\u8217\'20\'19re just one election away from falling into the same trap.\par \par \uc2 Follow The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  Opinion section on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.facebook.com/nytopinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Facebook}}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://twitter.com/NYTOpinion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Twitter}}}\uc2  (@NYTOpinion), and sign up for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/newsletters/opiniontoday/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Opinion Today newsletter}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Scaachi Koul, a culture writer for \uc2 BuzzFeed\uc2 , is the author of the forthcoming book \u8220\'20\'1COne Day We\u8217\'20\'19ll All Be Dead and None of This Will Matter.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Correction: February 6, 2017, Monday\par \par \uc2 This article has been revised to reflect the following correction: An earlier version of this article misstated the name of \uc2 Kinder Morgan\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s oil pipeline. It is the Trans-Mountain pipeline, not the Trans-Atlantic.\par \par \uc2 A sign stating \u8220\'20\'1CQuebec in mourning\u8221\'20\'1D at a rally near the Islamic Cultural Center in Quebec City last month. | Alice Chiche/Agence France-Presse \u8212\'20\'14 Getty Images \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170206ed26000b6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw126\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal1890\pichgoal600
