\par\par \uc2 Food\par {\*\bkmkstart toc70}{\*\bkmkend toc70}\b \uc2 Small Cheese Makers Invest in a Stinky Science\b0\par\par\uc2 By LARISSA ZIMBEROFF \par \uc2 1,342 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par 14:49\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 GREENSBORO, Vt. \u8212\'20\'14 There\u8217\'20\'19s no sign announcing that you\u8217\'20\'19ve arrived at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.jasperhillfarm.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Jasper Hill Farm}}}\uc2 , a creamery in the Northeast Kingdom, as Vermonters call that end of their state, but you can\u8217\'20\'19t miss it. The main barn is painted midnight blue with a giant cheese moon and cows floating happily in space. Blasted into the hillside is a concrete bunker with seven cheese caves radiating from a central core.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s one other surprising detail: a modern two-room laboratory filled with microbiology equipment and staffed with scientists.\par \par \uc2 Why does a small, rural creamery invest in technology for what has long been a low-tech product? Because it doesn\u8217\'20\'19t have 500 years to learn what its European counterparts already know: the biological intricacies of how to make the best cheese in a particular place. And because the same diversity of microbial cultures is not available in North America.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBuilding a lab might seem extravagant or of questionable value, but what we get as a business over two, three, four generations \u8212\'20\'14 it\u8217\'20\'19s a no-brainer,\u8221\'20\'1D said Mateo Kehler, who owns the farm with his brother, Andy.\par \par \uc2 The making of cheese depends on the contribution of myriad microbial actors. Both yeast and bacteria are components of the starter cultures that help turn milk into solids, and those solids into cheeses with distinctive aromas, flavors and textures that are hard to resist. The interplay of these species, while understood in a basic sense, is now receiving renewed scientific scrutiny and appreciation in the United States.\par \par \uc2 Unlike their peers in Europe, who benefit from centuries of tradition and from government support for research, American farmstead cheese makers have typically gone it alone. Starter cultures are a particularly vexing ingredient. The only three domestic suppliers, including \uc2 DuPont\uc2  and Cargill, are multinational corporations better known for chemicals, which has limited the number of available cultures and caused discomfort in a field that strives for individuality.\par \par \uc2 But now several small cheese producers are working with scientists to develop their own starters and use microbiology to create better cheeses.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.murrayscheese.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Murray\u8217\'20\'19s Cheese}}}\uc2  is working with Rockefeller \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  to learn more about the microflora in its cheese caves in Long Island City, Queens. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.uplandscheese.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Uplands Cheese Company}}}\uc2  is working with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cdr.wisc.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Center for Dairy Research}}}\uc2  at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Wisconsin to create a new soft cheese, its first in seven years.\par \par \uc2 But perhaps none have taken on cheese science as rigorously as Jasper Hill. Its laboratory, opened in 2013, has become a hub for other cheese makers seeking help and insight.\par \par \uc2 When the Kehler brothers began making cheese in 2003, their aim was to invigorate the local dairy industry, which was, and still is, struggling. They started on their path to applied science in 2010, when {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/19/dining/for-gastronomists-a-go-to-microbiologist.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Rachel Dutton}}}\uc2 , a Harvard scientist, decided to use cheese as a model to research how small microbial communities interact; she focused on the composition of cheese rinds.\par \par \uc2 Her first contact in the cheese business was Mateo Kehler, who taught her to make cheese and then helped her reach out to more than 100 other producers for samples. The response was overwhelming. \u8220\'20\'1CI don\u8217\'20\'19t think she realized how excited the artisan cheese industry was going to be,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Kehler said.\par \par \uc2 In 2014, Dr. Dutton published her findings in the journal {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4222527/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Cell}}}\uc2 . Working with Benjamin Wolfe, a postdoctoral researcher, she reported that the environment (cows, cheese caves, pastures) and methods (washing, salting, managing acidity) were as important to the development of cheese rinds, if not more so, than the ingredients.\par \par \uc2 This was a revelation. With this new scientific proof in hand, the Kehlers stopped adding starter cultures to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.jasperhillfarm.com/winnimere/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Winnimere}}}\uc2 , one of their most popular raw-milk cheeses. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat we were adding wasn\u8217\'20\'19t growing, and when we stopped adding that, the cheese ripened more gracefully and deliciously,\u8221\'20\'1D Mateo Kehler said.\par \par \uc2 Their pasteurized cheeses, though, still needed starters because pasteurization kills bacteria both good and bad for cheese. So they began making starter cultures from bacteria in their own milk supply.\par \par \uc2 Besides ending their reliance on big business, this has allowed the brothers to create a cheese that can come only from a singular place: Greensboro, Vt.\par \par \uc2 An on-site laboratory has its perks. In addition to having staff members who deeply understand microbiology, Jasper Hill Farm has become a magnet for researchers near and far. Now working there are an engineering intern from Brittany, France; a local microbiologist; and Panos C. Lekkas, a food microbiologist who has investigated the best ways to feed, tend and milk a cow for cheese production.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Lekkas, who was hired in November to work full time at Jasper Hill, collaborates with Dr. Dutton, now at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of California, San Diego\uc2 , and with Dr. Wolfe, who leads a microbiology laboratory at \uc2 Tufts \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In addition to helping improve {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/f/food_safety/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 food safety}}}\uc2  procedures at the 85-person Jasper Hill farm, Dr. Lekkas is overseeing the development of a new cheese \u8212\'20\'14 a French Camembert style that for now the team is calling Wild Moses.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Lekkas was told that it takes eight months to bring a new cheese to market. \u8220\'20\'1CMateo wants me to do it in three,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. With science comes speed.\par \par \uc2 In order to make a soft pasteurized cheese that does not rely on corporate additives, the scientists sampled 300 promising strains of yeast and bacteria, all pulled from milk from Jasper Hill\u8217\'20\'19s own 250 cows.\par \par \uc2 What makes a homegrown starter promising? Sometimes it\u8217\'20\'19s the color of the microbes in a petri dish, but smell, too, can be telling. The group sniffed the samples and noted any pleasing aromas: Play-Doh, Concord grapes, tomato juice, clams, Kraft American Singles. Dr. Wolfe\u8217\'20\'19s lab ran a full genomic sequencing on the 15 top contenders, which will provide a blueprint for understanding how these strains are related to, or differ from, other cultures in the cheese world.\par \par \uc2 Making funky cheese is tricky, even for scientists. \u8220\'20\'1CThere are subtle variations in flavor and aroma that you perceive in cheese,\u8221\'20\'1D Dr. Wolfe said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe want to understand what drives that variation.\u8221\'20\'1D With Dr. Wolfe\u8217\'20\'19s genomic data, the team can track the microbes through the entire cheese-making process.\par \par \uc2 In November, the first batch of cheese was produced using five strains from the original 15 parent cultures \u8212\'20\'14 two yeast-based and three bacterial. New batches are being made every two weeks using different combinations, and every 10 days, each will be tasted to see whether it is on target for the \u8220\'20\'1Cdeliciousness factor,\u8221\'20\'1D Jasper Hill\u8217\'20\'19s zero-to-10 grading system.\par \par \uc2 Seven or above is pretty good. Eight is out of this world. Tens are likely to be bestowed only outside the farm: Jasper Hill\u8217\'20\'19s Harbison cheese {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.jasperhillfarm.com/news2/2016/1/6/super-gold-at-the-world-cheese-awards"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 recently took Super Gold}}}\uc2  at the World Cheese Awards in Spain.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI will be happy with a seven,\u8221\'20\'1D Dr. Lekkas said.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/27/dining/american-sheep-cheese.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Sheep\u8217\'20\'19s Milk Cheeses in U.S. Earn Ribbons but Little Profit}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/28/dining/oxford-companion-to-cheese-book.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 For the Cheese Lover, the Ultimate Reference Book}}}\par \par \uc2 Mateo Kehler, left, and Andy Kehler make award-winning cheese at Jasper Hill Farm in Greensboro, Vt. The mural on the barn behind them is the work of Tara Goreau. | Caleb Kenna for The New York Times | Mateo Kehler tests Bayley Hazen Blue cheese in one of the seven cellars of Jasper Hill Farm. | Caleb Kenna for The New York Times | Mr. Kehler with Sayer Dion, a technician in the cheese lab. Jasper Hill is working with scientists to develop its own starters and to use microbiology to create better cheeses. | Caleb Kenna for The New York Times | Panos C. Lekkas, a food microbiologist, is the quality and safety manager at Jasper Hill and is overseeing the development of a new cheese in a French Camembert style. | Caleb Kenna for The New York Times | Bayley Hazen Blue is a raw-milk cheese. The Kehler brothers are seeking to develop their own starters so they can produce cheeses with a taste of place. | Caleb Kenna for The New York Times \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170206ed260073l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
