\par\par \uc2 New York Today\par \uc2 N.Y. / Region\par {\*\bkmkstart toc71}{\*\bkmkend toc71}\b \uc2 New York Today: A Makeshift Law Office Closes at Kennedy\b0\par\par\uc2 By JONATHAN WOLFE \par \uc2 1,240 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par 05:01\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Updated, 9:30 a.m.\par \par \uc2 Good morning on this chilly-cheery Monday.\par \par \uc2 Amid the bustle at Kennedy International Airport on Sunday, a group of recently acquainted New Yorkers packed up boxes of office supplies, snapped a group photograph and said their goodbyes.\par \par \uc2 With that, the makeshift legal aid office set up to help detained passengers in the aftermath of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/us/politics/trumps-travel-ban.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s targeted travel ban}}}\uc2  was dismantled.\par \par \uc2 Over the past week, hundreds of lawyers had rotated though the group\u8217\'20\'19s base camp: the Central Diner restaurant in Terminal 4.\par \par \uc2 On a recent afternoon, Camille Mackler, the director of legal initiatives at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.thenyic.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 New York Immigration Coalition}}}\uc2 , stood among the bleary-eyed volunteers in \u8220\'20\'1Cthe pen,\u8221\'20\'1D an improvised office of folding tables, snaking power cords, sugary snacks and handmade signs offering legal help in English, Arabic and Farsi.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAt first it was like the inmates running the asylum,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Mackler said of the initial chaos. She had been one of the first lawyers on the scene and later began organizing the crush of volunteer attorneys.\par \par \uc2 Within days, the group had set up servers, \uc2 Google\uc2  spreadsheets and a steering committee. Sprawled across crowded tables and the terminal\u8217\'20\'19s polished floors, they used their laptops and cellphones to write manuals on how to help travelers.\par \par \uc2 And things moved quickly at Terminal 4.\par \par \uc2 Chris Hennessy, 24, a volunteer from Harlem, stumbled upon the group and began picking up trash and getting coffee for the lawyers. A few days later, he was the project coordinator.\par \par \uc2 Others who couldn\u8217\'20\'19t make it to the airport showed their support.\par \par \uc2 A stack of pizzas was delivered. A sorority from \uc2 Kean \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  sent bags of ramen. A box of toothbrushes arrived.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey must think we\u8217\'20\'19re not showering,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Mackler said.\par \par \uc2 (While it was a round-the-clock operation, most volunteers didn\u8217\'20\'19t spend more than eight hours at a stretch there, she added.)\par \par \uc2 A few days after a federal judge in Brooklyn {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/28/us/refugees-detained-at-us-airports-prompting-legal-challenges-to-trumps-immigration-order.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 blocked the order}}}\uc2  on Jan. 28, the demand for lawyers began to fade. Travelers were being detained for shorter periods, or not at all, according to members of the group. But the lawyers stayed to assist families and write {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/h/habeas_corpus/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 habeas corpus}}}\uc2  petitions for those detained for more than six hours.\par \par \uc2 While most of the lawyers have now left the airport (a skeleton crew will still mill about the terminals), they are vowing to remain active offsite.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNow we know how to do rapid response, if we need to,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Mackler said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19ll be ready for the next fight.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Here\u8217\'20\'19s what else is happening:\par \par \uc2 Weather\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sYi7uEvEEmk"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 And I know it\u8217\'20\'19s gonna be a lovely day}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A cool one, but a lovely one.\par \par \uc2 We\u8217\'20\'19re looking at a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=40.77657244207131&lon=-73.96940231323242#.WJg8_5LGLD3"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 high of 42}}}\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 with the wind, that could feel as shivery as 25 \u8212\'20\'14 but at least the sun will be smiling in the sky.\par \par \uc2 Soak it up while it lasts; rain and flurries are on their way for much of the rest of the week.\par \par \uc2 In the News\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 New York\u8217\'20\'19s growth can be measured in trash bags. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/06/nyregion/new-yorks-growth-can-be-measured-in-trash-bags.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fnyregion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 New York Times}}}\uc2 ]\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 A 20-year-old Brooklyn man has been charged in the murder of Karina Vetrano, a jogger in Queens, last summer. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/nyregion/queens-jogger-karina-vetrano-suspect-arrest.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fnyregion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 New York Times}}}\uc2 ]\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 New Yorkers on a subway train banded together to scrub away anti-Semitic graffiti. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/nyregion/swastika-nyc-subways.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fnyregion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 New York Times}}}\uc2 ]\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 The lifting of President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s travel ban has set off a rush to reach the United States. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/05/us/trump-refugee-travel-ban-lifted-reunited-families.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fnyregion"}}{\fldrslt{\cf