 is \u8220\'20\'1Chong,\u8221\'20\'1D meaning red, or trendy.\par \par \uc2 In the 13 years I have {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/29/world/asia/29iht-letter.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 reported}}}\uc2  from here, \u8220\'20\'1Cheart science study\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1Cheart science analysis,\u8221\'20\'1D as psychology and psychoanalysis are known in Chinese, have gained enormously in popularity, for perhaps the first time in the country\u8217\'20\'19s history.\par \par \uc2 Thousands of people offer counseling services in person or online, via couch sessions or magazine columns.\par \par \uc2 Rattled by suicides among students, each \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2  has a counseling center.\par \par \uc2 The Ministry of Human Resources and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/s/social_security_us/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Social Security}}}\uc2  has a multilevel accreditation system for those who want to shrink China, though some set up illegally, too.\par \par \uc2 Sure, part of psychology\u8217\'20\'19s popularity is the impact of pop culture from overseas, with American and European movies and TV shows making self-examination, and the language of psychology, seem sophisticated and desirable.\par \par \uc2 And yes, the ordinary dynamics of life and relationships anywhere in the world may be enough to give anyone problems that require counseling. In that way China is like everywhere.\par \par \uc2 But specific to this part of the world is a particular combination of Confucianism and Communism that has made social and political repression very extreme at times.\par \par \uc2 China is ripe for the couch.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s the people\u8217\'20\'19s dictatorship that began in 1949 with the Communist revolution, eventually causing the deaths of tens of millions in political campaigns and in starvation. That {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/28/world/asia/china-cultural-revolution-thomas-plankers.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 pain}}}\uc2  still cannot be freely acknowledged because the party that caused it continues in power and rules with an iron fist.\par \par \uc2 Then there is the regret, even torment, over that most intimate of issues: reproduction. Millions of women were forced to abort \u8220\'20\'1Cout-of-plan\u8221\'20\'1D babies to not transgress the one-child policy that ran from 1979 to 2016.\par \par \uc2 Just this week I spoke to a woman, age 59, who still thinks with longing about the second baby she accidentally conceived 24 years ago, then had to abort, since she already had one child.\par \par \uc2 The list is long, and there are obstacles to figuring this all out, of course.\par \par \uc2 Confucianism decrees that a person\u8217\'20\'19s identity is largely determined by her position in the family and society. Rituals of behavior, or \u8220\'20\'1Cli,\u8221\'20\'1D may severely limit what a person can say or do \u8212\'20\'14 or even feel \u8212\'20\'14 consciously or unconsciously.\par \par \uc2 A Chinese friend who trained as a Freudian analyst recently expressed her frustration at how hard people find it to open up. Psychically pummeled by families and schools that mold children aggressively from birth, many people have no idea who they are or what they want, she said, though they know when things feel wrong.\par \par \uc2 I asked my friend for examples of some of the deep issues she sees among her clients these days.\par \par \uc2 Curiously perhaps for a society that puts so much emphasis on the importance of family, she singled out two problems that seem to spring from familial indifference: the emotionally poor state of many marriages, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/06/world/asia/china-kindergarten-boarding-children.html?_r=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 early separation}}}\uc2  of children from their primary caregivers \u8212\'20\'14 with many children farmed out to boarding schools or relatives to free up the parents for work. She has run group workshops on both.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s also the vexing question of fathers. In the Confucian scheme, which authoritarian Communism closely mirrors, the emperor, or leader, is to the people what the father is to his wife and children: in charge.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CMy father says, \u8216\'20\'18I\u8217\'20\'19m your father so everything I say is right,\u8217\'20\'19 \u8221\'20\'1D said Ms. Dong, adding (unsurprisingly perhaps), \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m not close to my father.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s a lot to deal with, one might say.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/28/world/asia/china-cultural-revolution-thomas-plankers.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Q. and A.: Tomas Pl\u228\'00\'E4nkers on the Psychic Legacy of the Cultural Revolution}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/06/world/asia/china-kindergarten-boarding-children.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Recognizing Boarding Schools\u8217\'20\'19 Psychic Toll in China}}}\par \par \uc2 Rachel Levit \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170206ed26003e9\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
