\par\par \uc2 ScienceTake\par \uc2 Science\par {\*\bkmkstart toc75}{\*\bkmkend toc75}\b \uc2 Of a Frog\u8217\'20\'19s Slap Shot and Saliva\b0\par\par\uc2 By JAMES GORMAN \par \uc2 593 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 You never know when a frog playing an electronic game will lead to an experiment on the physics of saliva.\par \par \uc2 But then, who even knew that frogs could play electronic games?\par \par \uc2 So let\u8217\'20\'19s start with that.\par \par \uc2 Alexis C. Noel, a Ph.D. student in mechanical engineering at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/g/georgia_institute_of_technology/index.html?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Georgia Tech}}}\uc2 , and her supervisor, David L. Hu, were watching a viral \uc2 YouTube{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WlEzvdlYRes"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 video }}}\uc2 in which a frog is attacking the screen of a smartphone running an ant-smashing game. It appears to be winning.\par \par \uc2 They started wondering how \u8212\'20\'14 in reality \u8212\'20\'14 frog tongues stick to insects so quickly when they shoot out to grab them, and decided it was a phenomenon worth studying.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s been an adventure ever since,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Noel said.\par \par \uc2 First, the whole frog tongue slap shot occurs in the blink of an eye, requiring Ms. Noel and her colleagues to shoot high-speed video of a variety of frogs at the Atlanta Botanical Garden and Zoo Atlanta.\par \par \uc2 Then they ran tests on the saliva itself and the frog tissue.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Noel fondly recalled spending hours at night in the lab scraping tongues from dissected frogs donated by a biology class at the \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI needed about a fifth of a teaspoon of saliva,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 With data on the speed of the tongue shot and retraction, the viscosity \u8212\'20\'14 or stickiness \u8212\'20\'14 of the saliva, and the softness of the tongue tissue, they came up with a computer simulation to test their ideas of what was going on.\par \par \uc2 What they found was that frog saliva, which is normally 50,000 times stickier than human saliva, flows freely when it hits an insect.\par \par \uc2 That makes the saliva a non-Newtonian fluid, which means that the speed at which it flows (to be precise, its shear rate) changes how viscous it is.\par \par \uc2 In the case of frog saliva, the faster it is forced to flow, the looser it gets. When the frog tongue hits a cricket, the saliva becomes 100 times less viscous and flows around the cricket into every little crevice.\par \par \uc2 By the time the frog starts to pull its tongue back, in a much smoother and slower motion than the body slam attack, the saliva has gotten thick and sticky again and the tongue has wrapped all around the cricket.\par \par \uc2 There is one more step. The frog has to get the cricket unstuck and into its stomach. What helps here is that frog swallowing involves {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TUbx1tBnpG0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 retracting its }}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TUbx1tBnpG0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  eyeballs}}}\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 so violently that it loosens up the saliva again.\par \par \uc2 The researchers published their findings in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rsif.2016.0764"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Royal Society Interface}}}\uc2 . Dr. Hu said the detailed understanding of how the process worked had obvious applications for the growing field of soft robots made of very flexible materials.\par \par \uc2 Not that they will have tongues, but they may need to grab and release \u8212\'20\'14 who knows what \u8212\'20\'14 with appendages more like tongues than metal claws.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Noel said her research was \u8220\'20\'1Call about how you grab things with very soft surfaces.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 She is also studying {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://phys.org/news/2016-11-cat-tongues-handier.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 cat tongues}}}\uc2 , for instance. They are covered in tiny little curved spikes, like claws, which, oddly enough, are very good at detangling snarls in fur.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/05/science/a-reprieve-for-fungus-battered-frogs.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 A Reprieve for Fungus-Battered Frogs}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/25/science/a-frog-thats-a-living-breathing-pac-man.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 A Frog That\u8217\'20\'19s a Living, Breathing Pac-Man}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/science/frogs-find-themselves-in-a-downward-spiral.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Frogs Find Themselves in a Downward Spiral}}}\par \par \uc2 Frogs are known for shooting out their tongues in a fraction of a second to catch insects to swallow. Now scientists have found how important sticky spit is for hunting success. | By ROBIN LINDSAY and JAMES GORMAN \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170206ed26002jw\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
