\par\par \uc2 Nonfiction\par \uc2 Books; Book Review\par {\*\bkmkstart toc76}{\*\bkmkend toc76}\b \uc2 Lincoln Served Six Ways: Reframing a President\b0\par\par\uc2 By ALICE KESSLER-HARRIS \par \uc2 683 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par 04:00\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 SIX ENCOUNTERS WITH LINCOLN\par \par \uc2 A President Confronts Democracy and Its Demons\par \par \uc2 By Elizabeth Brown Pryor\par \par \uc2 Illustrated. 480 pp. Viking. $35.\par \par \uc2 At a moment when questions about the efficacy of democracy are on everyone\u8217\'20\'19s lips, this book eerily reflects some of today\u8217\'20\'19s key issues. Among them are the military\u8217\'20\'19s part in domestic policy; the protections appropriate to noncitizens (in Lincoln\u8217\'20\'19s case, Native Americans); the limits of female citizenship; the meaning of free speech; and states\u8217\'20\'19 rights to contravene personal liberty.\par \par \uc2 Abraham Lincoln confronted these and other issues during his tenure as president, often choosing between expanding democratic potential and adhering to constitutional mandates. Deploying humor as a weapon, Lincoln emerges from the history books as a benign and democratic figure, ultimately a champion of slave emancipation.\par \par \uc2 A different Lincoln inhabits the pages of \u8220\'20\'1CSix Encounters With Lincoln.\u8221\'20\'1D Here we meet the skilled raconteur whose tales promote vacillation, and whose humor disguises costly indecision and delay. Many of his contemporaries labeled him cowardly and vulgar, an illegitimate ruler and despot. Elizabeth Brown Pryor, the author of two previous Civil War-era biographies, sees him as none of these, and yet she has produced a portrait of a president whose failures to act often undermine the democratic ideals and the moral values to which he claims commitment.\par \par \uc2 Uncertainty manifested itself in a complicated stance, sometimes fostering democracy and at others sticking to the letter of the Constitution. Convinced that states had a right to determine their economic and social priorities, Lincoln debated the use of military force to coerce recalcitrant states to remain in the Union. He wavered only when states\u8217\'20\'19 rights threatened national unity. But once decided, he acted unilaterally to increase the size of the Army without elucidating lines of command. From that followed Lincoln\u8217\'20\'19s dragging his feet on the issue of slave emancipation because he hoped that he could bring the South back into the Union with compromise rather than military victory. The dilemma inherent in using force to ensure liberty emerged most starkly in loyal border states that continued to legitimize slave owning. To ensure their commitment to the Union, Lincoln simply turned a blind eye, dashing the democratic aspirations of thousands of enslaved people.\par \par \uc2 In other instances, Lincoln did not hesitate to curtail constitutional rights in the interests of an initially controversial war. He famously ignored habeas corpus, claiming the right to seize suspicious individuals in wartime, and he attempted to control flows of information: acts that placed him at odds with the principle of safeguarding informed criticism in a democratic society.\par \par \uc2 Nor did Lincoln imagine extending democracy to Native Americans or to women. Pryor tells us that the greatest contradiction he faced was between the ideal of democracy and prevailing negative views of Indians. Like others of his generation, he thought all men were created equal except for Indians and women. He did not hesitate to abrogate Indian treaties, though he sometimes expressed concern for Indian life. He consistently rebuffed or denigrated women\u8217\'20\'19s efforts to participate in wartime activities, rarely acknowledging even their heroic work as nurses.\par \par \uc2 Pryor died in 2015, and so she could have hardly intended this posthumously published book to suggest any parallels between Lincoln\u8217\'20\'19s ambivalent politics and contemporary efforts to limit suffrage, spread fake news and eliminate federal efforts to protect the civil rights of women, African-Americans and the poorest wage earners. Yet the notion that democracy involves compromises resonates today. Lincoln\u8217\'20\'19s dilemmas illuminate how apparently benign federal mandates \u8212\'20\'14 like universal health care, paid maternity leave or federal land acquisition \u8212\'20\'14 that seem on their face to extend democratic possibilities, can be viewed from within state borders as coercive. Fascinating reading on its own terms, \u8220\'20\'1CSix Encounters With Lincoln\u8221\'20\'1D nevertheless confronts readers with startlingly relevant questions.\par \par \uc2 Alice Kessler-Harris, the R. Gordon Hoxie professor emerita of history at \uc2 Columbia \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is editing a book with Maurizio Vaudagna called \u8220\'20\'1CDemocracy and the Welfare State.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 A rare visit to the front: Antietam, 1862. | MPI/Getty Images \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020170206ed26002jq\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
