\par\par \uc2 Business/Financial Desk; SECTB\par {\*\bkmkstart toc80}{\*\bkmkend toc80}\b \uc2 Immigrants Challenge Denial of Student Loans\b0\par\par\uc2 By STACY COWLEY \par \uc2 917 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2017\par \uc2 The New York Times\par \uc2 NYTF\par \uc2 Late Edition - Final\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2017 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Student loan debt is not something most people covet, but for Mitzie Perez, a 25-year-old \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2  student in California, borrowing money to cover her tuition bills would be a boon.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Perez is an undocumented immigrant who was illegally brought to the United States from Guatemala in 1997, when she was 5 years old. She was sheltered from deportation by the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, known as DACA, an Obama-era initiative that grants some protections to those who were brought here as children.\par \par \uc2 But Ms. Perez, a junior majoring in gender and sexuality studies at the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of California, Riverside, has never been able to do something that most college students take for granted: obtain a loan to finance her studies. She sued a lender, \uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2 , that turned her down, claiming that its policy of denying applicants because of their immigration status is illegal.\par \par \uc2 The lawsuit, which seeks class-action status, is one of the first to challenge common industry policies that make it difficult for undocumented students to finance higher education. The case was filed in San Francisco federal court, with the California League of United Latin American Citizens participating as a plaintiff.\par \par \uc2 ''Our position is that banks are supposed to make these kinds of loan decisions based on an assessment of risk,'' said Ossai Miazad, a lawyer who is representing Ms. Perez. ''To put that aside completely and deny people based on their immigration status is discriminatory.''\par \par \uc2 Most student borrowers rely on loans backed by the federal government, but undocumented students are not eligible for federal loans. Those wishing to borrow must turn to private loans, which generally carry fewer protections -- and, often, higher rates -- than federal loans.\par \par \uc2 No laws prohibit lenders from making loans to undocumented borrowers who possess identifying information like a Social Security number, which Ms. Perez has. Still, this is an area where banks tread very lightly.\par \par \uc2 Among five of the nation's largest issuers of private student loans, two -- \uc2 Discover Bank\uc2  and \uc2 Sallie Mae\uc2  -- said they made loans to undocumented students under some circumstances.\par \par \uc2 Discover ''does not differentiate between borrowers based on DACA status, and would loan to such individuals if they were otherwise qualified,'' said Robert Weiss, a company spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Sallie Mae\uc2  will make loans to qualifying students enrolled in DACA if they have a co-signer who is a United States citizen or permanent resident, said Rick Castellano, a company spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Those loans are typically more expensive than federal loans. For undergraduates, the interest rate on federal loans disbursed this year is fixed at 3.76 percent. (The loans also carry an origination fee of around 1 percent.) The rates that Discover and \uc2 Sallie Mae\uc2  offer vary by borrower, but can top 11 percent.\par \par \uc2 At other banks, even high-interest student loans cannot be obtained by undocumented borrowers. \uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2  and \uc2 PNC Bank\uc2  said they required student borrowers to have United States citizenship or permanent resident status. Citizens Bank did not provide details on its policy.\par \par \uc2 ''\uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2  understands the dream of pursuing higher education, and we remain focused on our responsible lending practices to assist temporary and permanent residents and United States citizens in obtaining student financing,'' Jason A. Vasquez, a spokesman for Wells Fargo, said in response to Ms. Perez's lawsuit.\par \par \uc2 Lenders face unique challenges in extending credit to borrowers who are not in the country legally. Students with DACA status can legally work in the United States, but that right could vanish if the program is curtailed or eliminated.\par \par \uc2 Still, many banks, including \uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2 , will issue credit cards to undocumented borrowers. Ms. Perez has several credit cards (from banks other than \uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2 ), and uses them to help pay her tuition -- at a much higher interest rate than a student loan would carry.\par \par \uc2 The fate of the DACA program and the 750,000 young immigrants in it is one of the thorniest immigration issues facing President Trump.\par \par \uc2 Created in 2012 by President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2  through an executive action, the program has allowed hundreds of thousands of people who were brought here as children to obtain jobs, pursue college degrees and live openly in the country where they were raised. Many are worried that they will lose those protections under Mr. Trump, who has moved to upend America's immigration policies.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Perez said she was deeply anxious about the future of the DACA program and how Mr. Trump's actions would affect her and her family. But she also has immediate concerns, like how to pay for her next few months of schooling.\par \par \uc2 For the moment, she works as a community organizer and uses her income and credit card loans to finance her education.\par \par \uc2 ''I'm considering having to drop out or cut back, because I can't make ends meet,'' Ms. Perez said.\par \par \uc2 Thomas A. Saenz\uc2 , the president of the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, which helped Ms. Perez bring her lawsuit, said expanding access to student loans was a critical issue for thousands of people.\par \par \uc2 ''We are hoping that businesses will understand that this type of discrimination is not permissible -- regardless of how folks may erroneously conclude that the rhetoric of the new administration may change things,'' Mr. Saenz said. ''It doesn't change what anti-discrimination laws provide.''\par \par \uc2 Mitzie Perez, an unauthorized immigrant who is suing Wells Fargo, in Los Angeles last week. (PHOTOGRAPH BY RICHARD VOGEL/ASSOCIATED PRESS) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170206ed260003k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw284\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4260\pichgoal600
