uc2 Still, for the most part, overtly political statements were few and far between -- by design. A first-time advertiser, 84 Lumber, had its initial proposal for a commercial rejected by Fox last month for being ''too controversial'' because it showed a Spanish-speaking mother and daughter confronting a border wall between the United States and Mexico. The company edited its spot to remove the wall and directed users to see the end of its commercial online.\par \par \uc2 Budweiser spent days telling the news media that its ad was not a response to President Trump's recent immigration crackdown. The company's commercial featured the journey of one of its founders to the United States from Germany in the 1800s and the discrimination he overcame on his way to success.\par \par \uc2 The hashtag #BoycottBudweiser trended on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  early on Sunday evening, apparently started by people who disliked the ad. But it was then used by others to defend Budweiser and mock the people who were boycotting the ad.\par \par \uc2 Carl Marci\uc2 , chief neuroscientist at Nielsen, the TV ratings company, said, ''If you make people think too much or get too serious during a game where people are really looking to be entertained, you're taking a risk.''\par \par \uc2 That risk can pay off, though.\par \par \uc2 Audi\uc2 's ad went viral before the game, having passed five million views on \uc2 YouTube\uc2  as of Friday. It was narrated by a father asking pointed questions about what to tell his young daughter one day as she competed in a cart race, such as, ''Do I tell her that despite her education, her drive, her skills, her intelligence, she will automatically be valued as less than every man she ever meets?''\par \par \uc2 [Video: \uc2 Audi\uc2  #DriveProgress Big Game Commercial -- ''Daughter'' Watch on \uc2 YouTube\uc2 .]\par \par \uc2 As she won the race, he reflected that perhaps he would be able to ''tell her something different.'' The commercial ended with text including a line saying that \uc2 Audi of America\uc2  is ''committed to equal pay for equal work.''\par \par \uc2 But escapism and sentimentality were the strategy for many advertisers as brands tried to provide an antidote to the weighty issues facing the country this year.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Clean was unexpectedly portrayed as something of a sex symbol. Michelob Ultra used the theme song from ''Cheers'' in its ad, which presented the label as a post-workout beer. Justin Bieber showed off his dance moves for \uc2 T-Mobile\uc2  while Avocados From Mexico jokingly used subliminal messaging to urge more avocado consumption.\par \par \uc2 ''Very often on the Super Bowl, we see emotional advertising, or we see issue-driven advertising,'' said Tim Calkins, a marketing professor at Northwestern \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 's Kellogg School of Management.\par \par \uc2 He added, ''All the controversy in the country is making advertisers nervous about addressing big, significant issues, and in a polarizing time, it is safest to stick to the product and stick to lighthearted humor.''\par \par \uc2 [Video: Mr. Clean | New Super Bowl Ad | Cleaner of Your Dreams Watch on \uc2 YouTube\uc2 .]\par \par \uc2 Advertisers were willing to pay, on average, about $5 million for 30-second spots during the Super Bowl this year -- or around $167,000 per second -- and even more in promotional costs to reach the game's more than 100 million viewers. Many released the full ads or teasers online before Sunday while brands such as Snickers and \uc2 Hyundai\uc2  went the opposite route, producing their commercials during the game itself, which aired on Fox.\par \par \uc2 Some were not impressed by the bulk of the ads that aired on Sunday, particularly given the rising cost of the commercials.\par \par \uc2 ''Comedy, celebrities and anthropomorphic creatures seem to be the go-to schtick,'' said Andrew Essex, the chief executive of Tribeca Enterprises and a former C.E.O. of the creative agency Droga5.\par \par \uc2 ''After 50 years, half a century, it's all feeling a little formulaic,'' he added. ''I find myself, as someone who's not doing this anymore, wondering if this is the single greatest act of economic immolation on the planet.''\par \par \uc2 Others felt that the ads delivered.\par \par \uc2 ''People want to see lighthearted things in the Super Bowl, especially at a time when there are so many big issues in the country,'' Mr. Calkins said.\par \par \uc2 Among the escapist ads to air during Super Bowl LI, Mr. Clean was depicted as something of a sex symbol. (B1); Cam Newton and Miranda Kerr in a comical Buick ad aired during the Super Bowl on Sunday. (B3) \par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170206ed2600033\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
