campus law school, the \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2  is organizing legal help for students detained for deportation.\par \par \uc2 Another worrisome prospect, Ms. Napolitano said, is that students could lose the permits that allow them to work. Undocumented students, including any losing DACA, will continue to pay in-state tuition and be eligible for state financial aid and for a revolving loan program funded, in part, by the \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 ''We want to do everything we can so students are safe on our campuses,'' Ms. Napolitano said, ''so they can focus on what they are there to do, which is to study.''\par \par \uc2 Students at dozens of college campuses, galvanized by Mr. Trump's depictions of immigrants as criminals or potential terrorists, have pressed administrators to provide sanctuary for those without legal papers. But universities have had differing ideas about what that would mean in practice, and most leaders have been careful to say they would not defy the law.\par \par \uc2 Some institutions have flatly rejected sanctuary plans as encouraging lawbreaking. At \uc2 New Mexico State \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the president, \uc2 Garrey Carruthers\uc2 , said that banning federal agents from campus might imperil its federal funding.\par \par \uc2 One of the first presidents to declare a sanctuary campus explicitly was Michael S. Roth of Wesleyan, who announced in November that it ''will not voluntarily assist'' any efforts by federal authorities to deport students (a policy he reaffirmed on Jan. 29). Soon after, John Coatsworth, the provost of \uc2 Columbia \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2 , said that it would not allow immigration agents on campus without a warrant.\par \par \uc2 Some administrators point out that student information, including their immigration status, is already protected under long-existing privacy laws requiring the authorities to show a warrant or court order before any data can be released without students' consent.\par \par \uc2 In Georgia, Emory, which is a private \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2 , considered but ultimately decided against protective measures. ''Emory is not seeking to establish itself as a sanctuary campus, for which there is no legal definition,'' the \b \highlight22\uc2 university\b0 \highlight\uc2  said in a Jan. 4 statement. Taking a tougher line, the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  System of Georgia said that any call for sanctuary was ''unacceptable'' and added, ''We expect our institutions to follow the law.''\par \par \uc2 In his first formal briefing, on Jan. 23, \uc2 Sean Spicer\uc2 , the White House press secretary, suggested that canceling DACA would not be a priority for the new administration, but he did not provide any explicit reassurance that the program would continue.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Napolitano is still contemplating the bitter possibility that Mr. Trump will sweep away her most significant immigration accomplishment. She hopes to persuade him that the program is a good use of executive power, emphasizing that DACA immigrants pose little security risk because they pass background checks to get into the program.\par \par \uc2 Her message for Mr. Trump: ''Why waste resources trying to deport good students who've done everything right?''\par \par \uc2 Correction: February 5, 2017, Sunday\par \par \uc2 This article has been revised to reflect the following correction: An article on Page 20 this weekend about sanctuary campuses for undocumented students refers imprecisely to the institution that said that calls to provide sanctuary were ''unacceptable.'' It is the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  System of Georgia -- not \uc2 the \b \highlight22\uc2 University\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Georgia\uc2 , which is one campus within the system.\par \par \uc2 Document NYTF000020170205ed2500083\par }\page {\par\fs